{"title_page": "List of Indian independence activists", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n{{expand list|date=January 2015}}\nThis is a list of individuals who [[political campaign|campaign]]ed against or are considered to have campaigned against colonial rule on the [[Indian sub-continent]].\n\nThe [[Indian independence movement]] consisted of efforts by individuals and organizations from a wide spectrum of philosophies to obtain political independence from British, French and Portuguese rule through the use of a variety of methods.\n\nPost-Independence, \"Freedom fighter\" is an officially recognised category by the [[Government of India|Indian government]] covering those who took part in the movement; people in this category (can also include dependant family members)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/pension-of-freedom-fighters-hiked-by-rs-5000/article9003109.ece|title=Pension of freedom fighters hiked by Rs 5,000|last=PTI|date=2016-08-18|newspaper=The Hindu Business Line|access-date=2017-02-23|language=en}}</ref> get pensions and other benefits like special railway counters.<ref name=\"Mitchell2009\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fBchTO0NS0EC&pg=PA193|title=Language, Emotion, and Politics in South India: The Making of a Mother Tongue|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2009|isbn=0-253-35301-7|page=193|author=Lisa Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n==List of Indian freedom fighters==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Birth !! Death !! Activity\n|-\n||[[Maveeran Alagumuthu Kone|Maveeran]] [[Maveeran Alagumuthu Kone|alagumuthu]] [[Maveeran Alagumuthu Kone|kone]] ||1728 ||1759 ||Defeated by the British and [[haliyal]]'s forces and executed in 1759.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Puli Thevar|Puli]] [[Puli Thevar|thevar]] || 1715 ||1767\n|Ruled [[Nerkattumseval]] and fought and defeated the British and [[Nawab of Arcot]] in 1755.<ref name=Kumar2017>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XJ8rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=thevar+army&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjspYO2tPbkAhVrQUEAHcu-D50Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=thevar%20army&f=false|title=Thamizh Is Not Just A Language: The Valour|last=Kumar|first=Madhan|date=2017|publisher=Educreation Publishing|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5mtkAAAAMAAJ&q=puli+thevar+1755&dq=puli+thevar+1755&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjnuf2SvfbkAhXJOcAKHaACCeU4ChDoAQgnMAA|title=The role of Tamil poets in freedom struggle|last=Gomathinayagam|first=Piramanayagam|date=1989|publisher=Mukil Pathippagam|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n||[[Velu Nachiyar]] \n||1730 ||1796 ||She was the first queen to fight against the British colonial power in India.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Jayi Rajaguru]]||1739||1806|| He was a prominent figure of the Indian independence movement in the state of Odisha.\n|-\n||[[Maruthu Pandiyar]]\n||1748 ||1801 ||Maruthu Brothers are good in aerodynamics and invented many variants of spears and Valari.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Pazhassi Raja]]\n||1753 ||1805 ||Used guerrilla warfare to fight British in [[Cotiote War]] (Kottayathu war) across a span of thirteen years from 1793 to 1806 to preserve the independence and unity of his kingdom and was killed in 1805 in a gun-fight at Mavila Thodu in the present-day Kerala-Karnataka border.\n|-\n|[[Dheeran Chinnamalai]]\n||1756 ||1805 ||Chinnamalai engaged in guerrilla warfare and defeated the British in battles at Cauvery in 1801, Odanilai in 1802 and Arachalur in 1804. Dheeran Chinnamalai Gounder was betrayed by his cook Nallapan and was captured by the British sepoys in 1805. He was hanged at Sankagiri Fort along with his two brothers on 31 July 1805 on the day of Aadi Perukku.\n|-\n||[[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]]\n||1760 ||1799 ||He refused to accept the sovereignty of the British East India Company and the British waged a war against them.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Kittur Chennamma|Kittur chennamma]]||1778 || 1829||Was an Indian freedom fighter and [[Rani]] of the [[Kittur]], a former princely state in [[Karnataka]]. She led an armed force against the [[British East India Company]] in 1824 in defiance of the [[doctrine of lapse]] in an attempt to maintain Indian control over the region, but was defeated in the third war and died imprisoned. \n|-\n| [[Titumir]]\n| 1782\n| 1831\n| Was a freedom fighter who led a campaign against the British-rule in India, during the 19th century. He eventually built a bamboo fort (Basher Kella in Bengali) in Narikelberia village, which passed into Bengali folk legend. After the storming of the fort by British soldiers, Titumir died of his wounds on 19 November 1831.\n|-\n|[[Sangolli Rayanna|Sangoli rayanna]]||1798 || 1831||Was an [[India|Indian]] military chief [[warrior]] from [[Karnataka]]. He was the [[army]] chief of the [[Monarchy|Kingdom]] of [[Kittur]] ruled at the time by [[Rani Chennamma]] and fought the [[British East India Company]] till his death.\n|-\n| [[Uyyalawada Narasimha Reddy]] || 1805 ||1847 ||In 1846, he led an uprising in [[Andhra Pradesh]]. He was executed by the British by hanging.<ref name=Ramachandran2008>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6Q7EiZmcMPMC&pg=PA121&dq=Uyyalawada+Narasimha+Reddy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibzYqvtfbkAhXPEcAKHcMzChsQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=Uyyalawada%20Narasimha%20Reddy&f=false|title=Empire's First Soldiers|last=Ramachandran|first=D. P.|date=2008|publisher=[[Lancer Publishers & Distributors|Lancer Publishers]]|year=|isbn=9780979617478|location=|pages=121|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ahmadullah Shah]] || 1787 ||1857 || Leader of various battles for freedom like [[Battle of Chinhat]], [[Siege of Lucknow]], [[Capture of Lucknow]], [[Chapati Movement]].\n|-\n|  [[Mangal Pandey]]  || 1827 || 1857 ||Early martyr of Indian rebellion. Pandey was a soldier of the British Indian army, but rebelled against it. He was executed on 8 April 1857 in Barrackpore.\n|-\n| [[V. O. Chidambaram Pillai]] || 1872 ||1936 || He launched the first indigenous Indian shipping service between Tuticorin and Colombo with the [[Swadeshi Steam Navigation Company]], competing against British ships.\n|-\n|[[Vallabhbhai Patel]]\n|1875\n|1950\n|Founding father of Republic of India who played leading role in the country's struggle towards independence and integration of united India.\n|-\n|[[B. R. Ambedkar]]\n|1891\n|1956\n|Founding father of Republic of India and the architect of the [[Indian Constitution]] who played role in the country's struggle towards independence.\n|-\n| [[Subramania Bharati]] || 1882 ||1921 || Wrote many fiery songs kindling patriotism and nationalism during Indian independence. \n|-\n| [[Alluri Sitarama Raju]] || 1897 || 1924 || Leader of the [[Rampa Rebellion of 1922]].\n|-\n| [[Inayatullah Khan Mashriqi]] || 1888 ||1963 || Founder of the Khaksar Movement in British India\n|-\n| [[Bhagat Singh]] || 1907 || 1931 || Worked with several revolutionary organisations and became prominent in the Hindustan Republican Association (HRA).\n|-\n| [[Aruna Asaf Ali]] || 1909 || 1996 || She is widely remembered for hoisting the [[Indian National Congress]] flag at the Gowalia Tank maidan in [[Mumbai|Bombay]] during the [[Quit India Movement]], 1942. \n|-\n| [[Shambhu Dutt Sharma]] || 1918|| 2016 || Joined [[Quit India Movement]] in 1942. Hon. General Secretary of GSB (Gandhian Satyagraha Brigade). Founder of Transparency International India. Sharma's team was known as Gandhian Seva Brigade. \n|-\n| [[Tanguturi Prakasam]] || 1872|| 1957 || Pantulu was an Indian politician and freedom fighter, chief minister of the Madras Presidency, and subsequently became the first chief minister of the new Andhra state, created by the partition of Madras State along linguistic lines. He was also known as Andhra Kesari (Lion of Andhra). The Andhra Pradesh government declared his birth anniversary a state festival.\n|-\n| [[Khudiram Bose]] || 1889 || 1908 || Bose planted bombs near British government officials and police stations. Due to his activities against the British, he was arrested and hanged. At the time of his hanging, he was 18 years, 8 months 8 days old, making him one of the youngest revolutionaries in India.\n|-\n| [[Chandra Shekhar Azad]] || 1906 || 1931 || Azad (\"The Free\"), was an Indian revolutionary who reorganised the Hindustan Republican Association under its new name of Hindustan Socialist Republican Association (HSRA) after the death of its founder, Ram Prasad Bismil, and three other prominent party leaders, Roshan Singh, Rajendra Nath Lahiri and Ashfaqulla Khan.\n|-\n| [[Chittaranjan Das]] || 1869 || 1925 || Das founded the [[Swaraj]] party in [[Bengal]], became leader in [[Non-cooperation Movement]] in [[Bengal]].\n|-\n| [[Komaram Bheem]] || 1901 || 1940|| Bheem was a tribal leader who fought for the liberation of Hyderabad. \n|-\n| [[Ram Prasad Bismil]] || 1897 || 1927 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Udham Singh]] || 1899 || 1940 || Shooting in Caxton Hall.\n|-\n| [[Hemu Kalani]] || 1923 || 1943 || Sabotage of railway track.\n|-\n| [[Ashfaqulla Khan]] ||1900 || 1927 ||[[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Sachindra Bakshi]] || 1904 || 1984 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Manmath Nath Gupta]] ||1908 || 2000 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Vasudev Balwant Phadke]] || 1845 || 1883 || Deccan Rebellion\n|-\n| [[Matangini Hazra]] || 1870 || 1942 || Active member of [[Quit India Movement]], shot dead by British at the age of 71.\n|-\n| [[Anant Laxman Kanhere]] || 1891 || 1910 || Shooting of British officer Jackson.\n|-\n| [[Vanchinathan]] || 1886 || 1911 || Shooting of British Collector/District Magistrate [[Robert William Escourt Ashe]].\n|-\n| [[Krishnaji Gopal Karve]] || 1887 || 1910 || Shooting of British officer Jackson.\n|-\n\n| [[Bagha Jatin]] || 1879 || 1915 || The Howrah-Sibpur conspiracy case, [[Indo-German Conspiracy]].\n|-\n| [[Batukeshwar Dutt]] || 1910 || 1965 || [[Revolutionary movement for Indian independence#Central Assembly Bomb Case .281929.29|Central Assembly Bomb Case 1929]].\n|-\n| [[Sukhdev Thapar]] || 1907 || 1931 || [[Revolutionary movement for Indian independence#Central Assembly Bomb Case|Central Assembly Bomb Case 1929]]\n|-\n| [[Shivaram Rajguru]] || 1908 || 1931 || Associate of Bhagat Singh and Sukhdev Thapar in [[Hindustan Socialist Republican Association]]. Murder of a British police officer J. P. Saunders.\n|-\n| [[Roshan Singh]] || 1892 || 1927 || [[Kakori conspiracy]], Bamrauli Action\n|-\n|[[Prabhavati Devi]] ||1906   || 1973 || Gandhian leader. Wife of Jayaprakash Narayan.\n|-\n| [[Pritilata Waddedar]] || 1911 || 1932 || Pahartali European Club attack\n|-\n| [[Jatindra Nath Das]] || 1904 || 1929 || Hunger strike and Lahore conspiracy case\n|-\n| [[Durgawati Devi]]|| 1907 || 1999 || Running the bomb factory.\n|-\n| [[Bhagwati Charan Vohra]] || 1904 || 1930 || ''Philosophy of the Bomb''\n|-\n| [[Madan Lal Dhingra]] || 1883 || 1909 || Assassination of [[Curzon Wyllie]].\n|-\n| [[Alluri Sitarama Raju]] || 1897 || 1924 ||[[Alluri Sitarama Raju#Rampa Rebellion of 1922|Rampa Rebellion of 1922]]\n|-\n| [[Kushal Konwar]] || 1905 || 1943 || Train sabotage at Sarupathar.\n|-\n| [[Surya Sen]] || 1894 || 1934 || President of [[Indian National Congress]] [[Chittagong]] Branch, mastermind of [[Chittagong armoury raid]].\n|-\n| [[Ananta Singh]] || 1903 || 1979 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Ganesh Ghosh]] || 1900 || 1994 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Sri Aurobindo]] || 1872 || 1950 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Rash Behari Bose]] ||1886 || 1945 || [[Rash Behari Bose#Indian National Army|Indian National Army]]\n|-\n| [[Ubaidullah Sindhi]] || 1872 || 1944 || [[Silk Letter Conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Lokenath Bal]] || 1908 || 1964 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Jogesh Chandra Chatterjee]] || 1895 || 1969 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Baikuntha Shukla]] || 1907 || 1934 || Assassination of Phanindra Nath Ghosh, a British government approver.\n|-\n| [[Ambika Chakrabarty]] || 1892 || 1962 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Badal Gupta]] || 1912 || 1930 || [[Badal Gupta#The battle at Writers.27 Building|Attack at Writers Building]]\n|-\n| [[Dinesh Gupta]] ||1911 || 1931 || [[Badal Gupta#The battle at Writers.27 Building|Attack at Writers Building]]\n|-\n| [[Benoy Basu]] || 1908 || 1930 || [[Badal Gupta#The battle at Writers.27 Building|Attack at Writers Building]]\n|-\n| [[Rajendra Lahiri]] || 1901 || 1927 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Barindra Kumar Ghosh]] || 1880 || 1959 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Prafulla Chaki]] || 1888 || 1908 || The Muzaffarpur killing.\n|-\n| [[Ullaskar Dutta]] || 1885 || 1965 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Bhupendra Kumar Datta]] || 1892 || 1979 || Member of [[Anushilan Samiti]].\n|-\n| [[Ramesh Chandra Jha]] || 1925 || 1994 || Sugauli police station robbery.\n|-\n| [[Hemchandra Kanungo]] || 1871 || 1951 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Surendranath Tagore]] || 1872 || 1940 || Involved in the [[Swadeshi]] movement in [[Bengal]], in opposition to the 1905 partition of Bengal.\n|-\n| [[Basawon Singh (Sinha)]]|| 1909 || 1989 || Lahore conspiracy case\n|-\n| [[Bhavabhushan Mitra]] || 1881 || 1970 || [[Ghadar Mutiny]]\n|-\n| [[Bina Das]] || 1911 || 1986 || Attempted to assassinate the Bengal Governor [[Stanley Jackson]].\n|-\n| [[Kalpana Datta]] || 1913 || 1995 || Indian Independence Movement, also part of the [[Chittagong armoury raid]] planning.\n|-\n| [[Kartar Singh Sarabha]] || 1896 || 1915 || Most famous accused in the Lahore conspiracy trial.\n|-\n| [[Shyamji Krishna Varma]] || 1857 || 1930 || Founded the Indian Home Rule Society, [[India House]] and \"The Indian Sociologist\" in London.\n|-\n| [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] || 1897 || ? || Founded the [[Indian Legion]] and revamped the [[Indian National Army]].\n|-\n| [[Binod Bihari Chowdhury]] || 1911 || 2013 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Bhupendranath Datta]] || 1880 || 1961 || [[Indo-German Conspiracy]], member of [[Anushilan Samiti]].\n|-\n| [[Amarendranath Chatterjee]] || 1880 || 1957 || [[Indo-German Conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Atulkrishna Ghosh]] || 1890 || 1966 || [[Indo-German Conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Subodh Roy]] || 1916 || 2006 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]], [[Tebhaga movement]]\n|-\n| [[Maulvi Liaquat Ali]] || 1812 || 1892 || Captured Khusro Bagh in Allahabad and declared \"independence\" of India.\n|- \n| [[Asaf Ali]] || 1888 || 1953 || Indian national movement\n|- \n| [[Rani of Jhansi]] || 19 November 1828, Varanasi || 18 June 1858, Gwalior || Rani Laxmi Bhai was one of the leading figures of the Indian Rebellion of 1857 and became a symbol of resistance to the British Raj for Indian nationalists.\n|-\n| [[Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi]] || 1869 || 1948 || Father of the Nation, he was the preeminent leader of the Indian independence movement in British-ruled India. Employing non-violent civil disobedience, Gandhi led India to independence and inspired movements for civil rights and freedom across the world.\n|-\n| [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]] || 1875 || 1950 ||  popularly known as Sardar Patel, was an Indian politician. He served as the first Deputy Prime Minister of India. He was an Indian barrister, a senior leader of the Indian National Congress and a founding father of the Republic of India who played a leading role in the country's struggle for independence and guided its integration into a united, independent nation.\n|-\n| [[Jawahar Lal Nehru]] || 1889 || 1964 || Founding father of India, an Indian independence activist, and subsequently, the first Prime Minister of India and a central figure in Indian politics before and after Independence.\n|-\n| [[S. Satyamurti]] || 1887 || 1943 || Mayor of Madras, President of the Madras District Congress Party Committee, Advocate of the High Court of Madras, Senior Advocate of the Federal Court of India, Deputy leader of the Congress party, Member of the Indian Legislative Assembly.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 March 1943 |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1943/03/28/83911189.html?pageNumber=24 |title=S, SATYAMURTI; Indian Political Leader, 56, Long Active in Civil Disobedience |newspaper=The New York Times}} {{Subscription required}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Shaukat Ali (politician)|Shaukat Ali]] || 1873 || 1938 || Maulana, \"Shaukat Ali\", his brother \"Mohammad Ali\" and their mother \"Bi Amman\", played an incredible role in the freedom movement of India against the British Imperialism. These brave freedom fighters were unmitigated champions of Hindu-Muslim unity who endorsed the Hindus and the Muslims to fight together in the struggle for independence from the British forgetting their religious feelings and thinking only they are Indians, they were the ambassadors of Hindu-Muslim Unity. They were arrested and imprisoned from 1921 to 1923 for his support to Mahatma Gandhi and the Indian National Congress during the Non-Cooperation Movement (1919\u20131922).<ref>[http://www.royalbook.com.pk/bookpage.aspx?TID=95 Brief History of Shaukat Ali],[http://storyofpakistan.com/maulana-shaukat-ali], [http://indianprofiles.blogspot.in/2007/04/maulana-shaukat-ali.html]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sushila Chain Trehan]] || 1923 || 2011 || Leading member of Arya Samaj who fought for women's rights.\n|-\n| [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] || 1856 || 1920 || Tilak was one of the first and strongest advocates of [[Swaraj]] (\"self-rule\") and a strong radical in Indian consciousness.\n|-\n| [[Bipin Chandra Pal]] || 1858 || 1932 || Member of [[Swaraj]] \n|-\n| [[Lala Lajpat Rai]] || 1865 || 1928 || Member of [[Swaraj]] \n|-\n| [[Alekh Patra]] || 1923 || 1999 || Member of [[Congress]], [[sarvodaya]], who participated in the freedom movement at the age of about 18. \n|-\n| [[Accamma Cherian]] || 1909 || 1982 || popularly known as the Jhansi Rani of Travancore. \n|-\n| [[Rosamma Punnoose]] || 1913 || 2013 || Indian independence activist, politician and lawyer. \n|-\n| [[Annie Mascarene]] || 1902 || 1963 || [[Indian freedom fighter]] and [[Member of Parliament]] from [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]]. \n|-\n| [[Titusji]] || 1905 || 1980 || one of the 78 marchers selected by [[Mahatma Gandhi]] to take part in the 1930 [[Dandi March]]. \n|-\n| [[George Joseph (Kerala)]] || 1887 || 1938 || '''George Joseph''' was a [[lawyer]] and [[Indian independence activist]]. One of the earliest and among the most prominent [[Syrian Christians of Kerala|Syrian Christians from Kerala]] to join the freedom struggle. \n|-\n| [[T. V. Thomas]] || 1910 || 1977 || He was one of the first generation trade union leaders in Kerala and was actively involved in the [[Indian independence movement]].\n|-\n| [[Madhusudan Das]] || 1848 || 1934 || A well-known leader from the Christian community in Odisha, popularly known as \"Utkal Gourab\". He was the first graduate and advocate of Odisha.\n|-\n| [[Kali Charan Banerjee]] || 1847 || 1907 || He being a fine orator and representative of Bengali Christian community, he joined the Indian National Congress(Congress) in 1885, and regularly addressed the Congress annual sessions in moulding the policy of national movement.\n|-\n| [[Vinayak Damodar Savarkar]] || 28 May 1883 || 26 February 1966 || He was an Indian independence activist.\n|-\n|}\nBABU  KUNWAR   1777            1858       HE WAS A \n\nSINGH                                                             MILITARY \n\nCOMMANDER \n\nOF 1857 REVOLT\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n# [https://www.jaborejob.com/freedom-fighters-in-india/ Freedom Fighters of India: Backbone of Our Independence]\n# [https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-history/modern-history/freedom-fighters.html Indian Freedom Fighters - List & Brief Bio of Freedom Activists]<br />\n{{Portal|India}}\n\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Independence Activists}}\n[[Category:Lists of Indian people]]\n[[Category:India history-related lists]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of activists]]\n[[Category:British India-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n{{expand list|date=January 2015}}\nThis is a list of individuals who [[political campaign|campaign]]ed against or are considered to have campaigned against colonial rule on the [[Indian sub-continent]].\n\nThe [[Indian independence movement]] consisted of efforts by individuals and organizations from a wide spectrum of philosophies to obtain political independence from British, French and Portuguese rule through the use of a variety of methods.\n\nPost-Independence, \"Freedom fighter\" is an officially recognised category by the [[Government of India|Indian government]] covering those who took part in the movement; people in this category (can also include dependant family members)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/pension-of-freedom-fighters-hiked-by-rs-5000/article9003109.ece|title=Pension of freedom fighters hiked by Rs 5,000|last=PTI|date=2016-08-18|newspaper=The Hindu Business Line|access-date=2017-02-23|language=en}}</ref> get pensions and other benefits like special railway counters.<ref name=\"Mitchell2009\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fBchTO0NS0EC&pg=PA193|title=Language, Emotion, and Politics in South India: The Making of a Mother Tongue|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2009|isbn=0-253-35301-7|page=193|author=Lisa Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n==List of Indian freedom fighters==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Birth !! Death !! Activity\n|-\n||[[Maveeran Alagumuthu Kone|Maveeran]] [[Maveeran Alagumuthu Kone|alagumuthu]] [[Maveeran Alagumuthu Kone|kone]] ||1728 ||1759 ||Defeated by the British and [[haliyal]]'s forces and executed in 1759.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Puli Thevar|Puli]] [[Puli Thevar|thevar]] || 1715 ||1767\n|Ruled [[Nerkattumseval]] and fought and defeated the British and [[Nawab of Arcot]] in 1755.<ref name=Kumar2017>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XJ8rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=thevar+army&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjspYO2tPbkAhVrQUEAHcu-D50Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=thevar%20army&f=false|title=Thamizh Is Not Just A Language: The Valour|last=Kumar|first=Madhan|date=2017|publisher=Educreation Publishing|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5mtkAAAAMAAJ&q=puli+thevar+1755&dq=puli+thevar+1755&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjnuf2SvfbkAhXJOcAKHaACCeU4ChDoAQgnMAA|title=The role of Tamil poets in freedom struggle|last=Gomathinayagam|first=Piramanayagam|date=1989|publisher=Mukil Pathippagam|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n||[[Velu Nachiyar]] \n||1730 ||1796 ||She was the first queen to fight against the British colonial power in India.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Jayi Rajaguru]]||1739||1806|| He was a prominent figure of the Indian independence movement in the state of Odisha.\n|-\n||[[Maruthu Pandiyar]]\n||1748 ||1801 ||Maruthu Brothers are good in aerodynamics and invented many variants of spears and Valari.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Pazhassi Raja]]\n||1753 ||1805 ||Used guerrilla warfare to fight British in [[Cotiote War]] (Kottayathu war) across a span of thirteen years from 1793 to 1806 to preserve the independence and unity of his kingdom and was killed in 1805 in a gun-fight at Mavila Thodu in the present-day Kerala-Karnataka border.\n|-\n|[[Dheeran Chinnamalai]]\n||1756 ||1805 ||Chinnamalai engaged in guerrilla warfare and defeated the British in battles at Cauvery in 1801, Odanilai in 1802 and Arachalur in 1804. Dheeran Chinnamalai Gounder was betrayed by his cook Nallapan and was captured by the British sepoys in 1805. He was hanged at Sankagiri Fort along with his two brothers on 31 July 1805 on the day of Aadi Perukku.\n|-\n||[[Veerapandiya Kattabomman]]\n||1760 ||1799 ||He refused to accept the sovereignty of the British East India Company and the British waged a war against them.<ref name=\"Kumar2017\"/>\n|-\n|[[Kittur Chennamma|Kittur chennamma]]||1778 || 1829||Was an Indian freedom fighter and [[Rani]] of the [[Kittur]], a former princely state in [[Karnataka]]. She led an armed force against the [[British East India Company]] in 1824 in defiance of the [[doctrine of lapse]] in an attempt to maintain Indian control over the region, but was defeated in the third war and died imprisoned. \n|-\n| [[Titumir]]\n| 1782\n| 1831\n| Was a freedom fighter who led a campaign against the British-rule in India, during the 19th century. He eventually built a bamboo fort (Basher Kella in Bengali) in Narikelberia village, which passed into Bengali folk legend. After the storming of the fort by British soldiers, Titumir died of his wounds on 19 November 1831.\n|-\n|[[Sangolli Rayanna|Sangoli rayanna]]||1798 || 1831||Was an [[India|Indian]] military chief [[warrior]] from [[Karnataka]]. He was the [[army]] chief of the [[Monarchy|Kingdom]] of [[Kittur]] ruled at the time by [[Rani Chennamma]] and fought the [[British East India Company]] till his death.\n|-\n| [[Uyyalawada Narasimha Reddy]] || 1805 ||1847 ||In 1846, he led an uprising in [[Andhra Pradesh]]. He was executed by the British by hanging.<ref name=Ramachandran2008>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6Q7EiZmcMPMC&pg=PA121&dq=Uyyalawada+Narasimha+Reddy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibzYqvtfbkAhXPEcAKHcMzChsQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=Uyyalawada%20Narasimha%20Reddy&f=false|title=Empire's First Soldiers|last=Ramachandran|first=D. P.|date=2008|publisher=[[Lancer Publishers & Distributors|Lancer Publishers]]|year=|isbn=9780979617478|location=|pages=121|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ahmadullah Shah]] || 1787 ||1857 || Leader of various battles for freedom like [[Battle of Chinhat]], [[Siege of Lucknow]], [[Capture of Lucknow]], [[Chapati Movement]].\n|-\n|  [[Mangal Pandey]]  || 1827 || 1857 ||Early martyr of Indian rebellion. Pandey was a soldier of the British Indian army, but rebelled against it. He was executed on 8 April 1857 in Barrackpore.\n|-\n| [[V. O. Chidambaram Pillai]] || 1872 ||1936 || He launched the first indigenous Indian shipping service between Tuticorin and Colombo with the [[Swadeshi Steam Navigation Company]], competing against British ships.\n|-\n|[[Vallabhbhai Patel]]\n|1875\n|1950\n|Founding father of Republic of India who played leading role in the country's struggle towards independence and integration of united India.\n|-\n|[[B. R. Ambedkar]]\n|1891\n|1956\n|Founding father of Republic of India and the architect of the [[Indian Constitution]] who played role in the country's struggle towards independence.\n|-\n| [[Subramania Bharati]] || 1882 ||1921 || Wrote many fiery songs kindling patriotism and nationalism during Indian independence. \n|-\n| [[Alluri Sitarama Raju]] || 1897 || 1924 || Leader of the [[Rampa Rebellion of 1922]].\n|-\n| [[Inayatullah Khan Mashriqi]] || 1888 ||1963 || Founder of the Khaksar Movement in British India\n|-\n| [[Bhagat Singh]] || 1907 || 1931 || Worked with several revolutionary organisations and became prominent in the Hindustan Republican Association (HRA).\n|-\n| [[Aruna Asaf Ali]] || 1909 || 1996 || She is widely remembered for hoisting the [[Indian National Congress]] flag at the Gowalia Tank maidan in [[Mumbai|Bombay]] during the [[Quit India Movement]], 1942. \n|-\n| [[Shambhu Dutt Sharma]] || 1918|| 2016 || Joined [[Quit India Movement]] in 1942. Hon. General Secretary of GSB (Gandhian Satyagraha Brigade). Founder of Transparency International India. Sharma's team was known as Gandhian Seva Brigade. \n|-\n| [[Tanguturi Prakasam]] || 1872|| 1957 || Pantulu was an Indian politician and freedom fighter, chief minister of the Madras Presidency, and subsequently became the first chief minister of the new Andhra state, created by the partition of Madras State along linguistic lines. He was also known as Andhra Kesari (Lion of Andhra). The Andhra Pradesh government declared his birth anniversary a state festival.\n|-\n| [[Khudiram Bose]] || 1889 || 1908 || Bose planted bombs near British government officials and police stations. Due to his activities against the British, he was arrested and hanged. At the time of his hanging, he was 18 years, 8 months 8 days old, making him one of the youngest revolutionaries in India.\n|-\n| [[Chandra Shekhar Azad]] || 1906 || 1931 || Azad (\"The Free\"), was an Indian revolutionary who reorganised the Hindustan Republican Association under its new name of Hindustan Socialist Republican Association (HSRA) after the death of its founder, Ram Prasad Bismil, and three other prominent party leaders, Roshan Singh, Rajendra Nath Lahiri and Ashfaqulla Khan.\n|-\n| [[Chittaranjan Das]] || 1869 || 1925 || Das founded the [[Swaraj]] party in [[Bengal]], became leader in [[Non-cooperation Movement]] in [[Bengal]].\n|-\n| [[Komaram Bheem]] || 1901 || 1940|| Bheem was a tribal leader who fought for the liberation of Hyderabad. \n|-\n| [[Ram Prasad Bismil]] || 1897 || 1927 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Udham Singh]] || 1899 || 1940 || Shooting in Caxton Hall.\n|-\n| [[Hemu Kalani]] || 1923 || 1943 || Sabotage of railway track.\n|-\n| [[Ashfaqulla Khan]] ||1900 || 1927 ||[[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Sachindra Bakshi]] || 1904 || 1984 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Manmath Nath Gupta]] ||1908 || 2000 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Vasudev Balwant Phadke]] || 1845 || 1883 || Deccan Rebellion\n|-\n| [[Matangini Hazra]] || 1870 || 1942 || Active member of [[Quit India Movement]], shot dead by British at the age of 71.\n|-\n| [[Anant Laxman Kanhere]] || 1891 || 1910 || Shooting of British officer Jackson.\n|-\n| [[Vanchinathan]] || 1886 || 1911 || Shooting of British Collector/District Magistrate [[Robert William Escourt Ashe]].\n|-\n| [[Krishnaji Gopal Karve]] || 1887 || 1910 || Shooting of British officer Jackson.\n|-\n\n| [[Bagha Jatin]] || 1879 || 1915 || The Howrah-Sibpur conspiracy case, [[Indo-German Conspiracy]].\n|-\n| [[Batukeshwar Dutt]] || 1910 || 1965 || [[Revolutionary movement for Indian independence#Central Assembly Bomb Case .281929.29|Central Assembly Bomb Case 1929]].\n|-\n| [[Sukhdev Thapar]] || 1907 || 1931 || [[Revolutionary movement for Indian independence#Central Assembly Bomb Case|Central Assembly Bomb Case 1929]]\n|-\n| [[Shivaram Rajguru]] || 1908 || 1931 || Associate of Bhagat Singh and Sukhdev Thapar in [[Hindustan Socialist Republican Association]]. Murder of a British police officer J. P. Saunders.\n|-\n| [[Roshan Singh]] || 1892 || 1927 || [[Kakori conspiracy]], Bamrauli Action\n|-\n|[[Prabhavati Devi]] ||1906   || 1973 || Gandhian leader. Wife of Jayaprakash Narayan.\n|-\n| [[Pritilata Waddedar]] || 1911 || 1932 || Pahartali European Club attack\n|-\n| [[Jatindra Nath Das]] || 1904 || 1929 || Hunger strike and Lahore conspiracy case\n|-\n| [[Durgawati Devi]]|| 1907 || 1999 || Running the bomb factory.\n|-\n| [[Bhagwati Charan Vohra]] || 1904 || 1930 || ''Philosophy of the Bomb''\n|-\n| [[Madan Lal Dhingra]] || 1883 || 1909 || Assassination of [[Curzon Wyllie]].\n|-\n| [[Alluri Sitarama Raju]] || 1897 || 1924 ||[[Alluri Sitarama Raju#Rampa Rebellion of 1922|Rampa Rebellion of 1922]]\n|-\n| [[Kushal Konwar]] || 1905 || 1943 || Train sabotage at Sarupathar.\n|-\n| [[Surya Sen]] || 1894 || 1934 || President of [[Indian National Congress]] [[Chittagong]] Branch, mastermind of [[Chittagong armoury raid]].\n|-\n| [[Ananta Singh]] || 1903 || 1979 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Ganesh Ghosh]] || 1900 || 1994 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Sri Aurobindo]] || 1872 || 1950 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Rash Behari Bose]] ||1886 || 1945 || [[Rash Behari Bose#Indian National Army|Indian National Army]]\n|-\n| [[Ubaidullah Sindhi]] || 1872 || 1944 || [[Silk Letter Conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Lokenath Bal]] || 1908 || 1964 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Jogesh Chandra Chatterjee]] || 1895 || 1969 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Baikuntha Shukla]] || 1907 || 1934 || Assassination of Phanindra Nath Ghosh, a British government approver.\n|-\n| [[Ambika Chakrabarty]] || 1892 || 1962 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Badal Gupta]] || 1912 || 1930 || [[Badal Gupta#The battle at Writers.27 Building|Attack at Writers Building]]\n|-\n| [[Dinesh Gupta]] ||1911 || 1931 || [[Badal Gupta#The battle at Writers.27 Building|Attack at Writers Building]]\n|-\n| [[Benoy Basu]] || 1908 || 1930 || [[Badal Gupta#The battle at Writers.27 Building|Attack at Writers Building]]\n|-\n| [[Rajendra Lahiri]] || 1901 || 1927 || [[Kakori conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Barindra Kumar Ghosh]] || 1880 || 1959 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Prafulla Chaki]] || 1888 || 1908 || The Muzaffarpur killing.\n|-\n| [[Ullaskar Dutta]] || 1885 || 1965 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Bhupendra Kumar Datta]] || 1892 || 1979 || Member of [[Anushilan Samiti]].\n|-\n| [[Ramesh Chandra Jha]] || 1925 || 1994 || Sugauli police station robbery.\n|-\n| [[Hemchandra Kanungo]] || 1871 || 1951 || [[Alipore bomb case]]\n|-\n| [[Surendranath Tagore]] || 1872 || 1940 || Involved in the [[Swadeshi]] movement in [[Bengal]], in opposition to the 1905 partition of Bengal.\n|-\n| [[Basawon Singh (Sinha)]]|| 1909 || 1989 || Lahore conspiracy case\n|-\n| [[Bhavabhushan Mitra]] || 1881 || 1970 || [[Ghadar Mutiny]]\n|-\n| [[Bina Das]] || 1911 || 1986 || Attempted to assassinate the Bengal Governor [[Stanley Jackson]].\n|-\n| [[Kalpana Datta]] || 1913 || 1995 || Indian Independence Movement, also part of the [[Chittagong armoury raid]] planning.\n|-\n| [[Kartar Singh Sarabha]] || 1896 || 1915 || Most famous accused in the Lahore conspiracy trial.\n|-\n| [[Shyamji Krishna Varma]] || 1857 || 1930 || Founded the Indian Home Rule Society, [[India House]] and \"The Indian Sociologist\" in London.\n|-\n| [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] || 1897 || ? || Founded the [[Indian Legion]] and revamped the [[Indian National Army]].\n|-\n| [[Binod Bihari Chowdhury]] || 1911 || 2013 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]]\n|-\n| [[Bhupendranath Datta]] || 1880 || 1961 || [[Indo-German Conspiracy]], member of [[Anushilan Samiti]].\n|-\n| [[Amarendranath Chatterjee]] || 1880 || 1957 || [[Indo-German Conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Atulkrishna Ghosh]] || 1890 || 1966 || [[Indo-German Conspiracy]]\n|-\n| [[Subodh Roy]] || 1916 || 2006 || [[Chittagong armoury raid]], [[Tebhaga movement]]\n|-\n| [[Maulvi Liaquat Ali]] || 1812 || 1892 || Captured Khusro Bagh in Allahabad and declared \"independence\" of India.\n|- \n| [[Asaf Ali]] || 1888 || 1953 || Indian national movement\n|- \n| [[Rani of Jhansi]] || 19 November 1828, Varanasi || 18 June 1858, Gwalior || Rani Laxmi Bhai was one of the leading figures of the Indian Rebellion of 1857 and became a symbol of resistance to the British Raj for Indian nationalists.\n|-\n| [[Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi]] || 1869 || 1948 || Father of the Nation, he was the preeminent leader of the Indian independence movement in British-ruled India. Employing non-violent civil disobedience, Gandhi led India to independence and inspired movements for civil rights and freedom across the world.\n|-\n| [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel]] || 1875 || 1950 ||  popularly known as Sardar Patel, was an Indian politician. He served as the first Deputy Prime Minister of India. He was an Indian barrister, a senior leader of the Indian National Congress and a founding father of the Republic of India who played a leading role in the country's struggle for independence and guided its integration into a united, independent nation.\n|-\n| [[Jawahar Lal Nehru]] || 1889 || 1964 || Founding father of India, an Indian independence activist, and subsequently, the first Prime Minister of India and a central figure in Indian politics before and after Independence.\n|-\n| [[S. Satyamurti]] || 1887 || 1943 || Mayor of Madras, President of the Madras District Congress Party Committee, Advocate of the High Court of Madras, Senior Advocate of the Federal Court of India, Deputy leader of the Congress party, Member of the Indian Legislative Assembly.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 March 1943 |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1943/03/28/83911189.html?pageNumber=24 |title=S, SATYAMURTI; Indian Political Leader, 56, Long Active in Civil Disobedience |newspaper=The New York Times}} {{Subscription required}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Shaukat Ali (politician)|Shaukat Ali]] || 1873 || 1938 || Maulana, \"Shaukat Ali\", his brother \"Mohammad Ali\" and their mother \"Bi Amman\", played an incredible role in the freedom movement of India against the British Imperialism. These brave freedom fighters were unmitigated champions of Hindu-Muslim unity who endorsed the Hindus and the Muslims to fight together in the struggle for independence from the British forgetting their religious feelings and thinking only they are Indians, they were the ambassadors of Hindu-Muslim Unity. They were arrested and imprisoned from 1921 to 1923 for his support to Mahatma Gandhi and the Indian National Congress during the Non-Cooperation Movement (1919\u20131922).<ref>[http://www.royalbook.com.pk/bookpage.aspx?TID=95 Brief History of Shaukat Ali],[http://storyofpakistan.com/maulana-shaukat-ali], [http://indianprofiles.blogspot.in/2007/04/maulana-shaukat-ali.html]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sushila Chain Trehan]] || 1923 || 2011 || Leading member of Arya Samaj who fought for women's rights.\n|-\n| [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] || 1856 || 1920 || Tilak was one of the first and strongest advocates of [[Swaraj]] (\"self-rule\") and a strong radical in Indian consciousness.\n|-\n| [[Bipin Chandra Pal]] || 1858 || 1932 || Member of [[Swaraj]] \n|-\n| [[Lala Lajpat Rai]] || 1865 || 1928 || Member of [[Swaraj]] \n|-\n| [[Alekh Patra]] || 1923 || 1999 || Member of [[Congress]], [[sarvodaya]], who participated in the freedom movement at the age of about 18. \n|-\n| [[Accamma Cherian]] || 1909 || 1982 || popularly known as the Jhansi Rani of Travancore. \n|-\n| [[Rosamma Punnoose]] || 1913 || 2013 || Indian independence activist, politician and lawyer. \n|-\n| [[Annie Mascarene]] || 1902 || 1963 || [[Indian freedom fighter]] and [[Member of Parliament]] from [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]]. \n|-\n| [[Titusji]] || 1905 || 1980 || one of the 78 marchers selected by [[Mahatma Gandhi]] to take part in the 1930 [[Dandi March]]. \n|-\n| [[George Joseph (Kerala)]] || 1887 || 1938 || '''George Joseph''' was a [[lawyer]] and [[Indian independence activist]]. One of the earliest and among the most prominent [[Syrian Christians of Kerala|Syrian Christians from Kerala]] to join the freedom struggle. \n|-\n| [[T. V. Thomas]] || 1910 || 1977 || He was one of the first generation trade union leaders in Kerala and was actively involved in the [[Indian independence movement]].\n|-\n| [[Madhusudan Das]] || 1848 || 1934 || A well-known leader from the Christian community in Odisha, popularly known as \"Utkal Gourab\". He was the first graduate and advocate of Odisha.\n|-\n| [[Kali Charan Banerjee]] || 1847 || 1907 || He being a fine orator and representative of Bengali Christian community, he joined the Indian National Congress(Congress) in 1885, and regularly addressed the Congress annual sessions in moulding the policy of national movement.\n|-\n| [[Vinayak Damodar Savarkar]] || 28 May 1883 || 26 February 1966 || He was an Indian independence activist.\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n# [https://www.jaborejob.com/freedom-fighters-in-india/ Freedom Fighters of India: Backbone of Our Independence]\n# [https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-history/modern-history/freedom-fighters.html Indian Freedom Fighters - List & Brief Bio of Freedom Activists]<br />\n{{Portal|India}}\n\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Independence Activists}}\n[[Category:Lists of Indian people]]\n[[Category:India history-related lists]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of activists]]\n[[Category:British India-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Ajpfrgvcc", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Indian_independence_activists"}
{"title_page": "Lava (Ramayana)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Lava (''Ramayana'')}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox deity <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type = Hindu\n| image = Lava and Kusa, the sons of R\u0101ma..jpg\n| caption = Lava and [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]], sons of [[Rama]]\n| name = Lava\n| Devanagari = \u0932\u0935 and kush\n| father = [[Rama]]\n| mother = [[Sita]]\n| birth_place = [[Bithoor#Notable landmarks|Valmiki Ashram]],  [[Bithoor|Brahmavart]], [[Kosala]] (present-day [[Bithoor]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]) \n| siblings = [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]]\n| dynasty = [[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]]\n| texts = ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]\n}}\n\n'''Lava''' ({{lang-sa|\u0932\u0935}}) <ref name=\"lcuk\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lcuk.org.uk/history.htm |title=Lohana Community United Kingdom |access-date=14 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215927/http://www.lcuk.org.uk/history.htm |archive-date=4 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and his twin brother [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]], were the children of [[Rama]] and [[Sita]]. Their story is recounted in the [[Hindu]] epic, ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]. Lava was younger of the two and is said to have a wheatish golden complexion like their mother, while Kusha had a blackish complexion like their father.\n\nLava got the the original Kosala kingdom, with the new capital of Sharavati, which later became Shravasti  <ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Bombay Historical Society\n  | title = Annual bibliography of Indian history and Indology, Volume 4\n  | page = 257\n  | year = 1946\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=FAS2AAAAIAAJ }}</ref> \n(the modern day city of [[Lahore]]),<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Baqir\n  | first = Muhammad\n  | title = Lahore, past and present\n  | publisher = B.R. Pub. Corp\n  | pages = 19\u201320\n  | year = 1985\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-pAcAAAAMAAJ&q=Lahore+Lava&dq=Lahore+Lava&ei=x78gSqXAIYWKygTqtNXmAg&pgis=1\n  | accessdate = 2009-05-29}}</ref>\nwhich is named after him.<ref>{{cite book|title= Guide to Lahore|author=Masudul Hasan|publisher=Ferozsons|year=1978}}</ref> The [[Bargujar]], Sikarwar ([[Sakarwar]]) and [[Sisodia]] [[Rajput]]s, [[Lohana]], [[Kurmi]], and [[Leva Patel|Leva Patidar]] are present-day castes who claim their descent from Lava. Lava belongs to the [[Ikshvaku]] clan or [[Suryavansha|Suryavansha Dynasty]] of [[Kshatriya]]s in [[ancient India]].<ref name=\"lcuk\" /><ref>Diwan Bherumal Mahirchand Advani. Trans. by Narain Sobhraj Kimatrai. ''The Source of Sindhi Surnames''. [http://www.dalsabzi.com/Books/Sindhi_surnames/chapter%206.htm#LOHANA Chapter 6.] 1947.</ref><ref>[http://www.kedareshwarpratishthan.com/homeaboutgujar.htm Leva Gurjars ancestry]</ref>\n\nLav was elder brother and Kush was younger.\n\n==Birth and childhood==\n[[File:Valmiki train Lava Kushas in Art of Archery.jpg|thumb|left|Valmiki trains Lava and Kusha in the Art of Archery]]\n[[File:The Poet Valmiki, teaching Ramayana to Kusa and Lava.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The Sage Valmiki, teaching Ramayana to Lava and Kusa]]\n\nAccording to the [[Ramayana]], [[Sita]] was banished from the kingdom of [[Ayodhya]] by [[Rama]] due to the gossip of the kingdom folk. She took refuge in the [[ashram]] of Sage [[Valmiki]] located on the banks of the [[Tamsa river]].<ref>{{cite book|title= Historic Rama of Valmiki|author=Vishvanath Limaye|publisher=Gyan Ganga Prakashan|year=1984}}</ref> Lava and Kusha were born at the ashram and were educated and trained in [[military]] skills under the tutelage of Sage Valmiki. They also learned the story of Rama.\n[[ File:Lava & kusha chant Ramayana before Rama.jpg |thumb|Kusha and lava recite Ramayana in Court of Rama]]\n\n==Ashwamedha Yagya==\n\nDuring an [[Ashvamedha|Ashvamedha Yagya]] held by [[Rama]], Sage Valmiki along with Lava and Kusha, attended with Sita in disguise.\n\nLava and Kusha chanted the Ramayana in the presence of Rama and a vast audience. When Lava and Kusha recited about Sita's exile, Rama became grief-stricken and Valmiki produced Sita. Sita, struck with embarrassment and grief, called upon the earth, her mother ([[Bh\u016bmi]]), to receive her and as the ground opened, she vanished into it. Rama then learnt that Lava and Kusha were his children.\n\nIn some versions, Lava and Kusha capture the horse of the sacrifice and defeat Rama's brothers and their army and when Rama came to fight with them, Sita intervened and unites father and sons.\n\n==Later history==\n\nLava and Kusha became rulers after their father Rama and founded the cities of [[Lavapuri]] (current day \"Lahore\") and [[Kasur]] respectively. The king of [[Kosala]] [[Raghava Rama]] installed his son Lava at [[Sravasti]] and Kusha at [[Kushavati]].<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Nadiem\n  | first = Ihsan N\n  | title = Punjab: land, history, people\n  | publisher = Al-Faisal Nashran\n  | page = 111\n  | year = 2005\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pyFuAAAAMAAJ&q=Kasur+Kusha&dq=Kasur+Kusha&ei=9rwgSritBZWQyASHk7maDw&pgis=1\n  | accessdate = 2009-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThere is a temple associated with Lava (or Loh) inside Shahi Qila, Lahore.<ref>Ahmed, Shoaib. [http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_3-11-2004_pg7_27 \"Lahore Fort dungeons to re-open after more than a century.\"] ''Daily Times''. 3 November 2004.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Luv Kush]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n[[Category:Ikshvaku dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Lava (''Ramayana'')}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox deity <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type = Hindu\n| image = Lava and Kusa, the sons of R\u0101ma..jpg\n| caption = Lava and [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]], sons of [[Rama]]\n| name = Lava\n| Devanagari = \u0932\u0935 and kush\n| father = [[Rama]]\n| mother = [[Sita]]\n| birth_place = [[Bithoor#Notable landmarks|Valmiki Ashram]],  [[Bithoor|Brahmavart]], [[Kosala]] (present-day [[Bithoor]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]) \n| siblings = [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]]\n| dynasty = [[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]]\n| texts = ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]\n}}\n\n'''Lava''' ({{lang-sa|\u0932\u0935}}) <ref name=\"lcuk\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lcuk.org.uk/history.htm |title=Lohana Community United Kingdom |access-date=14 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215927/http://www.lcuk.org.uk/history.htm |archive-date=4 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and his twin brother [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]], were the children of [[Rama]] and [[Sita]]. Their story is recounted in the [[Hindu]] epic, ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]. Lava was younger of the two and is said to have a wheatish golden complexion like their mother, while Kusha had a blackish complexion like their father.\n\nLava is purported to have founded ''Lavapuri''<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Bombay Historical Society\n  | title = Annual bibliography of Indian history and Indology, Volume 4\n  | page = 257\n  | year = 1946\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=FAS2AAAAIAAJ }}</ref> \n(the modern day city of [[Lahore]]),<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Baqir\n  | first = Muhammad\n  | title = Lahore, past and present\n  | publisher = B.R. Pub. Corp\n  | pages = 19\u201320\n  | year = 1985\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-pAcAAAAMAAJ&q=Lahore+Lava&dq=Lahore+Lava&ei=x78gSqXAIYWKygTqtNXmAg&pgis=1\n  | accessdate = 2009-05-29}}</ref>\nwhich is named after him.<ref>{{cite book|title= Guide to Lahore|author=Masudul Hasan|publisher=Ferozsons|year=1978}}</ref> The [[Bargujar]], Sikarwar ([[Sakarwar]]) and [[Sisodia]] [[Rajput]]s, [[Lohana]], [[Kurmi]], and [[Leva Patel|Leva Patidar]] are present-day castes who claim their descent from Lava. Lava belongs to the [[Ikshvaku]] clan or [[Suryavansha|Suryavansha Dynasty]] of [[Kshatriya]]s in [[ancient India]].<ref name=\"lcuk\" /><ref>Diwan Bherumal Mahirchand Advani. Trans. by Narain Sobhraj Kimatrai. ''The Source of Sindhi Surnames''. [http://www.dalsabzi.com/Books/Sindhi_surnames/chapter%206.htm#LOHANA Chapter 6.] 1947.</ref><ref>[http://www.kedareshwarpratishthan.com/homeaboutgujar.htm Leva Gurjars ancestry]</ref>\n\nLav was elder brother and Kush was younger.\n\n==Birth and childhood==\n[[File:Valmiki train Lava Kushas in Art of Archery.jpg|thumb|left|Valmiki trains Lava and Kusha in the Art of Archery]]\n[[File:The Poet Valmiki, teaching Ramayana to Kusa and Lava.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The Sage Valmiki, teaching Ramayana to Lava and Kusa]]\n\nAccording to the [[Ramayana]], [[Sita]] was banished from the kingdom of [[Ayodhya]] by [[Rama]] due to the gossip of the kingdom folk. She took refuge in the [[ashram]] of Sage [[Valmiki]] located on the banks of the [[Tamsa river]].<ref>{{cite book|title= Historic Rama of Valmiki|author=Vishvanath Limaye|publisher=Gyan Ganga Prakashan|year=1984}}</ref> Lava and Kusha were born at the ashram and were educated and trained in [[military]] skills under the tutelage of Sage Valmiki. They also learned the story of Rama.\n[[ File:Lava & kusha chant Ramayana before Rama.jpg |thumb|Kusha and lava recite Ramayana in Court of Rama]]\n\n==Ashwamedha Yagya==\n\nDuring an [[Ashvamedha|Ashvamedha Yagya]] held by [[Rama]], Sage Valmiki along with Lava and Kusha, attended with Sita in disguise.\n\nLava and Kusha chanted the Ramayana in the presence of Rama and a vast audience. When Lava and Kusha recited about Sita's exile, Rama became grief-stricken and Valmiki produced Sita. Sita, struck with embarrassment and grief, called upon the earth, her mother ([[Bh\u016bmi]]), to receive her and as the ground opened, she vanished into it. Rama then learnt that Lava and Kusha were his children.\n\nIn some versions, Lava and Kusha capture the horse of the sacrifice and defeat Rama's brothers and their army and when Rama came to fight with them, Sita intervened and unites father and sons.\n\n==Later history==\n\nLava and Kusha became rulers after their father Rama and founded the cities of [[Lavapuri]] (current day \"Lahore\") and [[Kasur]] respectively. The king of [[Kosala]] [[Raghava Rama]] installed his son Lava at [[Sravasti]] and Kusha at [[Kushavati]].<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Nadiem\n  | first = Ihsan N\n  | title = Punjab: land, history, people\n  | publisher = Al-Faisal Nashran\n  | page = 111\n  | year = 2005\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pyFuAAAAMAAJ&q=Kasur+Kusha&dq=Kasur+Kusha&ei=9rwgSritBZWQyASHk7maDw&pgis=1\n  | accessdate = 2009-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThere is a temple associated with Lava (or Loh) inside Shahi Qila, Lahore.<ref>Ahmed, Shoaib. [http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_3-11-2004_pg7_27 \"Lahore Fort dungeons to re-open after more than a century.\"] ''Daily Times''. 3 November 2004.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Luv Kush]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n[[Category:Ikshvaku dynasty]]\n", "name_user": "122.162.203.208", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lava_(Ramayana)"}
{"title_page": "Jay Shah", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Jaydev Shah}}\n{{infobox person\n| name               = Badio shah\n| birth_name         = Badio Amitbhai Shah\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |31 |2019|10|23}}<ref name=espn/>\n| alma_mater         = [[Nirma University]]\n| occupation         = Businessman, cricket administrator\n| father             = [[Amit Shah]]\n}}\n'''Jay Amitbhai Shah'''<ref name=thewire/> is an Indian businessman and [[cricket]] administrator. In October 2019, he became the secretary of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |work=Sportstar |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShah was born in 1987/1988 to [[Amit Shah]], a political activist for the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]'s youth wing, [[Bharatiya Janata Yuva Morcha]], and Sonal Shah. He graduated from [[Nirma University]] with a [[B.Tech]].<ref name=thewire/> He underwent cricket training in [[Ahmedabad]] under Jayendra Sehgal, who considered Shah to have been a \"decent enough [[batsman]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Amit Shah's son takes guard at BCCI |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/amit-shahs-son-takes-guard-at-bcci/articleshow/46856388.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShah worked as one of the directors of Temple Enterprise, a company which was founded in 2004 and involved in the trade of agricultural products. The company shut operations in October 2016. Shah owns a 60 per cent stake in Kusum Finserve which was established in 2015.<ref name=thewire>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Rohini |title=The Golden Touch of Jay Amit Shah |url=https://thewire.in/business/amit-shah-narendra-modi-jay-shah-bjp |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Wire |date=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chatterjee |first1=Manini |title=His father's son |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/his-father-s-son/cid/1454764 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an executive board member of the Central Board of Cricket, Ahmedabad, starting 2009, Shah became the joint secretary of the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] (GCA) in September 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Narhari Amin back in team GCA, but Saheba knocked out |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/ahmedabad/report-narhari-amin-back-in-team-gca-but-saheba-knocked-out-1886602 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=DNA India |date=9 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=espn>{{cite news |last1=Dikshit |first1=Vishal |title=Meet the BCCI's new office bearers |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27907780/meet-bcci-new-office-bearers |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 October 2019}}</ref> During his tenure as joint secretary, he oversaw GCA's construction of the [[Sardar Patel Stadium]], the world's largest cricket stadium, in Ahmedabad, along with his father Amit Shah who was GCA president at the time; the project was reportedly the brainchild of Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] who was the president of GCA before Amit Shah.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patwardhan |first1=Deepti |title=Assurance of not cutting corners over credibility |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/cricket/2019/oct/24/assurance-of-not-cutting-corners-over-credibility-2052178.html |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The New Indian Express |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World's largest cricket stadium in Motera few months away from completion |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/worlds-largest-cricket-stadium-in-motera-few-months-away-from-completion/articleshow/71125258.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=New Motera stadium is Prime Minister Narendra Modi's vision, says Amit Shah |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/new-motera-stadium-is-prime-minister-narendra-modis-vision-says-amit-shah/articleshow/70918902.cms |accessdate=6 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nShah became a member of the finance and marketing committees of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pandey |first1=Devendra |title=N Srinivasan loses BCCI's control |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/srini-loses-boards-control/ |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Indian Express |date=7 April 2015}}</ref> He stepped down from the position of GCA joint secretary in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=Amit Shah, son Jay, step down from Gujarat Cricket Association posts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/amit-shah-steps-down-as-gujarat-cricket-association-president/articleshow/71347398.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=29 September 2019}}</ref> The following month, he was elected as the secretary of BCCI for a one-and-a-half-year term and the youngest of the five office bearers.<ref name=espn/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Sportstar |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, the BCCI selected Shah as its representative for future CEC meetings of [[International Cricket Council]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah to represent BCCI at ICC CEC meeting |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/jay-shah-to-represent-bcci-at-icc-cec-meeting/articleshow/72317958.cms |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2015, Shah married Rishita Patel, a college friend, in a traditional Gujarati ceremony.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhan |first1=Rohit |title=Wedding of Amit Shah's son feels Delhi chill  |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Wedding-of-Amit-Shahs-son-feels-Delhi-chill/articleshow/46193764.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Political bigwigs, corporate czars at engagement of Amit Shah's son |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Political-bigwigs-corporate-czars-at-engagement-of-Amit-Shahs-son/articleshow/38345451.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Defamation case against ''The Wire''===\n{{see also|The Wire (India)#Jay Shah}}\nShah filed a criminal defamation case and a civil lawsuit of {{INR}}100 crore against the editors of ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]]'' for an October 2017 article in which the website reported Shah's company revenue increased 16,000 times one year after [[Narendra Modi]] became the Indian Prime Minister.<ref name=withdraw/> In 2018, the [[Gujarat High Court]] restored a [[gag order]], earlier placed by a civil court, on the website, preventing it from publishing any content connecting Shah's businesses to Modi.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: Gujarat High Court restores gag order on The Wire |url=https://scroll.in/latest/869344/jay-shah-defamation-case-gujarat-high-court-restores-gag-order-on-the-wire |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=20 February 2018}}</ref> In August 2019, ''The Wire'' withdrew its appeal against the criminal defamation case and announced that it will stand trial, even as the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] bench questioned the website's [[yellow journalism|journalism standards]].<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: 'The Wire' withdraws its plea from Supreme Court, says will stand trial |url=https://scroll.in/latest/935353/jay-shah-defamation-case-the-wire-withdraws-its-plea-from-supreme-court-says-will-stand-trial |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Jay}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Indian cricket administrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Jaydev Shah}}\n{{infobox person\n| birth_name         = Jay Amitbhai Shah\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |31 |2019|10|23}}<ref name=espn/>\n| alma_mater         = [[Nirma University]]\n| occupation         = Businessman, cricket administrator\n| father             = [[Amit Shah]]\n}}\n'''Jay Amitbhai Shah'''<ref name=thewire/> is an Indian businessman and [[cricket]] administrator. In October 2019, he became the secretary of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |work=Sportstar |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShah was born in 1987/1988 to [[Amit Shah]], a political activist for the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]'s youth wing, [[Bharatiya Janata Yuva Morcha]], and Sonal Shah. He graduated from [[Nirma University]] with a [[B.Tech]].<ref name=thewire/> He underwent cricket training in [[Ahmedabad]] under Jayendra Sehgal, who considered Shah to have been a \"decent enough [[batsman]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Amit Shah's son takes guard at BCCI |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/amit-shahs-son-takes-guard-at-bcci/articleshow/46856388.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShah worked as one of the directors of Temple Enterprise, a company which was founded in 2004 and involved in the trade of agricultural products. The company shut operations in October 2016. Shah owns a 60 per cent stake in Kusum Finserve which was established in 2015.<ref name=thewire>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Rohini |title=The Golden Touch of Jay Amit Shah |url=https://thewire.in/business/amit-shah-narendra-modi-jay-shah-bjp |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Wire |date=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chatterjee |first1=Manini |title=His father's son |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/his-father-s-son/cid/1454764 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an executive board member of the Central Board of Cricket, Ahmedabad, starting 2009, Shah became the joint secretary of the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] (GCA) in September 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Narhari Amin back in team GCA, but Saheba knocked out |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/ahmedabad/report-narhari-amin-back-in-team-gca-but-saheba-knocked-out-1886602 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=DNA India |date=9 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=espn>{{cite news |last1=Dikshit |first1=Vishal |title=Meet the BCCI's new office bearers |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27907780/meet-bcci-new-office-bearers |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 October 2019}}</ref> During his tenure as joint secretary, he oversaw GCA's construction of the [[Sardar Patel Stadium]], the world's largest cricket stadium, in Ahmedabad, along with his father Amit Shah who was GCA president at the time; the project was reportedly the brainchild of Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] who was the president of GCA before Amit Shah.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patwardhan |first1=Deepti |title=Assurance of not cutting corners over credibility |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/cricket/2019/oct/24/assurance-of-not-cutting-corners-over-credibility-2052178.html |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The New Indian Express |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World's largest cricket stadium in Motera few months away from completion |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/worlds-largest-cricket-stadium-in-motera-few-months-away-from-completion/articleshow/71125258.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=New Motera stadium is Prime Minister Narendra Modi's vision, says Amit Shah |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/new-motera-stadium-is-prime-minister-narendra-modis-vision-says-amit-shah/articleshow/70918902.cms |accessdate=6 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nShah became a member of the finance and marketing committees of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pandey |first1=Devendra |title=N Srinivasan loses BCCI's control |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/srini-loses-boards-control/ |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Indian Express |date=7 April 2015}}</ref> He stepped down from the position of GCA joint secretary in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=Amit Shah, son Jay, step down from Gujarat Cricket Association posts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/amit-shah-steps-down-as-gujarat-cricket-association-president/articleshow/71347398.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=29 September 2019}}</ref> The following month, he was elected as the secretary of BCCI for a one-and-a-half-year term and the youngest of the five office bearers.<ref name=espn/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Sportstar |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, the BCCI selected Shah as its representative for future CEC meetings of [[International Cricket Council]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah to represent BCCI at ICC CEC meeting |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/jay-shah-to-represent-bcci-at-icc-cec-meeting/articleshow/72317958.cms |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2015, Shah married Rishita Patel, a college friend, in a traditional Gujarati ceremony.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhan |first1=Rohit |title=Wedding of Amit Shah's son feels Delhi chill  |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Wedding-of-Amit-Shahs-son-feels-Delhi-chill/articleshow/46193764.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Political bigwigs, corporate czars at engagement of Amit Shah's son |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Political-bigwigs-corporate-czars-at-engagement-of-Amit-Shahs-son/articleshow/38345451.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Defamation case against ''The Wire''===\n{{see also|The Wire (India)#Jay Shah}}\nShah filed a criminal defamation case and a civil lawsuit of {{INR}}100 crore against the editors of ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]]'' for an October 2017 article in which the website reported Shah's company revenue increased 16,000 times one year after [[Narendra Modi]] became the Indian Prime Minister.<ref name=withdraw/> In 2018, the [[Gujarat High Court]] restored a [[gag order]], earlier placed by a civil court, on the website, preventing it from publishing any content connecting Shah's businesses to Modi.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: Gujarat High Court restores gag order on The Wire |url=https://scroll.in/latest/869344/jay-shah-defamation-case-gujarat-high-court-restores-gag-order-on-the-wire |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=20 February 2018}}</ref> In August 2019, ''The Wire'' withdrew its appeal against the criminal defamation case and announced that it will stand trial, even as the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] bench questioned the website's [[yellow journalism|journalism standards]].<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: 'The Wire' withdraws its plea from Supreme Court, says will stand trial |url=https://scroll.in/latest/935353/jay-shah-defamation-case-the-wire-withdraws-its-plea-from-supreme-court-says-will-stand-trial |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Jay}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Indian cricket administrators]]\n", "name_user": "2402:3a80:1557:1da7:ca6:43a4:13db:6f2c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Shah"}
{"title_page": "California's Great America", "text_new": "{{for|the theme park in Gurnee, Illinois|Six Flags Great America}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = California's Great America\n| image = <br>[[File:California's Great America Logo.svg|200px]]<br><br>[[File:California's Great America 2.JPG|240px]]\n| caption = \n| location = [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]] \n| location2 = [[California]]\n| location3 = [[United States]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|37|23|45.4|N|121|58|20.1|W|display=title,inline}}\n| opening_date = {{start date|1976|3|20}}\n| previous_names = '''''Marriott's Great America''''' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\"> 1976\u20131984</span><br />'''''Great America''''' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\"> 1985\u20131992, 2007 </span><br />'''''Paramount's Great America''''' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\"> 1993\u20132006 </span>\n| area = {{convert|100|acre}}\n| season = Late March\u2013December\n| rides = 52\n| coasters = 9\n| water_rides = 2\n| theme = \n| owner = [[Cedar Fair Entertainment Company]]\n| general_manager = Manuel Gonzalez \n| status = Operating\n| slogan = It's Amazing in Here\n| homepage = {{Official website|http://www.cagreatamerica.com}}\n}}\n\n'''California's Great America''' (formerly known as '''Marriott's Great America''' and '''Paramount's Great America''') is a {{convert|100|acre|adj=on}} [[amusement park]] located in [[Santa Clara, California]]. Owned and operated by [[Cedar Fair]], it originally opened in 1976 as one of two parks built by the [[Marriott Corporation]]. The park has appeared in 1994 films ''[[Beverly Hills Cop III]]'' and ''[[Getting Even with Dad]]'' and features over 40 rides and attractions. One of its most notable attractions, [[Gold Striker]], has been featured as a top-ranked wooden roller coaster in ''[[Amusement Today|Amusement Today's]]'' annual Golden Ticket Awards publication. Also featured is [[RailBlazer]], one of the first Raptor roller coasters by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]] in the world, and Flight Deck, a [[Bolliger & Mabillard]] inverted coaster.\n\n==History==\n\n===Marriott & KECO Era (1976\u20131992)===\nMarriott's Great America, built by hotel and restaurant operator [[Marriott Corporation]], opened to the public on March 20, 1976.<ref>{{cite news |title=Photos: A look back at 40 years of California's Great America |date=March 27, 2015 |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2015/03/27/photos-a-look-back-at-40-years-of-californias-great-america/}}</ref> Less than two months later on May 29, the company opened a second Marriott's Great America&nbsp;\u2013 later known as [[Six Flags Great America]]&nbsp;\u2013 north of [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] in [[Gurnee, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Six Flags purchase\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/27/business/marriott-to-sell-park-to-bally.html|title=Marriott to Sell Park to Bally|date=April 27, 1984|newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> [[Marriott's Great America (Maryland\u2013Virginia)|A third park]] was initially planned for the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area]], but the idea was later abandoned after several failed attempts to sway local opposition.<ref name=\"3rd Great America\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19770819&id=j95NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-ooDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5660,2451015|title=Marriott's high-powered approach|last=Flattau|first=Edward|date=August 19, 1977|work=The Free Lance-Star|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Great america.jpg|thumb|left|View of California's Great America from above]]\nThe park, though profitable, was still an earnings disappointment for Marriott, leading the company in 1983 to explore options to sell. An interested party, '''Caz Development Co.''', appraised the land value at US$800,000 to $1 million per acre. Marriott also involved the city of Santa Clara in negotiations, which was already leasing {{convert|55|acre}} of parking space for the amusement park. Fearing homebuilding on the land by Caz Development would lower home values of existing homeowners, the city council approved a $101 million purchasing agreement on January 31, 1984, by a 4\u20133 vote that also had to be approved by city residents. The citywide vote passed, approving the sale by a margin of 3 to 1. Caz Development then sued the city and Marriott in the [[Superior Court of Santa Clara County]] to block the transaction. The court nullified the sale, forcing the city to attempt to salvage the deal through negotiations with the other parties. Unable to broker a timely agreement, the city council voted 6\u20131 to scuttle the sale on February 5, 1985, though the city was still interested in owning the park. After Marriott refunded a $20 million down payment back to the city, negotiations were restarted. All parties were able to agree on a compromise, which was signed in marathon sessions taking place in early June 1985. The city acquired the park for $93.5 million from Marriott, which retained {{convert|20|acre}} from the sale for development. Caz Development settled and was allowed to build a hotel and office near the park, which the city renamed Great America.\n\n[[Kings Entertainment Company]], who owned and operated other amusement parks, was hired in 1985 to manage Great America for the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1948&dat=19850620&id=KNZJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aB0NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1152,5468771|title=A New Start At Great America|date=June 20, 1985|work=The Modesto Bee|accessdate=July 10, 2012|location=Modesto, CA}}</ref> In 1989, the city decided to return the park to the private sector and sold it to Kings Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1992&dat=19890606&id=W5VcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5086,1057726|title=Firm Acquires Big Theme Park|date=June 6, 1989|work=Merced Sun-Star|accessdate=July 10, 2012|location=Merced, California}}</ref> In the agreement, the city would earn 5% of all revenue that exceeds $56 million.{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n===Paramount Parks Era (1992\u20132006)===\n[[Image:Paramountgreatamerica.jpg|thumb|right|Logo used from 2003 until its sale to Cedar Fair.]]\nThree years later Paramount Communications (formerly [[Gulf+Western]]), the owners of [[Paramount Pictures]], sought to join other entertainment companies as a theme park owner. The company acquired Kings Entertainment, owner of three parks including Great America, and one other park for $400 million and created [[Paramount Parks]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]], the parent of [[Viacom Media Networks|MTV Networks]] (including [[Nickelodeon]]), then bought Paramount in 1994, allowing Nickelodeon theming and merchandise into the park as well. During the Paramount era, attractions from the Action FX Theatre, Nickelodeon Splat City (later Nickelodeon Central), Drop Zone Stunt Tower, Invertigo, and many more modern thrill ride attractions were added in. Because the park is landlocked in the center of Silicon Valley, several rides including the classic train ride and the [[Sky Whirl]], a Marriott's Great America signature attraction, were removed to make way for newer attractions.\n\nIn its last years as a Paramount Park, Great America was co-owned with several broadcasting stations in the Bay Area, including [[KPIX-TV]] and [[KBCW (TV)|KBCW]].\n\n===Cedar Fair Entertainment Company (2006\u2013present)===\n[[Image:Great America 2007.PNG|thumb|right|Logo used in 2006. This logo is still seen on the litter bins in and around California's Great America.]]\nAfter Viacom and [[CBS Corporation]] split, Paramount Parks became part of CBS. The merger did not last long, as CBS announced plans to sell the theme park division.\n\n[[Cedar Fair Entertainment Co.]] announced in May 2006 that they were acquiring the amusement park division from CBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cedarfair.com/ir/press_releases/index.cfm?current_root=15&mode=story&story_id=77 |title=Press Releases :: Cedar Fair Entertainment Company |publisher=Cedarfair.com |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060728185503/http://www.cedarfair.com/ir/press_releases/index.cfm?current_root=15&mode=story&story_id=77 |archivedate=July 28, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref> The transaction included licensing agreements with Nickelodeon and Paramount, providing the park the option to retain its Nickelodeon and Paramount theming for several years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/811532/000081153206000054/0000811532-06-000054-index.htm |title=EDGAR Filing Documents for 0000811532-06-000054 |publisher=Sec.gov |date=2006-06-06 |accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>\n\nOn October 25, 2007, Cedar Fair renamed the park '''California's Great America'''. For the 2008 season, the park saw the addition of a [[Huss Rides]] top spin ride called FireFall, a new ice show in the \"Great America Theatre\" (formerly The Paramount Theatre), and the addition of the Halloween Haunt event to the park.<ref>[http://www2.cedarfair.com/greatamerica/news/detail.cfm?item_id=652 Great America | San Francisco's Themed Amusement Park<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116231626/http://www2.cedarfair.com/GreatAmerica/news/detail.cfm?item_id=652 |date=November 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2009, Cedar Fair announced that all the Nickelodeon themed areas would be replaced with ''[[Peanuts]]'' themed areas. In 2010, the newly rethemed [[Planet Snoopy]] opened in the park.\n\nOn January 27, 2011, the park announced Invertigo would be removed and relocated to [[Dorney Park]], another Cedar Fair property.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.cagreatamerica.com/news/detail.cfm?item_id=1069 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-01-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202070540/http://www.cagreatamerica.com/news/detail.cfm?item_id=1069 |archivedate=February 2, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2011, Cedar Fair confirmed reports that California's Great America would be sold to JMA Ventures, LLC for $70 million in cash. The sale required approval by the City of Santa Clara, and its city council was scheduled to vote on the matter on December 6, 2011. Cedar Fair, which purchased the park in 2006, expected to use the cash proceeds from the sale to reduce its senior secured debt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cedar Fair to sell California's Great America park for $70 million|url=http://cf.wddnsweb2.wddonline.net/_upload/pressreleases/091911%20-%20definitive%20agmt%20-%20caga.pdf|publisher=Cedar Fair Entertainment Company|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=September 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402164136/http://cf.wddnsweb2.wddonline.net/_upload/pressreleases/091911%20-%20definitive%20agmt%20-%20caga.pdf|archivedate=April 2, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, on December 6, 2011, JMA Ventures cancelled its plans to purchase the amusement park.<ref name=\"JMA cancels\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2011/12/06/jma-cancels-70m-california-great.html|title=JMA cancels $70M California Great America purchase|date=December 6, 2011|publisher=Business Journal|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> In the same announcement, Cedar Fair also verified that a long-term agreement was reached with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] regarding parking and construction of a [[Levi's Stadium|new stadium]] adjacent to Great America.<ref name=\"49ers\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2011/12/06/cedar-fair-niners-jma-great-america.html|title=JMA drops plan to buy Great America, but 49ers stadium plans proceed|last=Young|first=Eric|date=December 6, 2011|publisher=San Francisco Business Times|accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/local/2011/12/great-america-remain-current-owners-49er-stadium-spat-averted | title=Great America to remain with current owners; 49er stadium spat averted | publisher=The Examiner | date=December 6, 2011 | accessdate=December 10, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213231812/http://www.sfexaminer.com/local/2011/12/great-america-remain-current-owners-49er-stadium-spat-averted | archivedate=December 13, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Areas and attractions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=1 style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|-\n! Intensity rating<ref name=Rating>Ratings assigned per California's Great America, where \"1\" is the least intense and \"5\" is the most. See their {{cite web|url=http://www.miadventure.com/images/uploads/file/MA12-Guest-Assistance-Guide.pdf|title=Guest Assistance Guide|publisher=Michigan's Adventure|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522173044/http://www.miadventure.com/images/uploads/file/MA12-Guest-Assistance-Guide.pdf|archivedate=May 22, 2012|df=mdy-all}} for more specific details.</ref> <small>''(out of 5)''</small>\n|-\n|{{legend inline|#1CADEA|1 <small>(low)</small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#99DA50|2 <small>(mild)</small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#FED530|3 <small>(moderate)</small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#F7B754|4 <small>(high) </small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#ED5B33|5 <small>(aggressive)</small>|outline=silver}}\n|-\n|}\n''Note: Number ratings assigned per California's Great America, while the colors are unique to Wikipedia. For more details, see the California's Great America {{cite web|url=https://www.cagreatamerica.com/images/uploads/file/94749_GA_Safety_Guide_pp3.pdf|title=Guest Assistance Guide|access-date=May 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202135243/https://www.cagreatamerica.com/images/uploads/file/94749_GA_Safety_Guide_pp3.pdf|archive-date=February 2, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}\n\n===Roller coasters===\n[[File:Roller coasters at Great America.jpg|right|thumb|Gold Striker Roller Coaster at Great America]]\n{| cla