'{{fontcolor|white|3}}'''\n|-\n|[[Demon (roller coaster)|Demon]]\n|1976\n|[[Arrow Dynamics]]\n|Originally opened as \"Turn of the Century\" in 1976. Reconfigured and renamed \"Demon\" in 1980.\n|bgcolor=\"#ED5B33\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|5}}'''\n|-\n|[[RailBlazer]]\n|2018\n|[[Rocky Mountain Construction]]\n|Replaced [[Stinger (Dorney Park)|Invertigo]], a roller coaster which closed on January 27, 2011\n|bgcolor=\"#ED5B33\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|5}}'''\n|}\n\n===Orleans Place===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Ride\n!Opened\n!Manufacturer, type\n!Notes\n!Rating<ref name=Rating/>\n|-\n|Delta Flyer\n|1976\n|Von Roll<br />Gondola line\n|''Delta Flyer'' is the name for the Orleans Place station.\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|[[Flight Deck (California's Great America)|Flight Deck]]\n|1993\n|[[Bolliger & Mabillard]]<br />[[Inverted roller coaster]]\n|Formerly known as ''Top Gun''.\n|bgcolor=\"#ED5B33\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|5}}'''\n|-\n|Rue Le Dodge\n|1976\n|Soli [[Bumper Cars]]\n|A classic bumper car ride.\n|bgcolor=\"#F7B754\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|4}}'''\n|}\n\n===Planet Snoopy===\n{{Main|Planet Snoopy}}\nPlanet Snoopy is California's Great America's kids area, which opened in 2010.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ride\n!Opened\n!Type\n!Notes\n!Rating<ref name=Rating/>\n|-\n|Character Carousel\n| 1976\n|Carousel\n| Originally known as ''Ameri-Go-Round'' in County Fair\n|bgcolor=\"#1CADEA\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|1}}'''\n|-\n|Flying Ace\n|1999\n|\n|Originally known as ''KidzAir''\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|GR8 SK8\n|2015\n|\n|Originally at [[Knott's Berry Farm]] as ''Joe Cool's GR8 SK8''.\n|bgcolor=\"#FED530\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|3}}'''\n|-\n|Joe Cool's Dodgem School\n|1999\n|Kiddie bumper cars\n|Originally known as ''Fender Bender 500''.\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Kite-Eating Tree\n|1999\n|\n|Originally known as ''Junior Jump Club''.\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|[[Lucy's Crabbie Cabbie]]\n|1999\n|[[Kiddie roller coaster]]\n|Originally known as ''Taxi Jam''.\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Peanuts 500\n|2015\n|\n|Originally operated at Knott's Berry Farm as ''Charlie Brown's Speedway''.\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|PEANUTS Pirates\n|2003\n|Breakdance 4\n|Originally known as ''SpongeBob's Boat Mobiles''.\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Planet Snoopy Construction Zone\n|2014\n|Playground\n|Originally known as ''KidZ Construction Co.''\n|bgcolor=\"#1CADEA\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|1}}'''\n|-\n|The Pumpkin Patch\n|2003\n|\n|Originally known as ''Wild Thornberry's Treetop Lookout''\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Sally's Love Buggies\n|2003\n|\n|Originally known as ''Dora's Dune Buggies''\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Sally's Swing Set\n|\n|Family Wave Swinger\n|Originally known as ''Swing Swing Swing''\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Snoopy's Space Buggies\n|2015\n|\n|\n|bgcolor=\"#99DA50\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|2}}'''\n|-\n|Snoopy's Space Race\n|\n|\n|Originally known as ''Ghost Chasers''.\n|bgcolor=\"#1CADEA\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|1}}'''\n|-\n|[[Woodstock's Express (California's Great America)|Woodstock Express]]\n|1987\n|[[Steel roller coaster]] \n|Originally known as ''Blue Streak, Rugrats Runaway Reptar''\n|bgcolor=\"#FED530\" align=center | '''{{fontcolor|white|3}}'''\n|}\n\n===Time Capsule===\nA time capsule was buried at then Paramount's Great America in the former KidZville area of the park on March 29, 2002. The time capsule is set to open on March 29, 2152. The time capsule reads, \"At this site is buried a time capsule with essays by students in second through twelfth grades in the Santa Clara Unified School District and other local schools. What will the next 150 years in Santa Clara be like? In honor of the City of Santa Clara's sesquicentennial 1852-2002.\"\n\n===South Bay Shores===\n{{Main|South Bay Shores}}\n[[South Bay Shores]] is a water park located within California's Great America that opened in 2004 as Crocodile Dundee's Boomerang Bay. The name was later shortened to just Boomerang Bay in 2007. In August 2019, it was announced that Boomerang Bay would be expanded and renamed South Bay Shores. Access to the park is included with the price of admission to California's Great America.\n\n==Defunct attractions==\n'''Past rides and attractions include:'''\n\n*'''H.M.B. Endeavor''': An Intamin Looping Starship that was removed after the 2017 season to make way for a water park expansion of South Bay Shores.\n*'''Snoopy's Splash Dance''': A kiddie splash walk-through attraction that was removed after the 2017 season to make way for a water park expansion of South Bay Shores.\n*'''Logger's Run (ride)''': A Log flume ride that was originally located in All American Corners that was removed after the 2017 season to make way for a water park expansion of South Bay Shores.\n* '''Firefall (ride)''': A [[HUSS Park Attractions]] Top Spin flat-ride attraction that was originally located at the now abandoned [[Geauga Lake]] amusement park. The ride unexpectedly closed after the 2016 Halloween Haunt season.\n* '''[[Patriot (California's Great America)|Vortex]]''': A [[Bolliger & Mabillard]] [[Stand-up roller coaster|standup roller coaster]], was the second standup to be built by B&M. The ride was closed on Labor Day 2016 to be converted into floorless Patriot for 2017.\n* '''[[Stinger (roller coaster)|Invertigo]]''': An inverted [[Vekoma]] [[Shuttle roller coaster|shuttle coaster]], was North America's first inverted face-to-face roller coaster. It was removed due to reliability issues; topped by three breakdowns that made the news. The site was eventually used for [[RailBlazer]]<ref>{{cite web |title=RailBlazer |publisher=California's Great America |url=https://www.cagreatamerica.com/explore/railblazer}}</ref> Invertigo was later known as Stinger at sister park, [[Dorney Park & Wildwater Kingdom|Dorney Park]], until its closure in 2017.\n* '''[[Nighthawk (roller coaster)|Stealth]]''': A [[Vekoma]] [[Flying roller coaster|Flying Dutchman]] that was removed for construction of [[South Bay Shores|Boomerang Bay]] and relocated to [[Carowinds]] as Nighthawk.\n* '''Great America Scenic Railway''': A custom-built, {{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railways|narrow gauge]] railroad around the perimeter of California's Great America. The roadbed can still be seen in many places. Great America Scenic Railway was rumored to have closed to make room for [[Hypersonic XLC]], a coaster that was later cancelled and moved to sister park, [[Kings Dominion]].\n* '''Yankee Clipper''': An [[Arrow Dynamics]] Hydro Flume that used to interlock with Logger's Run. Yankee Clipper was removed to make room for Stealth.\n* '''[[Greased Lightnin' (Six Flags Discovery Kingdom)|Greased Lightnin']]''': Originally The Tidal Wave, was a shuttle loop roller coaster manufactured by Anton Schwarzkopf. A model of The Tidal Wave exists in the park office.\n* '''The Edge''': First-generation [[Intamin]] [[Freefall (ride)|Freefall]]\n* '''Skyhawk''': An Intamin Flight Trainer that was rumored to be removed for its maintenance issues such as clear canopies on the cabins that would frequently fall off mid-ride.\n* '''[[Sky Whirl]]''': A [[Triple wheel|Triple Tree Wheel]] supplied by Intamin, later known as Triple Wheel, then removed to make room for Invertigo.{{Citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n* '''Lobster''': An octopus/spider ride that was removed to make room for the Action Theater.\n* '''Bottoms Up''': A classic amusement ride known in the industry as a [[Wipeout (ride)|Trabant]].\n* '''Triple Play''': A Huss [[Troika (ride)|Troika]] ride that was next to Vortex.\n* '''[[Nickelodeon Central]]''': A themed area containing rides, mascots, and attractions that were based on shows from [[Nickelodeon]] and [[Nick Jr.]] It was closed in 2009 and changed into [[Planet Snoopy]].\n* '''[[Whizzer (roller coaster)|Whizzer]]''': Originally named Willard's Whizzer, the original steel family roller coaster was made by [[Anton Schwarzkopf]]. Whizzer was removed because of maintenance issues and declining popularity. Gold Striker and Xtreme Skyflyer were eventually built on the site.\n* '''Trolley Cars''': In early years, Trolley Cars traveled in the Hometown Square area and other parts of California's Great America.\n* '''Dolphin and Seal Show''': During the Marriott era, dolphins and seals were kept to do daily shows. The show was removed when Paramount took over, and today it's now known as Peanuts Playhouse Theater.\n* '''Smurf Woods''': A Smurf-themed small kids area with small Smurf mushroom houses. Today, this area is now Planet Snoopy.\n* '''Cajun Carpet''': A large rotating platform ride located near the Orbit and Rip Roaring Rapids.<ref name=\"hq.usace.army.mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hq.usace.army.mil/cepa/pubs/jul98/story11.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823205905/http://www.hq.usace.army.mil/cepa/pubs/jul98/story11.htm |archivedate=August 23, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Gulf Coaster]]''': A steel kiddie coaster\n* '''[[Ameri-Go-Round]]''': A PTC carousel that was removed for Drop Tower.\n* '''Hilltopper''': A classic Himalaya ride located just to the right of the Demon's entrance adjacent to the lift hill. Whitewater Falls' station roughly occupies the space now.\n* '''Saskatchewan Scrambler''': A classic Scrambler ride in the original Yukon Territory area, and later moved to the County Fair area and renamed Industrial Revolution.\n\n==Fast Lane==\n{{Further|List of Fast Lane attractions#California's Great America}}\n\n[[Fast Lane (Cedar Fair Entertainment Company)|Fast Lane]], first introduced at a Cedar Fair park in July 2011, is a secondary queue system that offers shorter wait times on the park's most popular rides.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/Economy/2011/08/06/Cedar-Fair-trying-out-1st-in-line-access-fees-2.html|title=Cedar Fair trying out 1st-in-line access fees|last=Chavez|first=Jon|work=The Blade|publisher=August 6, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2017}}</ref> FastLane is a system where\nin addition to a standard admission charge, visitors can purchase a wrist band. The band grants access to the Fast Lane queue. In theory, a limited number of wrist bands are available each day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagreatamerica.com/tickets-passes/fast-lane |title=Fast Lane |publisher=California's Great America |accessdate=July 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Halloween Haunt==\n[[File:Halloween Haunt California's Great America logo.jpg|right|200px]]\nHalloween Haunt is a seasonal event at California's Great America. It had a \"teaser\" maze in 2007, but officially began in 2008 and is patterned after other Cedar Fair HAUNT such as [[Knott's Scary Farm|Knott's]]\n\n[[SCarowinds]] HAUNT XL The annual Haunt includes over 500 monsters placed in various haunted mazes and scare zones throughout the park.\n\n===Current attractions===\nFor 2017, Halloween Haunt features eight haunted mazes, three scare zones, four shows, and five Skeleton Keys. It gives guests with the Fright Lane pass an extra rooms to go through in which are scattered throughout the park. These rooms are interactive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fear is Waiting for You |publisher=California's Great America |url=https://www.cagreatamerica.com/play/haunt}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |title=California's Great America Halloween Haunt |via=Facebook |url=https://www.facebook.com/cgahaunt}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n|-\n! st