 attraction themed to BioWare's [[Mass Effect]] video game in newly renovated Action Theater. Winterfest debuts. Halloween Haunt expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagreatamerica.com/what-s-new/coming-in-2016|title=Great America Announces New Attraction Featuring Mass Effect Videogame Series for 2016|publisher=California's Great America|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/entertainment/ci_28896052/great-america-electronic-arts-creating-mass-effects-attraction|title=Great America, Electronic Arts creating 'Mass Effects' attraction|last=Zavoral|first=Linda|date=September 29, 2015|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015: Planet Snoopy takes over the former KidZville section of the park. Halloween Haunt expansion.\n* 2014: Flight Deck re-painted red and white, Grizzly Loading Dock painted red and white, Fun TV added to most rides, Grizzly re-tracked and new flooring in Carousel Columbia. Halloween Haunt expansion. Picnic Pavilion make-over and new entrance from the parking lot. All 6 Drop Tower cabins operating, and KidzVille Shooting Range removed for birthday party area. All Day Dining Pass and new food options added. Halloween Haunt expansion with more monsters, two new Haunted Mazes for 2014, and one new Haunted Attraction. Werewolf Canyon and Slaughterhouse: Annihilation mazes removed. The Overlord is removed as Haunt icon. Skeleton Key is added, giving 5 mazes a new interactive room.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 8, 2014 |title=Off season tour and 2014 season details |publisher=Park Valley |url=http://cgaintel.blogspot.com/2014/03/off-season-tour-and-2014-season-details.html#more}}</ref>\n* 2013: New [[Great Coasters International]] wooden coaster, \"[[Gold Striker]]\" added; Happy Feet: Mumble's Wild Ride in the Action Theater; Subway added, Halloween Haunt expansion.\n* 2012: Several park improvements such as a repaint of Carousel Columbia, Demon and Flight Deck. ADA improvements including an elevator lift entrance for Loggers Run and Vortex. Also, The Grizzly is retracked, [[Fast Lane (Cedar Fair)|Fast Lane]]. Construction commenced on [[Levi's Stadium]], the new home of the [[San Francisco 49ers]], in the former Great America overflow parking lot. Halloween Haunt expansion,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.49ers.com/2012/04/02/stadium-groundbreaking-slated-for-april-19/ |title=49ers.com &#124; Stadium Groundbreaking Slated for April 19 |publisher=Blog.49ers.com |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625211803/http://blog.49ers.com/2012/04/02/stadium-groundbreaking-slated-for-april-19/ |archivedate=June 25, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Construction of 2013 attraction, [[Gold Striker]] (wooden coaster), in former Whizzer site.\n* 2011: Invertigo is removed to be sent to [[Dorney Park]]; Three new live shows. Halloween Haunt Expansion.\n* 2010: Planet Snoopy (Retheme of Nickelodeon Central); Hanna Barbera references removed in KidZville; Panda Express\n* 2009: All Wheels Extreme Stunt show; Chipper Lowell Experience show; expanded Halloween Haunt\n* 2008: Park is renamed to '''California's Great America'''; FireFall; Dora's Sing-Along Adventure; Endless Summer On Ice show; Halloween Haunt debuts\n* 2007: Park is renamed to '''Great America'''; Great Barrier Reef Wavepool added to Boomerang Bay; [[Ed Alonzo]] Misfit of Magic; Twistin' to the '60s Show\n* 2006: Tiki Twirl (Formerly Survivor: The Ride); Park is sold to Cedar Fair\n* 2005: Boomerang Bay expansion to include lazy river, two other waterslides and a large swimming pool.\n* 2004: Boomerang Bay is added including a complex of children's water slides/play area, a 4-person adult raft/tube ride, a two-person inner-tube water slide and a fully enclosed two-person inner-tube water slide. Triple Play is removed\n* 2003: SpongeBob SquarePants 3-D in the Action Theater; [[Nickelodeon Central]] (expansion of Splat City); Stealth (flying steel coaster) is removed and sent to [[Carowinds]] as Nighthawk\n* 2002: Delirium; Flying Eagles; Greased Lightning (shuttle loop coaster) is removed; Time Capsule buried\n* 2001: Psycho Mouse; Celebration Swings; Thunder Raceway; Stan Lee's 7th Portal 3D/ Smash Factory in Action Theater\n* 2000: Stealth (flying steel coaster) opens to the public; Scenic Railroad and Skyhawk are removed\n* 1999: KidZVille; Tidal Wave renamed Greased Lightnin'; Stealth is constructed and tested all season; Logger's Run modified to allow construction of Stealth\n* 1998: Invertigo; James Bond: License to Thrill;<ref name=\"hq.usace.army.mil\"/> in the Paramount Action F/X Theater Yankee Clipper is removed\n* 1997: Xtreme Skyflyer; Triple Wheel (originally Sky Whirl) is removed\n* 1996: Drop Tower Scream Zone (Formerly Drop Zone Stunt Tower)\n* 1995: [[Nickelodeon Splat City]]; The Edge and Ameri- Go Round are removed.\n* 1994: Action Theater featuring Days of Thunder\n* 1993: Park is renamed '''Paramount's Great America'''; Flight Deck (Formerly Top Gun); Lobster is removed\n* 1992: KECO is acquired by Paramount, and renamed Paramount Parks; IMAX Pictorium Theater received a $1.5 million upgrade allowing it to screen 3-D films.\n* 1991: Vortex; Saskatchewan Scrambler is removed. \n* 1990: Whitewater Falls\n* 1989: Skyhawk; Park is acquired by KECO from the City of Santa Clara; Dolphin and Seal show and Cajun Carpet are removed.\n* 1988: Rip Roaring Rapids. Whizzer and Bottom's Up are removed\n* 1987: Woodstock Express (Formerly Blue Streak/ Green Slime Mine Car Coaster/ Runaway Reptar); Smurf Woods; Fort Fun; HMB Endeavor (Formerly known as The Revolution)\n* 1986: The Grizzly; Redwood Amphitheater with the ''Miami Sound Machine''\n* 1985: Park is renamed '''Great America.'''\n* 1984: Park is sold by Marriott corporation to the City of Santa Clara; management transfers to Kings Entertainment Company (KECO); Hilltopper is removed.\n* 1983: The Edge; Red Baron and Ladybugs are removed.\n* 1982: Atari Video Adventure\n* 1980: The Demon (remodeled from Turn of the Century); Gulf coaster is removed\n* 1979: Star Tower (formerly Sky Tower)\n* 1978: IMAX Pictorium Theater, with film ''Man Belongs to the Earth''\n* 1977: Tidal Wave\n* 1976: '''Marriott's Great America''' opens\n\n==On film and television==\n===Beverly Hills Cop III===\nThough appearing under the name \"Wonder World\", Paramount's Great America was used for exterior scenes of the theme park in the 1994 film ''[[Beverly Hills Cop III]]'' (itself released by Paramount Pictures) after [[Knott's Berry Farm]] declined filming rights.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/1993/voices/columns/cop-iii-displays-spectacle-for-wasserman-1117862394/ |title='Cop III' displays spectacle for Wasserman |author=Archerd, Army |author-link=Army Archerd |date=December 13, 1993 |work=Variety |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1994-05-25-9405240754-story.html |title='Cop III': Eddie rides again |author=Boyar, Jay |date=May 25, 1994 |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nWriter Steven E. de Souza originally wrote the story as more \"Die Hard in a theme park\". He was told that each of the rides he had designed would cost about $10 million to build and the whole film would cost about $70 million. When box office results for ''[[The Distinguished Gentleman]]'' came in, Paramount ordered the budget to be cut to $55 million.\n\nSome modifications were made to the Columbia Carousel and Vortex roller coaster. Most of the Sky Whirl/Triple Wheel stunts (renamed \"The Spider\" for the film) were filmed in a studio. To film the exterior scenes, the motors of the Triple Wheel were left unpowered; instead, to ensure the ride did not move too quickly, some cages were loaded with sandbags to unbalance the mechanism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ew.com/article/1994/06/10/eddie-murphys-dangerous-ride/ |title=Eddie Murphy's dangerous ride |author=Mannes, George |date=June 10, 1994 |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> In this scene, [[George Lucas]] has a small part as the man Axel cuts in front of to get on the ride, also known as 'disappointed man' (this can be seen in the credits). [[John Singleton]] and [[Martha Coolidge]] also made cameo appearances in the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940525&slug=1912261 |title='Cop III': Though Murphy's A Draw, There Oughta Be A Law |author=Shannon, Jeff |date=May 25, 1994 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany rides that were seen in the movie including Triple Play/Sky Whirl have since been removed. Also, the carousel at the back of the park (the Ameri-Go-Round, not the Columbia Carousel) was altered. The Ameri-Go-Round carousel has since been removed and Drop Zone is now in its place. The tunnels that supposedly ran under the park are a myth as well. No tunnels run under the park, as many thought after this was released.\n\nThe Alien Attack ride featured in the Wonder World theme park was in fact the \"Earthquake: The Big One attraction\" from the [[Universal Studios Florida]] theme park in [[Orlando, Florida]]. The \"aliens\" featured in the ride are suited actors (and not animatronic as suggested in the film) that closely resembled the Cylons from the original Battlestar Galactica.<ref name=TPI-131116>{{cite web |url=https://www.themeparkinsider.com/flume/201311/3778/ |title=Theme Park History: 10 top movies or TV shows filmed in theme parks |author=Potter, Derek |date=November 16, 2013 |website=Theme Park Insider |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other film and television===\n* Paramount's Great America was also used as the theme park [[Macaulay Culkin]] visits in the 1994 film ''[[Getting Even with Dad]]'' (not released by Paramount Pictures but rather [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://greatamericanthrills.net/2014/08/24/getting-even-with-dad-filmed-at-californias-great-america/ |title=Getting Even With Dad Filmed at California's Great America |author=Rowberry, Kris |date=August 24, 2014 |website=Great American Thrills |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n* The park's inverted steel coaster \"Top Gun\" (later renamed to \"Flight Deck\") was featured in a 2007 [[Excedrin]] commercial with music from [[The Stremes]].<ref>{{youtube |id=Nw-d5OZOWA0 |title=Excedrin TV Advert - Music by The Stremes}}</ref>\n* Marriott's Great America was used in the 1983 George Lucas and [[John Korty]] animated feature [[Twice Upon a Time (1983 film)|''Twice Upon A Time'']].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/58153 |title=Twice Upon a Time (1983) |publisher=AFI Catalog of Feature Films |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> It was used both as a background for animated scenes and for a short live-action shot at the end of the film.\n\n==Incidents==\n{{Main|Incidents at Cedar Fair parks}}\n* In 1980, a 13-year-old boy was killed and several others injured on the [[Whizzer (roller coaster)|Willard's Whizzer]] roller coaster. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/06/13/previous-accidents-at-great-america/|title=Previous accidents at Great America|last=Kaplan|first=Tracy|date=June 13, 2015|work=San Jose Mercury News|access-date=March 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In 1989, two boys intentionally jumped out of the Loggers' Run ride. One was killed and the other fell onto a platform and was injured.<ref name=\"abc7news.com: 7/12/07\">{{cite web |last=Rosales |first=Erik |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=local&id=5476441 |title=[Title lost before link went dead] |publisher=KGO-TV |date=2007-07-12 |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305235532/http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=local&id=5476441 |archivedate=March 5, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 1998, after riding [[Flight Deck (California's Great America)|Flight Deck]], a 24-year-old Spanish-speaking man, who could not read the English-language warning signs, entered a locked, gated area underneath the ride to retrieve his hat. He was hit by the foot of a passenger on the Flight Deck train and later died. The passenger suffered a broken leg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rideaccidents.com/1998.html |title=1998 News Archive: Roller coaster accident kills a man in California |publisher=Rideaccidents.com |date=September 7, 1998 |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420021129/http://rideaccidents.com/1998.html#sep7 |archivedate=April 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 1999, a 12-year-old boy fell to his death on '''Drop Tower''' after slipping from the ride's restraints, which were still locked at the end of the ride.<ref>{{cite news\n|publisher = Courier-Journal |date = June 23, 2007 |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?Date=20071129&Category=NEWS01&ArtNo=111290002&SectionCat=&Template=printart |title = Thrill ride lawsuits |accessdate =November 4, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rideaccidents.com/1999.html|title=Drop Zone death: no charges, no explanation|date=November 5, 1999|publisher=RideAccidents.com|accessdate=December 4, 2011|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420021130/http://www.rideaccidents.com/1999.html#nov5|archivedate=April 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* On July 12, 2007, a 4-year-old boy drowned in the Boomerang Bay's Great Barrier Reef [[wave pool]].<ref name=\"abc7news.com: 7/12/07\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc11.com/news/13672880/detail.html |title=4-Year-Old Drowns In California's Great America Wave Pool&nbsp;\u2013 News Story&nbsp;\u2013 KNTV &#124; San Francisco |publisher=Nbc11.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>\n* On June 12, 2015, a maintenance worker was critically injured after being struck in the head by a moving train on [[Flight Deck (California's Great America)|Flight Deck]]. A passenger sustained serious hand and leg injuries in the incident.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/california/ci_28306406/great-america-roller-coaster-accident-injures-two-people%7D%7D|title=Great America roller coaster accident injures two people|last1=Kaplan|first1=Tracy|last2=Nelson|first2=Katie|date=June 13, 2015|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n* On July 4, 2019, The Santa Clara PD were called near the entrance of the park where a woman was shot during the evening of the fireworks show. The victim was struck on the arm by a handgun. She did not suffer any serious injuries and was also treated at the scene. It was ruled as an altercation between two family groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Great-America-Shooting-Suspect-Still-at-Large-512279892.html|title=California's Great America Shooting Suspect Still at Large - NBC Bay Area|publisher=NBC Bay Area|first=Mandela|last=Linder|date=2019-07-05|accessdate=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n* On October 26, 2019, A group of teenagers sparked some firecrackers in the front gate causing guests to scramble, thinking it was a shooting. It was later determined to be due to a robbery. Concession stands within the park were also robbed by fleeing guests. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2019/10/29/details-released-on-false-shooting-report-panic-at-great-america-amusement-park/|title=Details Released On False Shooting Report, Panic At Great America Amusement Park|date=October 29, 2019|work=KPIX 5|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n* Michelson, Herb. (June 7, 1984). \"City will purchase Marriott's\". ''The Sacramento Bee'', p. A.\n* \"Santa Clara drops Great America pact\". (February 7, 1985). ''San Francisco Chronicle'', p.&nbsp;4.\n* Ewell, Miranda. (June 6, 1985). \"Santa Clara assumes ownership of Great America\". ''San Jose Mercury News'' (CA), p.&nbsp;8B.\n* Kava, Brad. (March 15, 1989). \"Great America reopens\". ''San Jose Mercury News'', p.&nbsp;1.\n* Eng, Sherri. (August 1, 1992). \"Paramount to buy Great America owner\". ''San Jose Mercury News'', p.&nbsp;1E.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://greatamericaparks.com/ Great America parks]&nbsp;\u2013 History of Marriott's Great America\n* {{RCDB|4541}}\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Santa+Clara,+CA&ll=37.395551,-121.972082&spn=0.010254,0.014473&t=k&hl=en Satellite view of the site]\n\n{{Cedar Fair}}\n{{California's Great America}}\n{{San Jose and Silicon Valley attractions}}\n{{Paramount Parks}}\n{{Amusement Parks & Theme Parks of California}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n[[Category:California's Great America| ]]\n[[Category:Cedar Fair amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in California]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Area amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Economy of Santa Clara, California]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Santa Clara, California]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1976]]\n", "name_user": "Latteboy50", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California%27s_Great_America"}
{"title_page": "Enggano language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Enggano\n|nativename=\n|states=[[Indonesia]]\n|region=[[Enggano Island]], off [[Sumatra]]\n|ethnicity=[[Enggano people|Enggano]]\n|speakers=700\n|date=2011\n|ref=<ref>Yoder (2011)</ref>\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam1 = [[Austronesian language|Austronesian]]\n|fam2 = [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3 = [[Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands languages|Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands]] ?\n|iso3=eno\n|glotto=engg1245\n|glottorefname=Enggano\n|map=Sumatra-Enggano.jpg\n|mapcaption=Enggano Island, in red\n|notice=IPA\n}}\n[[File:Wanita Sebagai Juru Damai Perang Antar Suku di Pulau Enggano - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Enggano female dancers]]\nThe '''Enggano language''', or '''Engganese''', is an [[Austronesian language|Austronesian]] language spoken on [[Enggano Island]] off the southwestern coast of Sumatra, Indonesia.\n\nEnggano is notable among the Austronesian languages of western [[Insular Southeast Asia]] because of many unusual sound changes, and a low number of words shared with other Austronesian languages. There is however general consensus among Austronesianists that Enggano belongs to the Austronesian language family.{{sfnp|Lafeber|1922}}<ref>Nothofer 1986.</ref><ref>Blust, R. A. (2013). ''The Austronesian Languages'', revised edition. Canberra: Pacific Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, Australian National University.</ref>{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=90}}{{sfnp|Smith|2017}} Failure to fully identify the inherited Austronesian elements in the basic lexicon and bound morphology of Enggano resulted in occasional proposals that Enggano might be a [[language isolate]] which had adopted Austronesian loanwords.<ref name=Capell>Capell, Arthur, 1982. 'Local Languages in the PAN Area'. In Reiner Carle et al. ed., ''Gava\u2018: Studies in Austronesian languages and cultures dedicated to Hans K\u00e4hler'', trans. Geoffrey Sutton, 1-15, p. 4.</ref><ref name=Blench>Blench, Roger. 2014. The Enggano: archaic foragers and their interactions with the Austronesian world. m.s.</ref>\n\nWhen first contacted by Europeans, the [[Enggano people]] had more cultural commonalities with indigenous peoples of the [[Nicobar Islands]] than those of with Austronesian Sumatra. For instance, beehive houses were typical of both Enggano Island and the Nicobar Islands. However, there are no apparent linguistic connections with [[Nicobarese language|Nicobarese]] or other [[Austroasiatic languages]].\n\n==Classification==\nThe classification of Enggano is controversial,{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=54\u201355}} ranging from proposals that negate its inclusion in the Austronesian family all the way to classifications that place Enggano in the [[Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands languages|Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands]] subgroup together with other [[Austronesian languages]] of the area (e.g. [[Nias language|Nias]]). \n\nBased on the low number of apparent Austronesian cognates, Capell (1982) concludes that Enggano is a [[language isolate]] rather than Austronesian as previously assumed.<ref name=Capell/> Blench (2014)<ref name=Blench/> considers Enggano to be a [[language isolate]] that has picked up Austronesian loanwords, and notes many basic vocabulary items in Enggano are of non-Austronesian origin. Based on lexical evidence from the Enggano language, he considers the Enggano people to be descendants of [[Pleistocene]] (pre-Neolithic) [[hunter-gatherer]]s that had preceded the [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesians]].\n\nEdwards (2015) demonstrates that pronouns, numerals and many affixes in Enggano can be directly derived from [[Proto-Malayo-Polynesian language|Proto-Malayo-Polynesian]].{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=70\u201379}} Based on this evidence, together with regular sound changes from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian to Enggano, Edwards concludes that Enggano clearly belongs to the [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] branch of the Austronesian languages. Within Malayo-Polynesian, he considers Enggano to be a primary branch.{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=93}}\n\nEdwards thus rejects Capell's and Blench's proposal that Enggano is a non-Austronesian language with Austronesian loanwords, and considers it to be clearly Austronesian. While a large portion of its lexicon obviously cannot be derived from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian, it remains unclear whether this represents a non-Austronesian [[substratum]] from an unknown source language, or the result of internal lexical replacement.{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=91\u201392}}. He notes that Enggano possesses many aberrant phonological features (such as a small phonological inventory) and a low lexical retention rate, which is more typical of Austronesian languages spoken in eastern Indonesia and Melanesia than rather than those of western Indonesia. Enggano's lexical retention rate (i.e., percentage of lexical items that are cognate with reconstructed [[Proto-Austronesian language|Proto-Austronesian]] forms) is only 21% (46 out of 217 words), while the lexical retention rate for [[Malay language|Malay]] is 59% (132.5 out of 223 words).{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=76}} Some non-Austronesian languages in Southeast Asia, such as [[Nancowry language|Nancowry]], [[Semelai language|Semelai]], and [[Abui language|Abui]] also have low lexical retention rates.{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=76}}\n\n==Evolution==\nEnggano has historically undergone [[nasal harmony]] in its identifiable Austronesian vocabulary, where all [[stop consonant|stop consonants]] and vowels in a word became nasal after a nasal vowel, and oral after an oral vowel, so that there is no longer a phonemic distinction between them. For example, *e\u0169\u2019ada\u2019a became ''e\u0169\u2019\u00e3n\u00e3\u2019\u00e3'', while nasal consonants are no longer found in ''\u2019ub'' 'house' or ''\u2019a-rib'' 'five' (cf. Malay ''rumah, lima'').\n\nEnggano is the only western Austronesian language in which *t shifted to {{IPA|/k/}}, an unusual change that occurred independently several times in [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] after *k shifted to [[glottal stop]].{{sfnp|Blust|2004|p=383}}\n\n== Phonology ==\nThe only major linguistic treatment of Enggano was conducted by Hans K\u00e4hler in 1937; he published a grammar (1940), texts, and a dictionary (1987). However, phonology is limited to a simple inventory and a short paragraph of basic features; the grammar and dictionary disagree with each other, the dictionary is not consistent, some words are not legible, and doubts have been raised about the accuracy of the transcriptions. Nothofer (1992) discusses loanwords and also lists phonemes.<ref name=\"Nothofer\">Nothofer, 1986, p. 97, after K\u00e4hler (1940).</ref> Yoder (2011) is a thesis on Enggano vowels, with some comments on consonants; it will be followed here.<ref>[http://www.und.edu/dept/linguistics/theses/2011Yoder.PDF Yoder, 2011.]</ref>\n\nStress was once reported to be penultimate but appears to occur on the final syllable. Alternating syllables preceding it have secondary stress.\n\nYoder and Nothofer report seven oral and seven nasal vowels:<ref>K\u00e4hler's dictionary is similar, but lacks {{IPA|/\u0268 \u0268\u0303/}}.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\" \n|- align=\"center\" \n!\n! front\n! central\n! back\n|- align=\"center\"\n! close\n| i \u0129\n| \u0268 \u0268\u0303\n| u \u0169\n|- align=\"center\"\n! mid\n| e \u1ebd\n| \u0258 \u0258\u0303\n| o \u00f5\n|- align=\"center\"\n! open\n| colspan=2| a \u00e3 \n|  \n|}\nDiphthongs are {{IPA|/ai, a\u0268, au, ei, \u0258i, oi/}}.\n\nVowels do not occur word-initially in Enggano apart from what Yoder analyzes as {{IPA|/i u/}} before another vowel; these are then pronounced as semivowels {{IPA|[j w]}}. (Nothofer counts these as consonants {{IPA|/j, w/}} restricted to initial position, which avoids the problem of not uncommon {{IPA|[ji]}} being analyzed as {{IPA|/ii/}}, when sequences of the same vowel are  otherwise quite rare.) The vowels {{IPA|/i \u0268 u e o/}} are all pronounced as semivowels in vowel sequences after medial glottal consonants {{IPA|/\u0294 h/}}, as in {{IPA|/k\u00f5\u0294\u0129\u00e3/ [k\u00f5\u0294j\u00e3]}} (a sp. tree) and {{IPA|/bohoe/ [boho\u032fe]}} 'wild'; otherwise, apart from diphthongs, vowel sequences are disyllabic, as in {{IPA|/\u0294a-piah/ [\u0294api.ah]}} 'to graze'. {{IPA|/i/}} optionally triggers a glide after a following glottal consonant, as in {{IPA|/ki-\u0294u/ [ki\u0294u ~ ki\u0294ju]}} 'to say'. Diphthongs lower to {{IPA|[a\u026a, a\u028a]}} etc. before a coda stop, as in {{IPA|/kipa\u0294\u00e3\u0169p/ [k\u0129p\u00e3\u0294\u00e3\u028a\u0303p]}} 'ten', and undergo metathesis when that stop is glottal, as in {{IPA|/kahai\u0294 kak/ [kaha\u0294\u026akak]}} 'twenty'. An [[intrusive vowel]] {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306]}} appears between glottal stop and another consonant (though not semivowels), as in {{IPA|/ka\u0294h\u0268\u0258/ [ka\u0294.\u0259\u0306.h\u0268.\u0258]}} 'female leader'; this does not affect the pattern of stress.\n\nIn many words, a final vowel transcribed by K\u00e4hler is not found in Yoder.\n\nThe offglide of diphthongs lowers before glottal consonants, and a glottal stop may intrude when another word follows, as in {{IPA|/kahai\u0294 m\u0258h/}} {{IPA|[kaha\u0294\u026am\u0258\u0303h]}} 'another'.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n! \n! Bilabial\n! Alveolar\n! Palatal\n! Velar \n! Glottal\n|- align=\"center\"\n! Voiceless stop\n| p \n| t\n| \n| k \n| \u0294 \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Voiced stop\n| b ~ m\n| d ~ n\n| \n|   \n| \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Fricative\n| \n| colspan=3| &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; s &nbsp; ~ &nbsp; \u00e7 &nbsp; ~ &nbsp; x\n| h \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Trill\n| \n| r ~ n\n| \n|  \n|  \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Approximant\n| \n| (l) \n| j ?\n| w ?\n|  \n|}\nYoder notes that the voiced stops {{IPA|[b~m, d~n]}} are in [[complementary distribution]], depending on whether the word has nasal vowels, but lists them separately. Voiced oral consonants, {{IPA|[b d l r]}}, do not occur in words with nasal consonants or vowels. Nasal consonants nasalize all vowels in a word, and there is therefore no contrast between {{IPA|[m n]}} and {{IPA|[b d]}} apart from the contrast between nasal and oral vowels. For example, with the oral stem ''tax'' 'bag', the possessive forms are ''tahi\u2019'' 'my bag' and ''tahib'' 'your bag', but with the nasal stem 'age', the forms are ''\u2019umunu\u2019'' 'my age' and ''\u2019umunum'' 'your age'.\n\n{{IPA|/l/}} occurs in only a few native words. {{IPA|/s ~ x/}} are infrequent and apparently a single phoneme; they only occur word finally, where they contrast with {{IPA|/h/}}: {{IPA|[x]}} occurs after the non-front vowels {{IPA|/\u0268 \u0259 u/}}, {{IPA|[\u00e7]}} after the front vowels {{IPA|/i a \u00e3/}}, and {{IPA|[s]}} after vowel sequences ending in {{IPA|/i/}} (including {{IPA|/ii, ui/}}). The resulting {{IPA|[a\u00e7 \u00e3\u00e7]}} may actually be {{IPA|/aix \u00e3\u0129x/}}, as most such words are attested with alternation like {{IPA|[ka\u00e7 ~ kais]}} 'box'. When a suffix is added, so that this consonant is no longer word-final, it becomes {{IPA|/h/}}, as in ''tahi\u2019'' 'my bag' above.\n\nNothofer is similar, but does not list the uncommon consonants {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/s ~ x/}} and counts {{IPA|[j w]}} as consonants rather than allophones of vowels. K\u00e4hler's dictionary adds {{IPA|/\u0272/}}, as well as {{IPA|/f t\u0283 d\u0292/}} as marginal phonemes, and claims that {{IPA|/t r/}} are only found in southern villages. However, Yoder states that at the time of his research in 2010 there were no differences among the six villages on Enggano Island, and that initial {{IPA|/t r/}} and final {{IPA|/t d/}} are rare in native words. Medial {{IPA|/d/}} and {{IPA|/r/}} are in free variation in a few words, with older people preferring {{IPA|/d/}} and younger speakers {{IPA|/r/}}.\n\n==Grammar==\nThe main reference on the syntax and morphology of the Enggano language is the grammar produced by the German scholar Hans K\u00e4hler, which was published in 1940.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940}} There are also some references to syntax and morphology in more recent work, such as Yoder (2011) and Edwards (2015). This section compares some of the findings in K\u00e4hler (1940) with those of Yoder (2011), where the language appears to have undergone some changes.\n\n=== Pronouns ===\nThe pronouns listed in K\u00e4hler (1940) are as follows:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=106}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Pronoun !! Independent\n!Enclitic \n!Proclitic I\n!Proclitic II\n|-\n| 1sg ||\u2019ua\n| -'u\n|'u-\n|'u-\n|-\n| 1du.{{sc|INCL}}||\u2019ika\n| -ka\n| ka-\n| ka-\n|-\n|1pl.{{sc|INCL}}\n|'ika'a\n| -ka'a\n| ka- -a'a\n| ka- -a'a\n|-\n|1pl.{{sc|EXCL}}\n|'ai\n| -dai, -n\u00e3\u0129\n|'u- -'ai\n|'u- -'ai\n|-\n| 2sg ||\u2019o'o\n| -bu, -m\u0169\n| u-\n| 'o-\n|-\n| 2pl ||adiu\n| -du, -n\u0169\n| u- -a'a\n| 'o- -a'a\n|-\n| 3sg ||kia\n| -dia, -n\u0129\u00e3\n| i-\n| ka-\n|-\n| 3pl ||ki\n| -da, -n\u00e3\n| da-\n| ki-/di-\n|}\nK\u00e4hler notes that the form ''<nowiki/>'ika'a'' is not often used and that ''<nowiki/>'ika'' can have both dual (speaker + addressee) and plural (speaker + multiple addressees) reference.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=88}} Enclitic pronouns, which typically express [[Possession (linguistics)|possessors]], are subject nasal harmony, depending on whether the root that they attach to contains nasal or oral vowels. There is also a phonological process whereby a vowel is inserted between the [[glottal stop]] and the u in the 1sg enclitic ''-'u''. This is the final vowel of the stem to which the suffix attaches, e.g. ''euba'' 'house' > ''euba'au'' 'my house', ''ebohe'' 'spear' > ''ebohe'eu'' 'my {{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=96}} Possession can also be indicated using the proclitic pronouns above.\n\nThe pronouns listed in Yoder (2011) are as follows:\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|+Enggano pronouns\n|-\n! Pronoun !! Independent !! Suffix\n|-\n| 1sg ||\u2019u || -\u2019\n|-\n| we.{{sc|EXCL}} ||\u2019a ||\n|-\n| we.{{sc|INCL}} ||\u2019ik || -k\n|-\n| 2sg ||\u2019\u0259\u2019 || -b ~ -m\n|-\n| 2pl ||\u2019ari || -du ~ -nu\n|-\n| 3sg ||ki || rowspan=2| -d(e) ~ -n(e)\n|-\n| 3pl ||ham\u0259\u2019 \n|-\n| this ||(p\u1ebd)\u2019\u1ebd\u2019\n|-\n| that ||\u2019\u1ebd\u00f5\u2019\n|-\n| who ||h\u00e3\n|-\n| what ||\u2019i.ah\n|}\nMost of these appear to be Austronesian: Compare Malay 1sg ''aku ~ ku'', 1.{{sc|ex}} ''kami'', 1.{{sc|in}} ''kita'', 2pl ''kalian'', 3sg/pl ''dia'', and suffixes 1sg ''-ku'', 2sg ''-mu'', 3sg ''-nya'', with *k, *t (d), *l, *m, *n having shifted to ''\u2019, k, r, b, d'' in Enggano, and with final consonants and (where possible) vowels being lost. The possessive suffixes appear on nouns, and they are often preceded by a vowel. Few forms are attested, but this vowel is ''i'' or ''ai'' after {{IPA|[\u00e7]}} (as with 'bag' in the phonology section), an [[echo vowel]] after several other consonants, and with several words not predictable on current evidence: ''\u2019eam \u2013 \u2019ami\u2019'' '(my) fishing rod'.\n\n=== Nouns ===\nNouns in Enggano can be subcategorised into three different classes: humans, proper nouns and common nouns. They take different articles to indicate singular and plural reference:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=85}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Articles in Enggano\n!Noun Class\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n|Human\n|e-\n|ka-\n|-\n|Proper\n|\u2205-\n|\u2205-\n|-\n|Common\n|e-\n|e-\n|}\nBlench notes that ''e-'' may be a [[determiner (linguistics)|determiner]]<ref name=\"Blench\" /> and Edwards argues that the articles not only mark [[noun class]] but also [[Grammatical case|case]].{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=60\u201361}} Nouns marked with ''e-'' and the other articles above can express both subjects and objects. The prefix ''e-'' can also be used to derive [[Gerund|gerunds]] from verbal stems.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940}} Plural number can also be indicated through [[reduplication]].{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=87}} In this case, the meaning is exhaustive, e.g. all of the nouns.\n\nNouns with an oblique function, e.g. those expressing nominal possessors, subjects of gerunds and any noun that follows the [[Oblique argument|oblique]] marker ''i'ioo'', take the article ''u-'' in place of ''e-''. Finally, [[Locative case|locative nouns]] take the locative prefix ''i-''.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940}}\n\nNouns in Enggano can be modified by demonstratives and relative clauses. As in other Austronesian languages, these typically follow the nominal head. There are three demonstratives in Enggano:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=92}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Demonstratives in Enggano\n!Demonstrative\n!Enggano\n!Rough Translation\n|-\n|Proximal\n|ei'ie\n|this\n|-\n|Medial\n|e'ana\n|that\n|-\n|Distal\n|ea'a\n|that\n|}\nRelative clauses are introduced by a relativiser ''m\u00f5'\u00f5''. K\u00e4hler suggests that older speakers of Enggano would use different relativisers depending on whether the head noun was singular (''hem\u00f5\u2019\u00f5'') or plural (''h\u00f5m\u00f5\u2019\u00f5''). However, in 1937 when he was conducting research, this practice was already uncommon in everyday language.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=93}} An example of a relative clause in Enggano is given below. This shows that demonstratives also follow relative clauses:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=93}}\n<br />\n{|\n|(1)\n|ka'u'ua-da'a\n|e-uba\n|m\u00f5'\u00f5\n|'am\u0169h\u00f5\n|ei'ie\n|-\n|\n|beautiful-<small>PRED</small>\n|<small>ART</small>-house\n|<small>REL</small>\n|big\n|<small>PROX.DEM</small>\n|-\n|\n| colspan=\"5\" |'This house which is big is beautiful'\n|}\n\nK\u00e4hler describes some processes of [[Morphological derivation|nominal derivation]] in Enggano. Specifically, he notes that instrumental nouns can be formed via the addition of a vowel or ''paV-'' to a verbal root, e.g. ''poko'' 'to chisel' > ''e-opoko'' 'a chisel' or ''kui'' 'to sew' > ''e-paukui'' 'needle'. Locative nouns are formed with an ''-a'' suffix, e.g. ''parudu'' 'gather' > ''e-parudu-a'' 'gathering place'.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|pp=316\u2013318}}\n\n=== Verbs and Adjectives ===\nAdjectives commonly have prefixes ''ka-, ka\u2019-, ki-''; the first two are attested in derivation, and the last is assumed as it is very common and many such adjectives otherwise appear to be reduplicated, as in ''kinanap'' 'smooth' (Yoder 2011).\n\nVerbs may have one or two prefixes and sometimes a suffix. Attested prefixes are ''ba-, ba\u2019-, ia-, iah-, ka-, ka\u2019-, kah-, ki-, kir-, ko-, pa-, pah-, \u2019a-.'' The functions of these are unknown. ''Ki-'' and ''pa-'' may occur together, as in ''pe, pape, kipe, kipape'', all glossed as 'give'. The three attested verbal suffixes are ''-i, -ar, -a\u2019'' (Yoder 2011).\n\n=== Numerals ===\nThe counting system is, or at least once was, [[vigesimal]]: K\u00e4hler recorded ''kahai'i ekaka'' 'one man' = 20, ''ariba ekaka'' 'five man' = 100, ''kahai'i edudodoka'' 'one our-body' = 400. (The last may be based on two people counting together: each time I count all twenty of my digits, you count one of yours, so that when you have counted all of your digits, the number is 20\u00d720 = 400.) However, most people now use Malay numerals when speaking Enggano, especially for higher numbers. Yoder (2011) recorded the following:<ref>Also found [https://web.archive.org/web/20101230153201/http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/Enggano.htm here]</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n! Numeral !! Enggano \n|-\n| 1|| kahai\u2019 \n|-\n| 2|| \u2019aru \n|-\n| 3|| \u2019ak\u0259r\n|-\n| 4|| \u2019aup\n|-\n| 5|| \u2019arib \n|-\n| 6|| \u2019aki\u2019akin\n|-\n| 7|| \u2019arib he \u2019aru \n|-\n| 8|| k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p, \u2019\u00e3p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p\n|-\n| 9|| k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p kabai kahai\u2019, \u2019\u00e3p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p \u2019abai kahai\u2019 \n|-\n| 10|| k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p\n|-\n| 20|| kahai\u2019 kak\n|}\n1\u20135 are Austronesian, assuming ''ka-'' is a prefix on 'one' and ''\u2019a-'' is a prefix on 2\u20135. Compare the remaining ''-hai\u2019, -ru, -k\u0259r, -up, -rib'' with [[Lampung language|Lampung]] ''\u0259say, rua, t\u0259lu, \u0259pat, lima''; *s, *t, *l, *m have shifted to ''h, k, r, b'' in Enggano, and final consonants and (simple) vowels have been lost. \n''\u2019aki\u2019akin'' 6 may be reduplication of ''\u2019ak\u0259r'' 3. ''\u2019arib he \u2019aru'' 7 is 'five and two'. The two forms for 8 mean 'hugging', from the verb ''p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p'' 'to hug', and 9 appears to be 'eight, one coming'; it may be shortened to ''kaba kahai\u2019'' (no ''-i'') in enumeration. Yoder believes 10 may also be a verb, based on an unelicited root ''\u2019\u00e3\u0169p'', as ''ki-'' and ''pa-'' are verbal prefixes (as in ''ki-pa-pe'' 'to give'); indeed, the apparent prefixes on 1\u20135 are identical to verbal prefixes as well.\n\nNumbers above 10 and 20 are formed with ''he ~ hi'' 'and': ''k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p he \u2019aru'' 'ten and two' for 12, ''kahai\u2019 kak he k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p'' 'twenty and ten' for 30. ''kak'' is 'person', so twenty is 'one person'. Multiples of twenty are formed from ''kak'', as in ''\u2019ak\u0259r kak he k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p'' 70, ''\u2019arib kak'' 100 (also ''kahai\u2019 ratuh'' from Malay ''ratus'').\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Blench, Roger, ''The Enggano: archaic foragers and their interactions with the Austronesian world.'' Draft 11th August, 2014.\n* {{cite journal |last=Blust |first=Robert |year=2004 |title=*t to k: An Austronesian sound change revisited |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages=365\u2013410 |jstor=3623363 |ref=harv}}\n* Capell, Arthur, ''Bezirkssprachen im gebiet des UAN''. In Gava\u2019: Studies in Austronesian languages and cultures dedicated to Hans K\u00e4hler, ed. by Rainer Carle, Martina Heinschke, Peter Pink, Christel Rost, and Karen Stadtlander, 1\u201314, Berlin, Dietrich Reimer, 1982.\n* {{cite journal |last=Edwards |first=Owen |year=2015 |title=The Position of Enggano within Austronesian |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=54-109 |hdl=1885/114506 |ref=harv}}\n* Helfrich, O. L., ''Aanvullingen en verbeteringen op de Maleisch\u2013Nederlansch\u2013Enganeesch woordenlijst.'' Tijdschrift voor Indische Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde 35:228\u201333, 1893.\n* {{cite journal |last=K\u00e4hler |first=Hans |year=1940 |title=Grammatischer Abriss des Enggano |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Eingeborenen-Sprachen |volume=30 |pages=81\u2013117, 182\u2013210, 296\u2013320 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lafeber |first=Abraham |title=Vergelijkende klankleer van het Niasisch |year=1922 |location=s'-Gravenhage |publisher=Hadi Poestaka |url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=MMKB02A:000030153:00001 |ref=harv}}\n* Nothofer, Bernd, ''The Barrier Island Languages in the Austronesian Language Family'', Focal II: Papers From the Fourth International Conference on Austronesian Linguistics, pp.&nbsp;87\u2013109, Pacific Linguistics, Series C, No. 94, Canberra, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, The Australian National University, 1986. {{hdl|1885/145382}} {{doi|10.15144/PL-C94}}\n* Nothofer, Bernd, ''Lehnw\u00f6rter Im Enggano'', In K\u00f6lner Beitr\u00e4ge Aus Malaiologie Und Ethnologie Zu Ehren Von Professor Dr. Irene Hilgers-Hesse, ed. F. Schulze and Kurt Tauchmann, K\u00f6lner S\u00fcdostasien Studien 1, Bonn: Holos, 1992\n* Nothofer, Bernd, ''The relationship between the languages of the Barrier Islands and the Sulawesi-Philippine languages''. In Language contact and change in the Austronesian world, ed. by Tom Dutton and Darrell Tryon, 389\u2013409, Berlin, Mouton de Gruyter, 1994.\n* {{cite journal |last=Smith |first=Alexander D. |year=2017 |title=The Western Malayo-Polynesian Problem |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages=435-490 |ref=harv}}\n* Yoder, Brendon, ''Phonological and phonetic aspects of Enggano vowels'', MA thesis, University of North Dakota, 2011 [https://arts-sciences.und.edu/academics/summer-institute-of-linguistics/theses/_files/docs/2011-yoder-brendon-e.pdf]\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Adelaar, Alexander, ''The Austronesian Languages of Asia and Madagascar: A Historical Perspective'', The Austronesian Languages of Asia and Madagascar, pp.&nbsp;1\u201342, Routledge Language Family Series, London, Routledge, 2005\n* Dyen, Isidore, ''A lexicostatistical classification of the Austronesian languages''. Indiana University Publications in Anthropology and Linguistics, 1965.\n* Goesmali, S.Z, et al, ''Morfofonemik bahasa Enggano,'' Padang, Pusat Penelitian Universitas Andalas. Laporan Penelitian, 1989.\n* Oudemans, J. A. C, ''Woordenlijst van de talen van Enggano, Mentawei en Nias,'' Tijdschrift voor Indische Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde 25:484\u201388, 1879.\n* K\u00e4hler, Hans, ''Texte von der Insel Enggano (Berichte \u00fcber eine untergehende Kultur)'', Berlin, Dietrich Reimer, 1975.\n* K\u00e4hler, Hans, ''Enggano-deutsches W\u00f6rterbuch'', Veroffentlichungen Des Seminars Fur Indonesische Und Sudseesprachen Der Universitat Hamburg, Hamburg: Dietrich Reimer, 1987.\n* Kaslim, Yuslina, et al, ''Pemetaan bahasa daerah di Sumatra Barat dan Bengkulu'', Jakarta: Pusat Pembinaan dan Pengembangan Bahasa, 1987\n* Nikelas, Syahwin, et al. ''Morfologi dan Sintaksis Bahasa Enggano,'' Jakarta, Pusat Pembinaan dan Pengembangan Bahasa, 1994.\n* van de Noord, A., ''Enggano'', In Holle lists: Vocabularies in languages of Indonesia, ed. by W. Stokhof, vol. 10/3, 189\u2013205, Canberra, Pacific Linguistics, 1987. {{hdl|1885/144589}} {{doi|10.15144/PL-D76}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721180840/http://www.rogerblench.info/Language%20data/Austronesian/Enggano/Enggano%20page.htm Language materials on Enggano]\n* [https://www.ethnologue.com/language/eno Enggano at Ethnologue]\n{{Languages of Indonesia}}\n{{Austronesian languages}}\n\n[[Category:Enggano language| ]]\n[[Category:Languages of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Sumatran languages]]\n[[Category:Unclassified languages of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Enggano\n|nativename=\n|states=[[Indonesia]]\n|region=[[Enggano Island]], off [[Sumatra]]\n|ethnicity=[[Enggano people|Enggano]]\n|speakers=700\n|date=2011\n|ref=<ref>Yoder (2011)</ref>\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam1 = [[Austronesian language|Austronesian]]\n|fam2 = [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3 = [[Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands languages|Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands]] ?\n|iso3=eno\n|glotto=engg1245\n|glottorefname=Enggano\n|map=Sumatra-Enggano.jpg\n|mapcaption=Enggano Island, in red\n|notice=IPA\n}}\n[[File:Wanita Sebagai Juru Damai Perang Antar Suku di Pulau Enggano - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Enggano female dancers]]\nThe '''Enggano language''', or '''Engganese''', is an [[Austronesian language|Austronesian]] language spoken on [[Enggano Island]] off the southwestern coast of Sumatra, Indonesia.\n\nEnggano is notable among the Austronesian languages of western [[Insular Southeast Asia]] because of many unusual sound changes, and a low number of words shared with other Austronesian languages. There is however general consensus among Austronesianists that Enggano belongs to the Austronesian language family.{{sfnp|Lafeber|1922}}<ref>Nothofer 1986.</ref><ref>Blust, R. A. (2013). ''The Austronesian Languages'', revised edition. Canberra: Pacific Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, Australian National University.</ref>{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=90}}{{sfnp|Smith|2017}} Failure to fully identify the inherited Austronesian elements in the basic lexicon and bound morphology of Enggano resulted in occasional proposals that Enggano might be a [[language isolate]] which had adopted Austronesian loanwords.<ref name=Capell>Capell, Arthur, 1982. 'Local Languages in the PAN Area'. In Reiner Carle et al. ed., ''Gava\u2018: Studies in Austronesian languages and cultures dedicated to Hans K\u00e4hler'', trans. Geoffrey Sutton, 1-15, p. 4.</ref><ref name=Blench>Blench, Roger. 2014. The Enggano: archaic foragers and their interactions with the Austronesian world. m.s.</ref>\n\nWhen first contacted by Europeans, the [[Enggano people]] had more cultural commonalities with indigenous peoples of the [[Nicobar Islands]] than those of with Austronesian Sumatra. For instance, beehive houses were typical of both Enggano Island and the Nicobar Islands. However, there are no apparent linguistic connections with [[Nicobarese language|Nicobarese]] or other [[Austroasiatic languages]].\n\n==Classification==\nThe classification of Enggano is controversial,{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=54\u201355}} ranging from proposals that negate its inclusion in the Austronesian family all the way to classifications that place Enggano in the [[Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands languages|Northwest Sumatra\u2013Barrier Islands]] subgroup together with other [[Austronesian languages]] of the area (e.g. [[Nias language|Nias]]). \n\nBased on the low number of apparent Austronesian cognates, Capell (1982) concludes that Enggano is a [[language isolate]] rather than Austronesian as previously assumed.<ref name=Capell/> Blench (2014)<ref name=Blench/> considers Enggano to be a [[language isolate]] that has picked up Austronesian loanwords, and notes many basic vocabulary items in Enggano are of non-Austronesian origin. Based on lexical evidence from the Enggano language, he considers the Enggano people to be descendants of [[Pleistocene]] (pre-Neolithic) [[hunter-gatherer]]s that had preceded the [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesians]].\n\nEdwards (2015) demonstrates that pronouns, numerals and many affixes in Enggano can be directly derived from [[Proto-Malayo-Polynesian language|Proto-Malayo-Polynesian]].{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=70\u201379}} Based on this evidence, together with regular sound changes from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian to Enggano, Edwards concludes that Enggano clearly belongs to the [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] branch of the Austronesian languages. Within Malayo-Polynesian, he considers Enggano to be a primary branch.{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=93}}\n\nEdwards thus rejects Capell's and Blench's proposal that Enggano is a non-Austronesian language with Austronesian loanwords, and considers it to be clearly Austronesian. While a large portion of its lexicon obviously cannot be derived from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian, it remains unclear whether this represents a non-Austronesian [[substratum]] from an unknown source language, or the result of internal lexical replacement.{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=91\u201392}}. He notes that Enggano possesses many aberrant phonological features (such as a small phonological inventory) and a low lexical retention rate, which is more typical of Austronesian languages spoken in eastern Indonesia and Melanesia than rather than those of western Indonesia. Enggano's lexical retention rate (i.e., percentage of lexical items that are cognate with reconstructed [[Proto-Austronesian language|Proto-Austronesian]] forms) is only 21% (46 out of 217 words), while the lexical retention rate for [[Malay language|Malay]] is 59% (132.5 out of 223 words).{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=76}} Some non-Austronesian languages in Southeast Asia, such as [[Nancowry language|Nancowry]], [[Semelai language|Semelai]], and [[Abui language|Abui]] also have low lexical retention rates.{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|p=76}}\n\n==Evolution==\nEnggano has historically undergone [[nasal harmony]] in its identifiable Austronesian vocabulary, where all [[stop consonant|stop consonants]] and vowels in a word became nasal after a nasal vowel, and oral after an oral vowel, so that there is no longer a phonemic distinction between them. For example, *e\u0169\u2019ada\u2019a became ''e\u0169\u2019\u00e3n\u00e3\u2019\u00e3'', while nasal consonants are no longer found in ''\u2019ub'' 'house' or ''\u2019a-rib'' 'five' (cf. Malay ''rumah, lima''). Enggano is the only western Austronesian language in which *t shifted to {{IPA|/k/}}, an unusual change that occurred independently several times in [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] after *k shifted to [[glottal stop]].{{sfnp|Blust|2004|p=383}}\n\n== Phonology ==\nThe only major linguistic treatment of Enggano was conducted by Hans K\u00e4hler in 1937; he published a grammar (1940), texts, and a dictionary (1987). However, phonology is limited to a simple inventory and a short paragraph of basic features; the grammar and dictionary disagree with each other, the dictionary is not consistent, some words are not legible, and doubts have been raised about the accuracy of the transcriptions. Nothofer (1992) discusses loanwords and also lists phonemes.<ref name=\"Nothofer\">Nothofer, 1986, p. 97, after K\u00e4hler (1940).</ref> Yoder (2011) is a thesis on Enggano vowels, with some comments on consonants; it will be followed here.<ref>[http://www.und.edu/dept/linguistics/theses/2011Yoder.PDF Yoder, 2011.]</ref>\n\nStress was once reported to be penultimate but appears to occur on the final syllable. Alternating syllables preceding it have secondary stress.\n\nYoder and Nothofer report seven oral and seven nasal vowels:<ref>K\u00e4hler's dictionary is similar, but lacks {{IPA|/\u0268 \u0268\u0303/}}.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\" \n|- align=\"center\" \n!\n! front\n! central\n! back\n|- align=\"center\"\n! close\n| i \u0129\n| \u0268 \u0268\u0303\n| u \u0169\n|- align=\"center\"\n! mid\n| e \u1ebd\n| \u0258 \u0258\u0303\n| o \u00f5\n|- align=\"center\"\n! open\n| colspan=2| a \u00e3 \n|  \n|}\nDiphthongs are {{IPA|/ai, a\u0268, au, ei, \u0258i, oi/}}.\n\nVowels do not occur word-initially in Enggano apart from what Yoder analyzes as {{IPA|/i u/}} before another vowel; these are then pronounced as semivowels {{IPA|[j w]}}. (Nothofer counts these as consonants {{IPA|/j, w/}} restricted to initial position, which avoids the problem of not uncommon {{IPA|[ji]}} being analyzed as {{IPA|/ii/}}, when sequences of the same vowel are  otherwise quite rare.) The vowels {{IPA|/i \u0268 u e o/}} are all pronounced as semivowels in vowel sequences after medial glottal consonants {{IPA|/\u0294 h/}}, as in {{IPA|/k\u00f5\u0294\u0129\u00e3/ [k\u00f5\u0294j\u00e3]}} (a sp. tree) and {{IPA|/bohoe/ [boho\u032fe]}} 'wild'; otherwise, apart from diphthongs, vowel sequences are disyllabic, as in {{IPA|/\u0294a-piah/ [\u0294api.ah]}} 'to graze'. {{IPA|/i/}} optionally triggers a glide after a following glottal consonant, as in {{IPA|/ki-\u0294u/ [ki\u0294u ~ ki\u0294ju]}} 'to say'. Diphthongs lower to {{IPA|[a\u026a, a\u028a]}} etc. before a coda stop, as in {{IPA|/kipa\u0294\u00e3\u0169p/ [k\u0129p\u00e3\u0294\u00e3\u028a\u0303p]}} 'ten', and undergo metathesis when that stop is glottal, as in {{IPA|/kahai\u0294 kak/ [kaha\u0294\u026akak]}} 'twenty'. An [[intrusive vowel]] {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306]}} appears between glottal stop and another consonant (though not semivowels), as in {{IPA|/ka\u0294h\u0268\u0258/ [ka\u0294.\u0259\u0306.h\u0268.\u0258]}} 'female leader'; this does not affect the pattern of stress.\n\nIn many words, a final vowel transcribed by K\u00e4hler is not found in Yoder.\n\nThe offglide of diphthongs lowers before glottal consonants, and a glottal stop may intrude when another word follows, as in {{IPA|/kahai\u0294 m\u0258h/}} {{IPA|[kaha\u0294\u026am\u0258\u0303h]}} 'another'.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n! \n! Bilabial\n! Alveolar\n! Palatal\n! Velar \n! Glottal\n|- align=\"center\"\n! Voiceless stop\n| p \n| t\n| \n| k \n| \u0294 \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Voiced stop\n| b ~ m\n| d ~ n\n| \n|   \n| \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Fricative\n| \n| colspan=3| &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; s &nbsp; ~ &nbsp; \u00e7 &nbsp; ~ &nbsp; x\n| h \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Trill\n| \n| r ~ n\n| \n|  \n|  \n|- align=\"center\"\n! Approximant\n| \n| (l) \n| j ?\n| w ?\n|  \n|}\nYoder notes that the voiced stops {{IPA|[b~m, d~n]}} are in [[complementary distribution]], depending on whether the word has nasal vowels, but lists them separately. Voiced oral consonants, {{IPA|[b d l r]}}, do not occur in words with nasal consonants or vowels. Nasal consonants nasalize all vowels in a word, and there is therefore no contrast between {{IPA|[m n]}} and {{IPA|[b d]}} apart from the contrast between nasal and oral vowels. For example, with the oral stem ''tax'' 'bag', the possessive forms are ''tahi\u2019'' 'my bag' and ''tahib'' 'your bag', but with the nasal stem 'age', the forms are ''\u2019umunu\u2019'' 'my age' and ''\u2019umunum'' 'your age'.\n\n{{IPA|/l/}} occurs in only a few native words. {{IPA|/s ~ x/}} are infrequent and apparently a single phoneme; they only occur word finally, where they contrast with {{IPA|/h/}}: {{IPA|[x]}} occurs after the non-front vowels {{IPA|/\u0268 \u0259 u/}}, {{IPA|[\u00e7]}} after the front vowels {{IPA|/i a \u00e3/}}, and {{IPA|[s]}} after vowel sequences ending in {{IPA|/i/}} (including {{IPA|/ii, ui/}}). The resulting {{IPA|[a\u00e7 \u00e3\u00e7]}} may actually be {{IPA|/aix \u00e3\u0129x/}}, as most such words are attested with alternation like {{IPA|[ka\u00e7 ~ kais]}} 'box'. When a suffix is added, so that this consonant is no longer word-final, it becomes {{IPA|/h/}}, as in ''tahi\u2019'' 'my bag' above.\n\nNothofer is similar, but does not list the uncommon consonants {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/s ~ x/}} and counts {{IPA|[j w]}} as consonants rather than allophones of vowels. K\u00e4hler's dictionary adds {{IPA|/\u0272/}}, as well as {{IPA|/f t\u0283 d\u0292/}} as marginal phonemes, and claims that {{IPA|/t r/}} are only found in southern villages. However, Yoder states that at the time of his research in 2010 there were no differences among the six villages on Enggano Island, and that initial {{IPA|/t r/}} and final {{IPA|/t d/}} are rare in native words. Medial {{IPA|/d/}} and {{IPA|/r/}} are in free variation in a few words, with older people preferring {{IPA|/d/}} and younger speakers {{IPA|/r/}}.\n\n==Grammar==\nThe main reference on the syntax and morphology of the Enggano language is the grammar produced by the German scholar Hans K\u00e4hler, which was published in 1940.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940}} There are also some references to syntax and morphology in more recent work, such as Yoder (2011) and Edwards (2015). This section compares some of the findings in K\u00e4hler (1940) with those of Yoder (2011), where the language appears to have undergone some changes.\n\n=== Pronouns ===\nThe pronouns listed in K\u00e4hler (1940) are as follows:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=106}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Pronoun !! Independent\n!Enclitic \n!Proclitic I\n!Proclitic II\n|-\n| 1sg ||\u2019ua\n| -'u\n|'u-\n|'u-\n|-\n| 1du.{{sc|INCL}}||\u2019ika\n| -ka\n| ka-\n| ka-\n|-\n|1pl.{{sc|INCL}}\n|'ika'a\n| -ka'a\n| ka- -a'a\n| ka- -a'a\n|-\n|1pl.{{sc|EXCL}}\n|'ai\n| -dai, -n\u00e3\u0129\n|'u- -'ai\n|'u- -'ai\n|-\n| 2sg ||\u2019o'o\n| -bu, -m\u0169\n| u-\n| 'o-\n|-\n| 2pl ||adiu\n| -du, -n\u0169\n| u- -a'a\n| 'o- -a'a\n|-\n| 3sg ||kia\n| -dia, -n\u0129\u00e3\n| i-\n| ka-\n|-\n| 3pl ||ki\n| -da, -n\u00e3\n| da-\n| ki-/di-\n|}\nK\u00e4hler notes that the form ''<nowiki/>'ika'a'' is not often used and that ''<nowiki/>'ika'' can have both dual (speaker + addressee) and plural (speaker + multiple addressees) reference.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=88}} Enclitic pronouns, which typically express [[Possession (linguistics)|possessors]], are subject nasal harmony, depending on whether the root that they attach to contains nasal or oral vowels. There is also a phonological process whereby a vowel is inserted between the [[glottal stop]] and the u in the 1sg enclitic ''-'u''. This is the final vowel of the stem to which the suffix attaches, e.g. ''euba'' 'house' > ''euba'au'' 'my house', ''ebohe'' 'spear' > ''ebohe'eu'' 'my {{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=96}} Possession can also be indicated using the proclitic pronouns above.\n\nThe pronouns listed in Yoder (2011) are as follows:\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|+Enggano pronouns\n|-\n! Pronoun !! Independent !! Suffix\n|-\n| 1sg ||\u2019u || -\u2019\n|-\n| we.{{sc|EXCL}} ||\u2019a ||\n|-\n| we.{{sc|INCL}} ||\u2019ik || -k\n|-\n| 2sg ||\u2019\u0259\u2019 || -b ~ -m\n|-\n| 2pl ||\u2019ari || -du ~ -nu\n|-\n| 3sg ||ki || rowspan=2| -d(e) ~ -n(e)\n|-\n| 3pl ||ham\u0259\u2019 \n|-\n| this ||(p\u1ebd)\u2019\u1ebd\u2019\n|-\n| that ||\u2019\u1ebd\u00f5\u2019\n|-\n| who ||h\u00e3\n|-\n| what ||\u2019i.ah\n|}\nMost of these appear to be Austronesian: Compare Malay 1sg ''aku ~ ku'', 1.{{sc|ex}} ''kami'', 1.{{sc|in}} ''kita'', 2pl ''kalian'', 3sg/pl ''dia'', and suffixes 1sg ''-ku'', 2sg ''-mu'', 3sg ''-nya'', with *k, *t (d), *l, *m, *n having shifted to ''\u2019, k, r, b, d'' in Enggano, and with final consonants and (where possible) vowels being lost. The possessive suffixes appear on nouns, and they are often preceded by a vowel. Few forms are attested, but this vowel is ''i'' or ''ai'' after {{IPA|[\u00e7]}} (as with 'bag' in the phonology section), an [[echo vowel]] after several other consonants, and with several words not predictable on current evidence: ''\u2019eam \u2013 \u2019ami\u2019'' '(my) fishing rod'.\n\n=== Nouns ===\nNouns in Enggano can be subcategorised into three different classes: humans, proper nouns and common nouns. They take different articles to indicate singular and plural reference:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=85}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Articles in Enggano\n!Noun Class\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n|Human\n|e-\n|ka-\n|-\n|Proper\n|\u2205-\n|\u2205-\n|-\n|Common\n|e-\n|e-\n|}\nBlench notes that ''e-'' may be a [[determiner (linguistics)|determiner]]<ref name=\"Blench\" /> and Edwards argues that the articles not only mark [[noun class]] but also [[Grammatical case|case]].{{sfnp|Edwards|2015|pp=60\u201361}} Nouns marked with ''e-'' and the other articles above can express both subjects and objects. The prefix ''e-'' can also be used to derive [[Gerund|gerunds]] from verbal stems.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940}} Plural number can also be indicated through [[reduplication]].{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=87}} In this case, the meaning is exhaustive, e.g. all of the nouns.\n\nNouns with an oblique function, e.g. those expressing nominal possessors, subjects of gerunds and any noun that follows the [[Oblique argument|oblique]] marker ''i'ioo'', take the article ''u-'' in place of ''e-''. Finally, [[Locative case|locative nouns]] take the locative prefix ''i-''.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940}}\n\nNouns in Enggano can be modified by demonstratives and relative clauses. As in other Austronesian languages, these typically follow the nominal head. There are three demonstratives in Enggano:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=92}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Demonstratives in Enggano\n!Demonstrative\n!Enggano\n!Rough Translation\n|-\n|Proximal\n|ei'ie\n|this\n|-\n|Medial\n|e'ana\n|that\n|-\n|Distal\n|ea'a\n|that\n|}\nRelative clauses are introduced by a relativiser ''m\u00f5'\u00f5''. K\u00e4hler suggests that older speakers of Enggano would use different relativisers depending on whether the head noun was singular (''hem\u00f5\u2019\u00f5'') or plural (''h\u00f5m\u00f5\u2019\u00f5''). However, in 1937 when he was conducting research, this practice was already uncommon in everyday language.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=93}} An example of a relative clause in Enggano is given below. This shows that demonstratives also follow relative clauses:{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|p=93}}\n<br />\n{|\n|(1)\n|ka'u'ua-da'a\n|e-uba\n|m\u00f5'\u00f5\n|'am\u0169h\u00f5\n|ei'ie\n|-\n|\n|beautiful-<small>PRED</small>\n|<small>ART</small>-house\n|<small>REL</small>\n|big\n|<small>PROX.DEM</small>\n|-\n|\n| colspan=\"5\" |'This house which is big is beautiful'\n|}\n\nK\u00e4hler describes some processes of [[Morphological derivation|nominal derivation]] in Enggano. Specifically, he notes that instrumental nouns can be formed via the addition of a vowel or ''paV-'' to a verbal root, e.g. ''poko'' 'to chisel' > ''e-opoko'' 'a chisel' or ''kui'' 'to sew' > ''e-paukui'' 'needle'. Locative nouns are formed with an ''-a'' suffix, e.g. ''parudu'' 'gather' > ''e-parudu-a'' 'gathering place'.{{sfnp|K\u00e4hler|1940|pp=316\u2013318}}\n\n=== Verbs and Adjectives ===\nAdjectives commonly have prefixes ''ka-, ka\u2019-, ki-''; the first two are attested in derivation, and the last is assumed as it is very common and many such adjectives otherwise appear to be reduplicated, as in ''kinanap'' 'smooth' (Yoder 2011).\n\nVerbs may have one or two prefixes and sometimes a suffix. Attested prefixes are ''ba-, ba\u2019-, ia-, iah-, ka-, ka\u2019-, kah-, ki-, kir-, ko-, pa-, pah-, \u2019a-.'' The functions of these are unknown. ''Ki-'' and ''pa-'' may occur together, as in ''pe, pape, kipe, kipape'', all glossed as 'give'. The three attested verbal suffixes are ''-i, -ar, -a\u2019'' (Yoder 2011).\n\n=== Numerals ===\nThe counting system is, or at least once was, [[vigesimal]]: K\u00e4hler recorded ''kahai'i ekaka'' 'one man' = 20, ''ariba ekaka'' 'five man' = 100, ''kahai'i edudodoka'' 'one our-body' = 400. (The last may be based on two people counting together: each time I count all twenty of my digits, you count one of yours, so that when you have counted all of your digits, the number is 20\u00d720 = 400.) However, most people now use Malay numerals when speaking Enggano, especially for higher numbers. Yoder (2011) recorded the following:<ref>Also found [https://web.archive.org/web/20101230153201/http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/Enggano.htm here]</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n! Numeral !! Enggano \n|-\n| 1|| kahai\u2019 \n|-\n| 2|| \u2019aru \n|-\n| 3|| \u2019ak\u0259r\n|-\n| 4|| \u2019aup\n|-\n| 5|| \u2019arib \n|-\n| 6|| \u2019aki\u2019akin\n|-\n| 7|| \u2019arib he \u2019aru \n|-\n| 8|| k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p, \u2019\u00e3p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p\n|-\n| 9|| k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p kabai kahai\u2019, \u2019\u00e3p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p \u2019abai kahai\u2019 \n|-\n| 10|| k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p\n|-\n| 20|| kahai\u2019 kak\n|}\n1\u20135 are Austronesian, assuming ''ka-'' is a prefix on 'one' and ''\u2019a-'' is a prefix on 2\u20135. Compare the remaining ''-hai\u2019, -ru, -k\u0259r, -up, -rib'' with [[Lampung language|Lampung]] ''\u0259say, rua, t\u0259lu, \u0259pat, lima''; *s, *t, *l, *m have shifted to ''h, k, r, b'' in Enggano, and final consonants and (simple) vowels have been lost. \n''\u2019aki\u2019akin'' 6 may be reduplication of ''\u2019ak\u0259r'' 3. ''\u2019arib he \u2019aru'' 7 is 'five and two'. The two forms for 8 mean 'hugging', from the verb ''p\u00e3\u2019\u0129\u00f5p'' 'to hug', and 9 appears to be 'eight, one coming'; it may be shortened to ''kaba kahai\u2019'' (no ''-i'') in enumeration. Yoder believes 10 may also be a verb, based on an unelicited root ''\u2019\u00e3\u0169p'', as ''ki-'' and ''pa-'' are verbal prefixes (as in ''ki-pa-pe'' 'to give'); indeed, the apparent prefixes on 1\u20135 are identical to verbal prefixes as well.\n\nNumbers above 10 and 20 are formed with ''he ~ hi'' 'and': ''k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p he \u2019aru'' 'ten and two' for 12, ''kahai\u2019 kak he k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p'' 'twenty and ten' for 30. ''kak'' is 'person', so twenty is 'one person'. Multiples of twenty are formed from ''kak'', as in ''\u2019ak\u0259r kak he k\u0129p\u00e3\u2019\u00e3\u0169p'' 70, ''\u2019arib kak'' 100 (also ''kahai\u2019 ratuh'' from Malay ''ratus'').\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Blench, Roger, ''The Enggano: archaic foragers and their interactions with the Austronesian world.'' Draft 11th August, 2014.\n* {{cite journal |last=Blust |first=Robert |year=2004 |title=*t to k: An Austronesian sound change revisited |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages=365\u2013410 |jstor=3623363 |ref=harv}}\n* Capell, Arthur, ''Bezirkssprachen im gebiet des UAN''. In Gava\u2019: Studies in Austronesian languages and cultures dedicated to Hans K\u00e4hler, ed. by Rainer Carle, Martina Heinschke, Peter Pink, Christel Rost, and Karen Stadtlander, 1\u201314, Berlin, Dietrich Reimer, 1982.\n* {{cite journal |last=Edwards |first=Owen |year=2015 |title=The Position of Enggano within Austronesian |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=54-109 |hdl=1885/114506 |ref=harv}}\n* Helfrich, O. L., ''Aanvullingen en verbeteringen op de Maleisch\u2013Nederlansch\u2013Enganeesch woordenlijst.'' Tijdschrift voor Indische Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde 35:228\u201333, 1893.\n* {{cite journal |last=K\u00e4hler |first=Hans |year=1940 |title=Grammatischer Abriss des Enggano |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Eingeborenen-Sprachen |volume=30 |pages=81\u2013117, 182\u2013210, 296\u2013320 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lafeber |first=Abraham |title=Vergelijkende klankleer van het Niasisch |year=1922 |location=s'-Gravenhage |publisher=Hadi Poestaka |url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=MMKB02A:000030153:00001 |ref=harv}}\n* Nothofer, Bernd, ''The Barrier Island Languages in the Austronesian Language Family'', Focal II: Papers From the Fourth International Conference on Austronesian Linguistics, pp.&nbsp;87\u2013109, Pacific Linguistics, Series C, No. 94, Canberra, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, The Australian National University, 1986. {{hdl|1885/145382}} {{doi|10.15144/PL-C94}}\n* Nothofer, Bernd, ''Lehnw\u00f6rter Im Enggano'', In K\u00f6lner Beitr\u00e4ge Aus Malaiologie Und Ethnologie Zu Ehren Von Professor Dr. Irene Hilgers-Hesse, ed. F. Schulze and Kurt Tauchmann, K\u00f6lner S\u00fcdostasien Studien 1, Bonn: Holos, 1992\n* Nothofer, Bernd, ''The relationship between the languages of the Barrier Islands and the Sulawesi-Philippine languages''. In Language contact and change in the Austronesian world, ed. by Tom Dutton and Darrell Tryon, 389\u2013409, Berlin, Mouton de Gruyter, 1994.\n* {{cite journal |last=Smith |first=Alexander D. |year=2017 |title=The Western Malayo-Polynesian Problem |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages=435-490 |ref=harv}}\n* Yoder, Brendon, ''Phonological and phonetic aspects of Enggano vowels'', MA thesis, University of North Dakota, 2011 [https://arts-sciences.und.edu/academics/summer-institute-of-linguistics/theses/_files/docs/2011-yoder-brendon-e.pdf]\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Adelaar, Alexander, ''The Austronesian Languages of Asia and Madagascar: A Historical Perspective'', The Austronesian Languages of Asia and Madagascar, pp.&nbsp;1\u201342, Routledge Language Family Series, London, Routledge, 2005\n* Dyen, Isidore, ''A lexicostatistical classification of the Austronesian languages''. Indiana University Publications in Anthropology and Linguistics, 1965.\n* Goesmali, S.Z, et al, ''Morfofonemik bahasa Enggano,'' Padang, Pusat Penelitian Universitas Andalas. Laporan Penelitian, 1989.\n* Oudemans, J. A. C, ''Woordenlijst van de talen van Enggano, Mentawei en Nias,'' Tijdschrift voor Indische Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde 25:484\u201388, 1879.\n* K\u00e4hler, Hans, ''Texte von der Insel Enggano (Berichte \u00fcber eine untergehende Kultur)'', Berlin, Dietrich Reimer, 1975.\n* K\u00e4hler, Hans, ''Enggano-deutsches W\u00f6rterbuch'', Veroffentlichungen Des Seminars Fur Indonesische Und Sudseesprachen Der Universitat Hamburg, Hamburg: Dietrich Reimer, 1987.\n* Kaslim, Yuslina, et al, ''Pemetaan bahasa daerah di Sumatra Barat dan Bengkulu'', Jakarta: Pusat Pembinaan dan Pengembangan Bahasa, 1987\n* Nikelas, Syahwin, et al. ''Morfologi dan Sintaksis Bahasa Enggano,'' Jakarta, Pusat Pembinaan dan Pengembangan Bahasa, 1994.\n* van de Noord, A., ''Enggano'', In Holle lists: Vocabularies in languages of Indonesia, ed. by W. Stokhof, vol. 10/3, 189\u2013205, Canberra, Pacific Linguistics, 1987. {{hdl|1885/144589}} {{doi|10.15144/PL-D76}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721180840/http://www.rogerblench.info/Language%20data/Austronesian/Enggano/Enggano%20page.htm Language materials on Enggano]\n* [https://www.ethnologue.com/language/eno Enggano at Ethnologue]\n{{Languages of Indonesia}}\n{{Austronesian languages}}\n\n[[Category:Enggano language| ]]\n[[Category:Languages of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Sumatran languages]]\n[[Category:Unclassified languages of Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Austronesier", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEvolution", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enggano_language"}
{"title_page": "Charles Ethelston", "text_new": "[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14750648056).jpg|thumb|Political caricature from 1819, the central figure with the staff intended as Charles Ethelston]]\n'''Charles Wickstead Ethelston''', also given as '''Wicksted''' (1767\u20131830) was an English cleric, now remembered for the part he played in his role as magistrate on 16 August 1819, ahead of the [[Peterloo massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of the Rev. Charles Ethelstone (1731\u20131795), an Oxford graduate, and his wife Margaret Hart (died 1803) of [[Salford]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Admission Register of the Manchester School |publisher=Manchester University Press |pages=4-5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HAYNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA4 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelstone, Charles}}</ref><ref>{{CCEd |type=person |id=26866 |name=Ethelstone, Charles |year1=1754 |year2=1795 |accessed=18 March 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]] under Charles Lawson, and matriculated at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] in 1787, graduating B.A. in 1790 and M.A. in 1793.<ref name=\"acad\">{{acad|id=ETLN785CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> He was known also by the surnames Ethelstone and Ethelstane.\n\nEthelston became a curate in 1794 at St Mark's Chapel, [[Cheetham Hill]], which was then an urbanising area adjacent to Manchester and [[Salford]].<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=168787 |name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted |year1=1790 |year2=1831 |accessed=18 March 2020 }}</ref> His father, who died the following year, had recently completed it, at his own expense, on the Shooting Butts field at Cheetham;<ref name=\"Stancliffe\">{{cite book |last1=Stancliffe |first1=F. S. |title=The Manchester Royal Eye Hospital |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cRgNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |language=en}}</ref> it was a [[chapel of ease]] between the [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Prestwich]] and [[Manchester Collegiate Church]], for which Charles Ethelstone the elder had permission to build in 1790, in a hamlet where cotton merchants lived.<ref name=\"Genuki\">{{cite book |title=Genuki: St Mark Church of England, Cheetham, Lancashire |url=https://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Cheetham/StMark |language=en}}</ref> The chapel was consecrated on 24 July 1794 by [[William Markham]].<ref name=\"Churches\">{{cite web |title=Lancashire OnLine Parish Clerk Project |url=https://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Manchester/Cheetham/churches.html |website=www.lan-opc.org.uk}}</ref> Later, Ethelston became a [[perpetual curate]] there. A Jubilee School was built in Cheetham, and a plot of land obtained from [[Thomas Reynolds-Moreton, 1st Earl of Ducie|Lord Ducie]] to build a church to seat 1500.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Samuel |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England: Comprising the Several Counties, Cities, Boroughs, Corporate and Market Towns, Parishes, Chapelries, and Townships, and the Islands of Guernsey, Jersey, and Man, with Historical and Statistical Descriptions|date=1840 |publisher=S. Lewis & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iARBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501 |language=en}}</ref> The church was closed in 1982, and demolished around 1998.<ref name=\"Genuki\"/><ref name=\"Churches\"/>\n\nIn 1801, Ethelston was made rector of [[Worthenbury]], near [[Wrexham]].<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The presentation was presumably (according to [[Francis Robert Raines]]) by [[Sir Richard Price Puleston, 1st Baronet]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=307 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew23chetuoft/page/306/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1804 he became a Fellow of Manchester Collegiate Church.<ref name=\"acad\"/>\n[[File:St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, 1891.jpg|thumb|St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, interior in 1891]]\n\n==Civic Manchester==\nEthelston was chaplain to Silvester's Volunteers, raised in 1803 by John Silvester.<ref name=\"Navickas\">{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA121 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Timperley |first1=Charles Henry |title=Records historical, municipal |date=1874 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YA4HAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA67 |language=en}}</ref> Silvester was a millowner and magistrate, and the volunteer unit, the 2nd Regiment of the Manchester and Salford Rifle Volunteers, was active against [[Luddites]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philp |first1=Mark |title=Resisting Napoleon: The British Response to the Threat of Invasion, 1797\u20131815 |date=2016 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-90385-1 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DamoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT65 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nFor the Golden Jubilee of [[George III]], celebrated on 25 October 1809, Ethelston addressed in the Collegiate Church John Ratliff the boroughreeve and his constables, joined by the Masonic Lodge and the Orange Order. There was a procession on to [[St Ann's Square, Manchester|St Ann's Square]], joyshots from dragoons and a volley from the rifle brigade. A loyal toast was drunk, and dinner for around 250 eaten at the [[Manchester Cotton Exchange]]. Nearly 800 children from the [[Lancasterian school]] lined Lever Street.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Tradesman |date=1809 |pages=532-533 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9C4aAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA532 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, Ethelston and Silvester were among a group of loyalists intending to hold a dinner in the Exchange, with a toast and pledge to the [[Prince Regent]]. It was frustrated by an occupation of the Exchange, that led to vandalism.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Phythian |first1=Graham |title=Peterloo: Voices, Sabres and Silence |date=2018 |publisher=History Press |isbn=978-0-7509-8951-0 |page=46 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hA5dDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT46 |language=en}}</ref> In 1814 Ethelston was a founding board member of [[Manchester Royal Eye Hospital]].<ref name=\"Stancliffe\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nClerical magistrates were common in England in the later 18th century and early 19th century. Their numbers dropped back after 1832 and the [[Great Reform Act]]: in 1740 they were uncommon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hole |first1=Robert |title=Pulpits, Politics and Public Order in England, 1760-1832 |date=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-89365-7 |edition=186 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8du3_4Q5V8AC&pg=PA186 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |page=13 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 |language=en}}</ref> In [[Lancashire]] the custom was to exclude manufacturers from the bench, to keep it impartial in trade disputes: the practical result was that it was dominated by landowners and clerics, and by [[High Church]] and [[High Tory]] views. In Manchester at this period the prominent magistrates, according to Marlow, were the lawyer [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]], and two clerics, Ethelston and William Robert Hay.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=49 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a magistrate, Ethelston employed informers and spies, passing information about possible subversion to the [[Home Office]]. The Home Office funded spies in industrial districts: for Ethelston and Hay, and also Ralph Fletcher, magistrate at [[Bolton]], John Lloyd who was a magistrate's clerk at [[Stockport]], and Henry Enfield, town clerk of [[Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |page=258|volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/258/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Bernadette |title=A Loyal Englishman?: John Lloyd and Aspects of Oath-taking in 1812 |url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1057/9780230509382_9 |website=Radicalism and Revolution in Britain, 1775\u20131848: Essays in Honour of Malcolm I. Thomis |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK |pages=133\u2013142 |language=en |doi=10.1057/9780230509382_9 |date=2000}}</ref> In 1816 Ethelston was encouraged by [[John Hiley Addington]], at the Home Office as parliamentary secretary to his brother [[Lord Sidmouth]], to employ spies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reid |first1=Robert |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=2017 |publisher=Random House |isbn=978-1-4735-5477-1 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QBcqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT45 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Riding |first1=Jacqueline |title=Peterloo: The Story of the Manchester Massacre |date=2018 |publisher=Head of Zeus Ltd |isbn=978-1-78669-582-6 |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ydVADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston, Fletcher and Hay had in common membership of the [[Loyal Orange Institution]].<ref name=\"Navickas\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Neal |first1=Frank |title=Sectarian Violence: The Liverpool Experience, 1819-1914 : an Aspect of Anglo-Irish History |date=1988 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1483-3 |page=19 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EqfnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA19 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nEthelston had some success in 1817, when he sent Samuel Fleming and another spy into Yorkshire, to look for [[pike (weapon)|pike]]s being stored.<ref name=\"Hammonds\">{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |pages=260-261 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/260/mode/2up}}</ref> Fleming was an Irish weaver who had served in Silvester's Volunteers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Michael T. |last2=Macleod |first2=Emma |last3=Pentland |first3=Gordon |title=Political Trials in an Age of Revolutions: Britain and the North Atlantic, 1793\u20141848 |date=2018 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-98959-4 |page=198 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j_CBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Ethelston clashed with and abused Thomas Chapman, proprietor of the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', at a vestry meeting of the Manchester parish. Chapman was concerned with the oversight of the accounts of the local constables.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=The Manchester Observer: Biography of a Radical Newspaper |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library |date=1 March 2019 |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=31\u2013123, at pp. 46-47 |doi=10.7227/BJRL.95.1.3 |url=http://clok.uclan.ac.uk/28037/1/28037.pdf}}</ref> In 1818 also, during the weavers' strike, the magistrates Ethelston, Norris, William Marriott, and Ralph Wright pre-empted a planned meeting of weavers on 4 September, at Ashton Cross, [[Tameside]], with a notice that such assemblies of the unemployed were a danger to the public peace.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The skilled labourer, 1760-1832 |date=1919 |publisher=London, New York [etc.] : Longmans, Green and co. |page=116 |url=https://archive.org/details/skilledlabourer00hammiala/page/116/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n===Events of 1819===\nSubsequently Ethelston's credibility with the Home Office dropped. He wrote to Lord Sidmouth in June 1819 of an intended \"general rising\".<ref>Robert Poole, \"By the Law or the Sword\": Peterloo Revisited'', History Vol. 91, No. 2 (302) (April 2006), pp. 254\u2013276, at p. 265\u2013266. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24427836}}</ref> Fleming had fed him a report that [[William Cobbett]]'s visit to Lancashire was the signal for such a rising.<ref name=\"Hammonds\"/> His spy John Livesey tried to make direct contact with Sidmouth in London during 1819, claiming Ethelston had directed him to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bend |first1=Nathan Ashley |title=The Home Office and Public Disturbance, c.1800-1832 |date=2018 |pge=105 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/27d9/3b2be3a1cb1820c00927156e5d56a60dd0b1.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Making of the English Working Class]]'', [[E. P. Thompson]] wrote of summer 1819 that \"The government wanted blood \u2014 not a holocaust, but enough to make an example.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=Edward Palmer |title=The Making of the English Working Class |date=1980 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0140136037 |page=723 |language=en}}</ref> In the historiography of Peterloo, however, Thompson's thesis from 1963, in the form that the Home Office deliberately triggered violence against the meeting in [[St Peter's Square, Manchester|St Peter's Field]], has been challenged.<ref name=\"Read\">Donald Read, ''Reviewed Work: Peterloo: The Case Reopened by Robert Walmsley'', History Vol. 55, No. 183 (1970), pp. 138\u2013140. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24406795}}</ref> \n\nCorrespondence of the Home Office with Lancashire magistrates was through [[Henry Hobhouse (archivist)|Henry Hobhouse]], under-secretary of state from 1817 to 1827. He made it clear that the magistrates should set their house in order. In January 1819 he used a phrase about blood \"shed either by the Law or the sword\", prompted by a letter from Ralph Fletcher.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-878346-6 |page=211 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q5ygDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA211 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 July the Select Committee of Lancashire and Cheshire Magistrates was formed, and its first act was to lay a case of [[seditious libel]] against [[James Wroe]], editor of the ''Manchester Observer''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=111 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===16 August 1819, Peterloo===\n{{main|Peterloo Massacre}}\nThe magistrates most involved with Peterloo were Ethelston, Hay, Hulton and Norris.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Read |first1=Donald |title=Peterloo The Masssacre and its Background |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=75 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JMVRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA75 |language=en}}</ref> The roles of both Ethelston, reader of the [[Riot Act]], and [[William Hulton]] who brought in the militia, were later questioned as part of revisionism applied to Thompson's account.<ref name=\"Read\"/> Marlow argues that the invocation of the Riot Act was a side-issue, the magistrates having power in [[common law]] to disperse crowds.<ref name=\"Marlow\">{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |pages=147\u2013148 |language=en}}</ref>\n \nThe four were present, and Hulton chaired the committee of magistrates. From around 11 am, a group of nearly a dozen Lancashire and Cheshire magistrates were at Edmund Buxton's house on Mount Steet, overlooking St Peter's Field. It included also Ralph Fletcher, William Marriott, John Silvester and Ralph Wright.<ref>Others being the Rev. John Holdsworth Mallory, Robert Fielden, and Thomas Willian Tatton. ''The Tories, and their punishment of the people at the Peterloo meeting: a few words addressed to working men, the electors of Manchester and elsewhere, as to their duty.'' 1868, at p. 5. {{jstor|60216487}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stanley |first1=Edward |title=Three Accounts of Peterloo |date=2015 |publisher=Manchester University Press |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sHq7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA3 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe radicals' meeting on St Peter's Field began at 1.40 pm, as [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] started to speak. Hulton's committee took two decisions: to arrest leading radicals; and to disperse the crowd. The stentorian Ethelston read the Riot Act from a window in the Mount Street house, at a point between the attempted enforcements of those decisions. Hay gave an account of how Ethelson hung out of the window, and he had stood behind, ready to catch the tails of Ethelston's coat if he had started to topple. It is not clear that Ethelston was heard. Silvester then left the house, and read the Riot Act from a card.<ref name=\"Marlow\"/>\n\nIn the film ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'' by [[Mike Leigh]], Ethelston is played by [[Vincent Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peterloo (2018) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4614612/fullcredits}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of Peterloo===\n[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14587018178).jpg|thumb|left|Caricature of a two-faced clerical magistrate, from 1819, with the right-hand part holding gallows, scourge, blunderbuss and shackles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hone |first1=William |title=Regency Radical: Selected Writings of William Hone |date=2003 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0-8143-3060-9 |page=423 note 21 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=52XRU9KuL9kC&pg=PA423 |language=en}}</ref>]] \nSome days afterwards, according to a letter published in the ''Manchester Observer'', Ethelston said while preaching that  Peterloo was the will of God.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref> Henry Hunt appeared before the magistrates on 20 August, initially charged with [[high treason]], those on the bench being Sir William Bagshawe, [[John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford|Sir John Byng]], Ethelston, Ralph Fletcher, William Hulton, William Marriott, James Norris as chairman, Thomas William Tatton, Trafford Trafford, J. Watkins and Richard Wright.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peterloo Massacre, Containing a Faithful Narrative of the Events which Preceded, Accompanied, and Followed the Fatal Sixteenth of August, 1819, on the Area Near St. Peter's Church, Manchester, Including the Proceedings which Took Place at the Inquest at Oldham ... to which is Added, an Accurate List of the Names and Places of Residence of Those who Were Killed, Wounded and Maimed |date=1819 |publisher=publisher not identified |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AP4xAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA28 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston became concerned with headgear: radical supporters were wearing white hats, in imitation of Hunt, with green ribbons, and he wrote to Sidmouth about it on 13 September.<ref>James Epstein, ''Understanding the Cap of Liberty: Symbolic Practice and Social Conflict in Early Nineteenth-Century England'', Past & Present No. 122 (Feb., 1989), pp. 75\u2013118, at p. 110. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650952}}</ref>\n\nEthelston defended William Robert Hay in the ''[[Manchester Gazette]]'' on 25 September 1819, complaining of the ''[[ad hominem]]'' attacks made on all those who opposed reformers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref> [[William Benbow]] in his ''Rambler's Magazine'' in 1822 listed \"Hay and Ethelstone\" with disreputable clerics as \"chief agitators\" in Manchester.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rambler's Magazine: Or, Fashionable Emporium of Polite Literature|date=1822 |publisher=Benbow |page=409 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r103AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA409 |language=en}}</ref> Satire against clerical magistrates picked on Ethelston.<ref>{{cite book |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5PiADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69}}</ref> According to Gibson, \"It took many years for the people to forget that the magistrates who read the Riot Act at the Peterloo d\u00e9b\u00e2cle were Anglican clergy.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |pages=88-89 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Henry Grey Bennet]] asked the radical [[John Shuttleworth (industrialist)|John Shuttleworth]] on 18 November 1819 for information about the magistrates who signed the warrant to arrest Henry Hunt. This request may have prompted the pamphlet ''Manchester Slaughter!'' by \"Old Radical\". It took the form of an unsympathetic review of Ethelston's book of verse from 1803.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA significant publication and best-seller of November 1819 was ''The Political House that Jack Built'', a 24-page verse pamphlet parody of ''[[This Is the House That Jack Built]]'', by [[William Hone]], illustrated by [[George Cruikshank]]'s woodcut caricatures.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Ben |title=The Laughter of Triumph: William Hone and the Fight for the Free Press |date=2014 |publisher=Faber & Faber |isbn=978-0-571-31721-9 |pages=289-290 |language=en}}</ref> It contained \"The Clerical Magistrate\" with lines\n\n<poem>If the People were legally Meeting, in quiet\nWould pronouce it, decidedly\u2014''sec. Stat''\u2014a Riot,\nAnd order the Soldiers 'to aid and assist',\nThat is\u2014kill the helpless, who cannot resist.</poem>\n\nThe accompanying cut by Cruikshank is based on Ethelston, and contains internal references to the way Cruikshank depicted [[Lord Castlereagh]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gardner |first1=J. |title=Poetry and Popular Protest: Peterloo, Cato Street and the Queen Caroline Controversy |date=2011 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-230-30737-7 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P-eHDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA57 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Patten |first1=Robert L. |title=George Cruikshank's Life, Times, and Art: 1792-1835 |date=1992 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |isbn=978-0-7188-2872-1 |page=162|volume=1 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Last years==\nEthelston suffered a head injury when the horse of his [[gig (carriage)|gig]] ran away. He resided at addresses west and north of Manchester (see under Family). He died in September 1830, at age 63, and was buried at St Mark's, Cheetham Hill.<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The Suicide with Other Poems'' (1803)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ethelston |first1=Charles Wicksted |title=The Suicide with Other Poems |date=1803 |publisher=Author and Published |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MfY_AQAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Address delivered in the Exchange Room, in Manchester, to a General Meeting convened by the Boroughreeve and Constables, on Wednesday the 11th. of Decr.,1811, for the purpose of Taking into Consideration the Expediency of Founding Schools on the Plan of Dr. Bell'' (Manchester, 1811), against the [[Lancasterian system]].\n*''The Unity of the Church'' (1814), sermon.<ref name=\"Chetham\">{{cite book |last1=Radcliffe |first1=John |last2=Greswell |first2=William Parr |last3=Jones |first3=Thomas |last4=Byrom |first4=John |title=Bibliotheca Chethamensis. Sive Bibliothec\u00e6 Public\u00e6 Mancuniensis ab Humfredo Chetham armigero fundat\u00e6 catalogus exhibens libros in varias classes pro varietate argumenti distributos ... |date=1883|volume=VI |publisher=Mancunii : Excudebat J. Harrop, etc. |pages=118-119 |url=https://archive.org/details/b29004470_0002/page/118/mode/2up/}}</ref> It was attacked by the [[Wesleyan Methodist]] apologist Edward Wesley Hare (1774\u20131818), writing from Liverpool in 1815, in ''The Exclusive Claims of Episcopal Ordination Examined and Rejected'' (1815);<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=The exclusive claims of episcopal ordination examined and rejected, and the Methodist ministry vindicated; in a ser. of letters to C.W. Ethelson: being a reply to his sermon on 'The unity of the Church'. |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QTRcAAAAQAAJ |language=en}}</ref> he had been on the Manchester circuit in 1813.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Joseph |title=Hall's circuits and ministers: an alphabetical list of the circuits in Great Britain, with the names of the ministers stationed in each circuit, from 1765 to 1885 : with appendix from 1886-1896 |date=1897 |page=208 |url=https://archive.org/details/28455030.1897.emory.edu/page/n209/mode/2up |language=English}}</ref> Ethelston was defended in the anonymous ''Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston'' (1815), <ref>{{cite book |title=Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston, and on the Methodistical Schism, etc |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NmljAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref> and Hare returned to the subject in ''A Further Vindication of the Methodist Ministry'' (1816).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=A further vindication of the Methodist Ministry, against the exclusive claims of Episcopal Ordination: in a series of letters, addressed to ... C. W. Ethelston ... occasioned by anonymous strictures on the author's former letters [to him in answer to his sermon on the Unity of the Church], etc |date=1816 |publisher=Roberts & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UQZgAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''A Patriotic Appeal to the Good Sense of All Parties'' (1817), pseudonymous, as \"An Anti-Jacobin\".<ref name=\"Chetham\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Dicitonary of Anonymous and Pseudonymous English Literature |publisher=Ardent Media |page=312 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Tg0caI1-EToC&pg=PA312 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nEthelston was twice married: firstly to Mary Threlfall, daughter of John Threlfall of [[Chorley]]; and secondly in 1804 to Hannah Edwards, daughter of John Edwards of [[Kelsterton]].<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Aikin |first1=John |last2=Hill |first2=Benson Earle |title=Monthly Magazine and British Register |date=1804 |publisher=R. Phillips |page=270 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2yYxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA270 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe son of the first marriage was Charles Wicksted Ethelston (1798\u20131872), a cleric who succeeded his father at Cheetham as a [[perpetual curate]], and was then incumbent at [[Uplyme]] in Devon. He married in 1822 Anne Peel, daughter of Robert Peel, of Wallington Hall, Norfolk.<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN818CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> The second daughter Ellen Mary married in 1847 [[Charles Joseph Parke]];<ref>{{cite book |last1=critic |first1=Court magazine and monthly |title=The Court magazine and belle assembl\u00e9e [afterw.] and monthly critic and the Lady's magazine and museum |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4kAFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA5-PA28 |language=en}}</ref> the youngest daughter Margaret Emily married [[John Perry-Watlington]] in 1849.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1849 |publisher=E. Cave |page=688 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SbNOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA688 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEdwards Ethelston (1805\u2013c.1868), eldest son of the second marriage, was a surgeon in Manchester; the Cambridge register entry of 1823 for Edwards gives his father's residence as \"Collis Smedley\", i.e. Smedley Hill now in [[Smedley, Manchester]].<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN823EE|name=Ethelston, Edwards}}</ref> Hart Ethelston, third son, was rector of St Mark's, Cheetham from 1831. The Oxford register entry of 1826 for him gives his father's residence as [[Ardwick]].<ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelston, Hart}}</ref> He married Elizabeth Peel, daughter of Edmund Peel of Church Bank.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1871 |publisher=Harrison |page=1068 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H65CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1068 |language=en}}</ref> Edwin Ethelston, fourth son, married Julia Croal, daughter of the plantation owner [[John Croal]] in [[Demerara]].<ref name=\"BurkeLG\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1879 |publisher=Harrison |page=520 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R3YyY91Uqi0C&pg=PA520 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=John Croal 1789-1853 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/41736 |website=www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethelston, Charles}}\n[[Category:1767 births]]\n[[Category:1830 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n[[Category:English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14750648056).jpg|thumb|Political caricature from 1819, the central figure with the staff intended as Charles Ethelston]]\n'''Charles Wickstead Ethelston''', also given as '''Wicksted''' (1767\u20131830) was an English cleric, now remembered for the part he played in his role as magistrate on 16 August 1819, ahead of the [[Peterloo massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of the Rev. Charles Ethelstone (1731\u20131795), an Oxford graduate, and his wife Margaret Hart (died 1803) of [[Salford]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Admission Register of the Manchester School |publisher=Manchester University Press |pages=4-5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HAYNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA4 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelstone, Charles}}</ref><ref>{{CCEd |type=person |id=26866 |name=Ethelstone, Charles |year1=1754 |year2=1795 |accessed=18 March 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]] under Charles Lawson, and matriculated at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] in 1787, graduating B.A. in 1790 and M.A. in 1793.<ref name=\"acad\">{{acad|id=ETLN785CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> He was known also by the surnames Ethelstone and Ethelstane.\n\nEthelston became a curate in 1794 at St Mark's Chapel, [[Cheetham Hill]], which was then an urbanising area adjacent to Manchester and [[Salford]].<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=168787 |name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted |year1=1790 |year2=1831 |accessed=18 March 2020 }}</ref> His father, who died the following year, had recently completed it, at his own expense, on the Shooting Butts field at Cheetham;<ref name=\"Stancliffe\">{{cite book |last1=Stancliffe |first1=F. S. |title=The Manchester Royal Eye Hospital |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=5 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cRgNAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |language=en}}</ref> it was a [[chapel of ease]] between the [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Prestwich]] and [[Manchester Collegiate Church]], for which Charles Ethelstone the elder had permission to build in 1790, in a hamlet where cotton merchants lived.<ref name=\"Genuki\">{{cite book |title=Genuki: St Mark Church of England, Cheetham, Lancashire |url=https://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Cheetham/StMark |language=en}}</ref> The chapel was consecrated on 24 July 1794 by [[William Markham]].<ref name=\"Churches\">{{cite web |title=Lancashire OnLine Parish Clerk Project |url=https://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Manchester/Cheetham/churches.html |website=www.lan-opc.org.uk}}</ref> Later, Ethelston became a [[perpetual curate]] there. A Jubilee School was built in Cheetham, and a plot of land obtained from [[Thomas Reynolds-Moreton, 1st Earl of Ducie|Lord Ducie]] to build a church to seat 1500.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Samuel |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England: Comprising the Several Counties, Cities, Boroughs, Corporate and Market Towns, Parishes, Chapelries, and Townships, and the Islands of Guernsey, Jersey, and Man, with Historical and Statistical Descriptions|date=1840 |publisher=S. Lewis & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iARBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501 |language=en}}</ref> The church was closed in 1982, and demolished around 1998.<ref name=\"Genuki\"/><ref name=\"Churches\"/>\n\nIn 1801, Ethelston was made rector of [[Worthenbury]], near [[Wrexham]].<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The presentation was presumably (according to [[Francis Robert Raines]]) by [[Sir Richard Price Puleston, 1st Baronet]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=307 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew23chetuoft/page/306/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1804 he became a Fellow of Manchester Collegiate Church.<ref name=\"acad\"/>\n[[File:St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, 1891.jpg|thumb|St Mark's Church, Cheetham Hill, interior in 1891]]\n\n==Civic Manchester==\nEthelston was chaplain to Silvester's Volunteers, raised in 1803 by John Silvester.<ref name=\"Navickas\">{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA121 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Timperley |first1=Charles Henry |title=Records historical, municipal |date=1874 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YA4HAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA67 |language=en}}</ref> Silvester was a millowner and magistrate, and the volunteer unit, the 2nd Regiment of the Manchester and Salford Rifle Volunteers, was active against [[Luddites]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philp |first1=Mark |title=Resisting Napoleon: The British Response to the Threat of Invasion, 1797\u20131815 |date=2016 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-90385-1 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DamoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT65 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nFor the Golden Jubilee of [[George III]], celebrated on 25 October 1809, Ethelston addressed in the Collegiate Church John Ratliff the boroughreeve and his constables, joined by the Masonic Lodge and the Orange Order. There was a procession on to [[St Ann's Square, Manchester|St Ann's Square]], joyshots from dragoons and a volley from the rifle brigade. A loyal toast was drunk, and dinner for around 250 eaten at the [[Manchester Cotton Exchange]]. Nearly 800 children from the [[Lancasterian school]] lined Lever Street.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Tradesman |date=1809 |pages=532-533 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9C4aAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA532 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, Ethelston and Silvester were among a group of loyalists intending to hold a dinner in the Exchange, with a toast and pledge to the [[Prince Regent]]. It was frustrated by an occupation of the Exchange, that led to vandalism.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Phythian |first1=Graham |title=Peterloo: Voices, Sabres and Silence |date=2018 |publisher=History Press |isbn=978-0-7509-8951-0 |page=46 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hA5dDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT46 |language=en}}</ref> In 1814 Ethelston was a founding board member of [[Manchester Royal Eye Hospital]].<ref name=\"Stancliffe\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nClerical magistrates were common in England in the later 18th century and early 19th century. Their numbers dropped back after 1832 and the [[Great Reform Act]]: in 1740 they were uncommon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hole |first1=Robert |title=Pulpits, Politics and Public Order in England, 1760-1832 |date=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-89365-7 |edition=186 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8du3_4Q5V8AC&pg=PA186 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |page=13 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 |language=en}}</ref> In [[Lancashire]] the custom was to exclude manufacturers from the bench, to keep it impartial in trade disputes: the practical result was that it was dominated by landowners and clerics, and by [[High Church]] and [[High Tory]] views. In Manchester at this period the prominent magistrates, according to Marlow, were the lawyer [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]], and two clerics, Ethelston and William Robert Hay.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=49 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a magistrate, Ethelston employed informers and spies, passing information about possible subversion to the [[Home Office]]. The Home Office funded spies in industrial districts: for Ethelston and Hay, and also Ralph Fletcher, magistrate at [[Bolton]], John Lloyd who was a magistrate's clerk at [[Stockport]], and Henry Enfield, town clerk of [[Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |page=258|volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/258/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Bernadette |title=A Loyal Englishman?: John Lloyd and Aspects of Oath-taking in 1812 |url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1057/9780230509382_9 |website=Radicalism and Revolution in Britain, 1775\u20131848: Essays in Honour of Malcolm I. Thomis |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK |pages=133\u2013142 |language=en |doi=10.1057/9780230509382_9 |date=2000}}</ref> In 1816 Ethelston was encouraged by [[John Hiley Addington]], at the Home Office as parliamentary secretary to his brother [[Lord Sidmouth]], to employ spies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reid |first1=Robert |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=2017 |publisher=Random House |isbn=978-1-4735-5477-1 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QBcqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT45 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Riding |first1=Jacqueline |title=Peterloo: The Story of the Manchester Massacre |date=2018 |publisher=Head of Zeus Ltd |isbn=978-1-78669-582-6 |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ydVADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston, Fletcher and Hay had in common membership of the [[Loyal Orange Institution]].<ref name=\"Navickas\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Neal |first1=Frank |title=Sectarian Violence: The Liverpool Experience, 1819-1914 : an Aspect of Anglo-Irish History |date=1988 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1483-3 |page=19 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EqfnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA19 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nEthelston had some success in 1817, when he sent Samuel Fleming and another spy into Yorkshire, to look for [[pike (weapon)|pike]]s being stored.<ref name=\"Hammonds\">{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The Town Labourer, 1760-1832; the new civilization |date=1917 |publisher=London, Longmans, Green |pages=260-261 |url=https://archive.org/details/townlabourer00hammuoft/page/260/mode/2up}}</ref> Fleming was an Irish weaver who had served in Silvester's Volunteers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=Michael T. |last2=Macleod |first2=Emma |last3=Pentland |first3=Gordon |title=Political Trials in an Age of Revolutions: Britain and the North Atlantic, 1793\u20141848 |date=2018 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-98959-4 |page=198 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j_CBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Ethelston clashed with and abused Thomas Chapman, proprietor of the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', at a vestry meeting of the Manchester parish. Chapman was concerned with the oversight of the accounts of the local constables.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=The Manchester Observer: Biography of a Radical Newspaper |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library |date=1 March 2019 |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=31\u2013123, at pp. 46-47 |doi=10.7227/BJRL.95.1.3 |url=http://clok.uclan.ac.uk/28037/1/28037.pdf}}</ref> In 1818 also, during the weavers' strike, the magistrates Ethelston, Norris, William Marriott, and Ralph Wright pre-empted a planned meeting of weavers on 4 September, at Ashton Cross, [[Tameside]], with a notice that such assemblies of the unemployed were a danger to the public peace.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hammond |first1=John Lawrence |last2=Hammond |first2=Barbara Bradby |title=The skilled labourer, 1760-1832 |date=1919 |publisher=London, New York [etc.] : Longmans, Green and co. |page=116 |url=https://archive.org/details/skilledlabourer00hammiala/page/116/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n===Events of 1819===\nSubsequently Ethelston's credibility with the Home Office dropped. He wrote to Lord Sidmouth in June 1819 of an intended \"general rising\".<ref>Robert Poole, \"By the Law or the Sword\": Peterloo Revisited'', History Vol. 91, No. 2 (302) (April 2006), pp. 254\u2013276, at p. 265\u2013266. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24427836}}</ref> Fleming had fed him a report that [[William Cobbett]]'s visit to Lancashire was the signal for such a rising.<ref name=\"Hammonds\"/> His spy John Livesey tried to make direct contact with Sidmouth in London during 1819, claiming Ethelston had directed him to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bend |first1=Nathan Ashley |title=The Home Office and Public Disturbance, c.1800-1832 |date=2018 |pge=105 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/27d9/3b2be3a1cb1820c00927156e5d56a60dd0b1.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Making of the English Working Class]]'', [[E. P. Thompson]] wrote of summer 1819 that \"The government wanted blood \u2014 not a holocaust, but enough to make an example.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=Edward Palmer |title=The Making of the English Working Class |date=1980 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0140136037 |page=723 |language=en}}</ref> In the historiography of Peterloo, however, Thompson's thesis from 1963, in the form that the Home Office deliberately triggered violence against the meeting in [[St Peter's Square, Manchester|St Peter's Field]], has been challenged.<ref name=\"Read\">Donald Read, ''Reviewed Work: Peterloo: The Case Reopened by Robert Walmsley'', History Vol. 55, No. 183 (1970), pp. 138\u2013140. Published by: Wiley {{jstor|24406795}}</ref> \n\nCorrespondence of the Home Office with Lancashire magistrates was through [[Henry Hobhouse (archivist)|Henry Hobhouse]], under-secretary of state from 1817 to 1827. He made it clear that the magistrates should set their house in order. In January 1819 he used a phrase about blood \"shed either by the Law or the sword\", prompted by a letter from Ralph Fletcher.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-878346-6 |page=211 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q5ygDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA211 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 July the Select Committee of Lancashire and Cheshire Magistrates was formed, and its first act was to lay a case of [[seditious libel]] against [[James Wroe]], editor of the ''Manchester Observer''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |page=111 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===16 August 1819, Peterloo===\n{{main|Peterloo Massacre}}\nThe magistrates most involved with Peterloo were Ethelston, Hay, Hulton and Norris.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Read |first1=Donald |title=Peterloo The Masssacre and its Background |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=75 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JMVRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA75 |language=en}}</ref> The roles of both Ethelston, reader of the [[Riot Act]], and [[William Hulton]] who brought in the militia, were later questioned as part of revisionism applied to Thompson's account.<ref name=\"Read\"/> Marlow argues that the invocation of the Riot Act was a side-issue, the magistrates having power in [[common law]] to disperse crowds.<ref name=\"Marlow\">{{cite book |last1=Marlow |first1=Joyce |title=The Peterloo Massacre |date=1969 |publisher=Rapp & Whiting |pages=147\u2013148 |language=en}}</ref>\n \nThe four were present, and Hulton chaired the committee of magistrates. From around 11 am, a group of nearly a dozen Lancashire and Cheshire magistrates were at Edmund Buxton's house on Mount Steet, overlooking St Peter's Field. It included also Ralph Fletcher, William Marriott, John Silvester and Ralph Wright.<ref>Others being the Rev. John Holdsworth Mallory, Robert Fielden, and Thomas Willian Tatton. ''The Tories, and their punishment of the people at the Peterloo meeting: a few words addressed to working men, the electors of Manchester and elsewhere, as to their duty.'' 1868, at p. 5. {{jstor|60216487}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stanley |first1=Edward |title=Three Accounts of Peterloo |date=2015 |publisher=Manchester University Press |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sHq7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA3 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe radicals' meeting on St Peter's Field began at 1.40 pm, as [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] started to speak. Hulton's committee took two decisions: to arrest leading radicals; and to disperse the crowd. The stentorian Ethelston read the Riot Act from a window in the Mount Street house, at a point between the attempted enforcements of those decisions. Hay gave an account of how Ethelson hung out of the window, and he had stood behind, ready to catch the tails of Ethelston's coat if he had started to topple. It is not clear that Ethelston was heard. Silvester then left the house, and read the Riot Act from a card.<ref name=\"Marlow\"/>\n\nIn the film ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'' by [[Mike Leigh]], Ethelston is played by [[Vincent Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peterloo (2018) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4614612/fullcredits}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of Peterloo===\n[[File:The political house that Jack built (1819) (14587018178).jpg|thumb|left|Caricature of a two-faced clerical magistrate, from 1819, with the right-hand part holding gallows, scourge, blunderbuss and shackles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hone |first1=William |title=Regency Radical: Selected Writings of William Hone |date=2003 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=978-0-8143-3060-9 |page=423 note 21 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=52XRU9KuL9kC&pg=PA423 |language=en}}</ref>]] \nSome days afterwards, according to a letter published in the ''Manchester Observer'', Ethelston said while preaching that  Peterloo was the will of God.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref> Henry Hunt appeared before the magistrates on 20 August, initially charged with [[high treason]], those on the bench being Sir William Bagshawe, [[John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford|Sir John Byng]], Ethelston, Ralph Fletcher, William Hulton, William Marriott, James Norris as chairman, Thomas William Tatton, Trafford Trafford, J. Watkins and Richard Wright.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peterloo Massacre, Containing a Faithful Narrative of the Events which Preceded, Accompanied, and Followed the Fatal Sixteenth of August, 1819, on the Area Near St. Peter's Church, Manchester, Including the Proceedings which Took Place at the Inquest at Oldham ... to which is Added, an Accurate List of the Names and Places of Residence of Those who Were Killed, Wounded and Maimed |date=1819 |publisher=publisher not identified |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AP4xAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA28 |language=en}}</ref> Ethelston became concerned with headgear: radical supporters were wearing white hats, in imitation ofHunt, with green ribbons, and he wrote to Sidmouth about it on 13 September.<ref>James Epstein, ''Understanding the Cap of Liberty: Symbolic Practice and Social Conflict in Early Nineteenth-Century England'', Past & Present No. 122 (Feb., 1989), pp. 75\u2013118, at p. 110. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650952}}</ref>\n\nEthelston defended William Robert Hay in the ''[[Manchester Gazette]]'' on 25 September 1819, complaining of the ''[[ad hominem]]'' attacks made on all those who opposed reformers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref> [[William Benbow]] in his ''Rambler's Magazine'' in 1822 listed \"Hay and Ethelstone\" with disreputable clerics as \"chief agitators\" in Manchester.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rambler's Magazine: Or, Fashionable Emporium of Polite Literature|date=1822 |publisher=Benbow |page=409 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r103AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA409 |language=en}}</ref> Satire against clerical magistrates picked on Ethelston.<ref>{{cite book |page=69 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5PiADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69}}</ref> According to Gibson, \"It took many years for the people to forget that the magistrates who read the Riot Act at the Peterloo d\u00e9b\u00e2cle were Anglican clergy.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gibson |first1=William |title=Church, State and Society, 1760\u20131850 |date=1994 |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education |isbn=978-1-349-23204-8 |pages=88-89 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KkpdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Henry Grey Bennet]] asked the radical [[John Shuttleworth (industrialist)|John Shuttleworth]] on 18 November 1819 for information about the magistrates who signed the warrant to arrest Henry Hunt. This request may have prompted the pamphlet ''Manchester Slaughter!'' by \"Old Radical\". It took the form of an unsympathetic review of Ethelston's book of verse from 1803.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=426 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA426 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA significant publication and best-seller of November 1819 was ''The Political House that Jack Built'', a 24-page verse pamphlet parody of ''[[This Is the House That Jack Built]]'', by [[William Hone]], illustrated by [[George Cruikshank]]'s woodcut caricatures.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Ben |title=The Laughter of Triumph: William Hone and the Fight for the Free Press |date=2014 |publisher=Faber & Faber |isbn=978-0-571-31721-9 |pages=289-290 |language=en}}</ref> It contained \"The Clerical Magistrate\" with lines\n\n<poem>If the People were legally Meeting, in quiet\nWould pronouce it, decidedly\u2014''sec. Stat''\u2014a Riot,\nAnd order the Soldiers 'to aid and assist',\nThat is\u2014kill the helpless, who cannot resist.</poem>\n\nThe accompanying cut by Cruikshank is based on Ethelston, and contains internal references to the way Cruikshank depicted [[Lord Castlereagh]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gardner |first1=J. |title=Poetry and Popular Protest: Peterloo, Cato Street and the Queen Caroline Controversy |date=2011 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-230-30737-7 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P-eHDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA57 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Patten |first1=Robert L. |title=George Cruikshank's Life, Times, and Art: 1792-1835 |date=1992 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |isbn=978-0-7188-2872-1 |page=162|volume=1 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Last years==\nEthelston suffered a head injury when the horse of his [[gig (carriage)|gig]] ran away. He resided at addresses west and north of Manchester (see under Family). He died in September 1830, at age 63, and was buried at St Mark's, Cheetham Hill.<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: the Case Reopened |date=1969 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-0392-9 |page=428 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WM5RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA428 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The Suicide with Other Poems'' (1803)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ethelston |first1=Charles Wicksted |title=The Suicide with Other Poems |date=1803 |publisher=Author and Published |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MfY_AQAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Address delivered in the Exchange Room, in Manchester, to a General Meeting convened by the Boroughreeve and Constables, on Wednesday the 11th. of Decr.,1811, for the purpose of Taking into Consideration the Expediency of Founding Schools on the Plan of Dr. Bell'' (Manchester, 1811), against the [[Lancasterian system]].\n*''The Unity of the Church'' (1814), sermon.<ref name=\"Chetham\">{{cite book |last1=Radcliffe |first1=John |last2=Greswell |first2=William Parr |last3=Jones |first3=Thomas |last4=Byrom |first4=John |title=Bibliotheca Chethamensis. Sive Bibliothec\u00e6 Public\u00e6 Mancuniensis ab Humfredo Chetham armigero fundat\u00e6 catalogus exhibens libros in varias classes pro varietate argumenti distributos ... |date=1883|volume=VI |publisher=Mancunii : Excudebat J. Harrop, etc. |pages=118-119 |url=https://archive.org/details/b29004470_0002/page/118/mode/2up/}}</ref> It was attacked by the [[Wesleyan Methodist]] apologist Edward Wesley Hare (1774\u20131818), writing from Liverpool in 1815, in ''The Exclusive Claims of Episcopal Ordination Examined and Rejected'' (1815);<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=The exclusive claims of episcopal ordination examined and rejected, and the Methodist ministry vindicated; in a ser. of letters to C.W. Ethelson: being a reply to his sermon on 'The unity of the Church'. |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QTRcAAAAQAAJ |language=en}}</ref> he had been on the Manchester circuit in 1813.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Joseph |title=Hall's circuits and ministers: an alphabetical list of the circuits in Great Britain, with the names of the ministers stationed in each circuit, from 1765 to 1885 : with appendix from 1886-1896 |date=1897 |page=208 |url=https://archive.org/details/28455030.1897.emory.edu/page/n209/mode/2up |language=English}}</ref> Ethelston was defended in the anonymous ''Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston'' (1815), <ref>{{cite book |title=Strictures on Hare's Letters to the Rev. C. Ethelston, and on the Methodistical Schism, etc |date=1815 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NmljAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref> and Hare returned to the subject in ''A Further Vindication of the Methodist Ministry'' (1816).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hare |first1=Edward Wesley |title=A further vindication of the Methodist Ministry, against the exclusive claims of Episcopal Ordination: in a series of letters, addressed to ... C. W. Ethelston ... occasioned by anonymous strictures on the author's former letters [to him in answer to his sermon on the Unity of the Church], etc |date=1816 |publisher=Roberts & Company |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UQZgAAAAcAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n*''A Patriotic Appeal to the Good Sense of All Parties'' (1817), pseudonymous, as \"An Anti-Jacobin\".<ref name=\"Chetham\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Dicitonary of Anonymous and Pseudonymous English Literature |publisher=Ardent Media |page=312 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Tg0caI1-EToC&pg=PA312 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nEthelston was twice married: firstly to Mary Threlfall, daughter of John Threlfall of [[Chorley]]; and secondly in 1804 to Hannah Edwards, daughter of John Edwards of [[Kelsterton]].<ref name=\"acad\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Aikin |first1=John |last2=Hill |first2=Benson Earle |title=Monthly Magazine and British Register |date=1804 |publisher=R. Phillips |page=270 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2yYxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA270 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe son of the first marriage was Charles Wicksted Ethelston (1798\u20131872), a cleric who succeeded his father at Cheetham as a [[perpetual curate]], and was then incumbent at [[Uplyme]] in Devon. He married in 1822 Anne Peel, daughter of Robert Peel, of Wallington Hall, Norfolk.<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN818CW|name=Ethelston, Charles Wicksted}}</ref> The second daughter Ellen Mary married in 1847 [[Charles Joseph Parke]];<ref>{{cite book |last1=critic |first1=Court magazine and monthly |title=The Court magazine and belle assembl\u00e9e [afterw.] and monthly critic and the Lady's magazine and museum |page=28 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4kAFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA5-PA28 |language=en}}</ref> the youngest daughter Margaret Emily married [[John Perry-Watlington]] in 1849.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1849 |publisher=E. Cave |page=688 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SbNOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA688 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEdwards Ethelston (1805\u2013c.1868), eldest son of the second marriage, was a surgeon in Manchester; the Cambridge register entry of 1823 for Edwards gives his father's residence as \"Collis Smedley\", i.e. Smedley Hill now in [[Smedley, Manchester]].<ref>{{acad|id=ETLN823EE|name=Ethelston, Edwards}}</ref> Hart Ethelston, third son, was rector of St Mark's, Cheetham from 1831. The Oxford register entry of 1826 for him gives his father's residence as [[Ardwick]].<ref>{{alox2|title=Ethelston, Hart}}</ref> He married Elizabeth Peel, daughter of Edmund Peel of Church Bank.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1871 |publisher=Harrison |page=1068 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H65CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1068 |language=en}}</ref> Edwin Ethelston, fourth son, married Julia Croal, daughter of the plantation owner [[John Croal]] in [[Demerara]].<ref name=\"BurkeLG\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Bernard |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland |date=1879 |publisher=Harrison |page=520 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R3YyY91Uqi0C&pg=PA520 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=John Croal 1789-1853 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/41736 |website=www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethelston, Charles}}\n[[Category:1767 births]]\n[[Category:1830 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n[[Category:English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester]]\n", "name_user": "Charles Matthews", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath of Peterloo:fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Ethelston"}
{"title_page": "Robocall", "text_new": "{{short description|Phone call delivering pre-recorded message}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Update|date=June 2019|reason=Information on the US FCC's [https://www.fcc.gov/document/fcc-affirms-robocall-blocking-default-protect-consumers-0 June 6, 2019, vote] needs to be included}}\n{{lead too short|date=May 2012}}\n{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=March 2010}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n\nA '''robocall''' is a phone call that uses a computerized [[autodialer]] to deliver a pre-recorded message, as if from a [[robot]]. Robocalls are often associated with political and [[telemarketing]] phone campaigns, but can also be used for public-service or emergency announcements. Some robocalls use [[Personalized audio messaging|personalized audio messages]] to simulate an actual personal phone call. In 2019 the [[United States Congress]] passed legislation expanding the regulation of robocalls.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Timothy B. |title=Congress passes legislation expanding robocall penalties |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2019/12/congress-slaps-robocallers-with-10000-penalty-per-call/?bxid=5be9fceb2ddf9c72dc8994b7&cndid=30462369 |website=Ars Technica |accessdate=26 December 2019 |language=en-us |date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==North America==\n===Canada===\n{{Main|Robocall scandal}}\n\nRobocalls can be and are legitimately used by mainstream political parties in Canada to reach voters. Controversy surrounded the use of robocalls during the [[2011 Canadian federal election]], leading [[Elections Canada]] and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] to investigate claims that robocalls were used in an attempt to dissuade voters from casting their ballot by falsely telling them their poll stations had changed locations.<ref>{{cite web |last=McGregor |first=Glen |title=Michael Sona to be sentenced Nov. 19 in robocalls affair |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/crown-seeks-increased-sentence-for-sona-over-2011-robocalls-case |website=Ottawa Citizen |publisher=Postmedia Network Inc. |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref> Elections Canada traced the origin of the automated calls to a disposable cellphone registered to a fictional name \"Pierre Poutine\" at a phony address from 450 [[area code]] of [[Joliette]], [[Quebec]], and issued a subpoena to the cellphone provider that produced a list of outgoing calls from the same number. One of the calls was to the toll-free number used by customers of 2call.ca, a subsidiary of [[Edmonton]]-based [[Internet Service Provider]] RackNine, to phone in and record their outgoing messages. The burner cell phone belonging to \"Pierre Poutine\" was used to contact the owner of Racknine at his personal unlisted number and gave the name \"Pierre Jones\". This burner phone initiated a series of automated robocalls mostly in Guelph but with a few dozen in other ridings, that targeted mostly non-Conservative voters with false voting location changes. Some voters attended what they had been led to believe were their voting locations, and sometimes destroyed their voter registration cards in anger.{{Citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\nIn November 2011, the investigator served RackNine with a production order for records and had the account holder associated with the bogus calls quickly identified.<ref>{{cite web|last=Maher and McGregor |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Tracking+telephone+tricks/6194759/story.html |title=Tracking telephone tricks |publisher=Ottawa Citizen |accessdate=28 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226004126/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/Tracking+telephone+tricks/6194759/story.html |archivedate=February 26, 2012 }}</ref> Investigators have also examined the Conservative Party's CIMS voter database and showed that \"Pierre Poutine\" used the Conservative voter database to select whom to call. Investigators have blank entries for one specific login, leading to speculation that evidence has been deleted. PayPal has also surrendered their records to investigators since \"Pierre Poutine\" has used a PayPal account to pay for the bill for the automated calls. The cost for these May 2, 2011, calls was $162.10, Elections Canada said in court filings. This expenditure was never reported to Elections Canada, as required for legitimate political spending.\n\nPrime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] have denied any knowledge or involvement.<ref>{{cite web|last=Maher and McGregor|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/robocalls-probe-centres-on-disposable-burner-cellphone-linked-to-guelph-black-ops|title=Robocalls probe centres on disposable \u2018burner\u2019 cellphone linked to black ops in Guelph riding|publisher=National Post|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> A Conservative party staffer resigned soon after the scandal was reported but has since come forward stating that he was not involved.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/who-s-who-in-the-election-phone-calls-controversy-1.1128163 | title=Who's who in the election phone calls controversy | work=CBC News | date=February 29, 2012}}</ref> Elections Canada has made a statement<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=med&document=mar1512&dir=pre&lang=e |title=Elections Canada Online - News Releases and Media Advisories}}</ref> and reported to Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=med&document=mar2912&dir=spe&lang=e|title=Elections Canada Online - Statements and Speeches|publisher=}}</ref> that the fraud was extensive, affecting 200 ridings in all ten provinces plus [[Yukon]] Territory.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/politics/article/1153879--robocall-probe-stretches-to-200-ridings-across-canada-chief-electoral-officer-marc-mayrand-tells-commons-committee | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Susan | last=Delacourt | title=Robocall probe stretches to 200 ridings across Canada, chief electoral officer Marc Mayrand tells Commons committee | date=March 30, 2012}}</ref> The Council of Canadians, a left of centre activist group, has asserted that the robocalls may have been enough to swing the result by 4%, enough to win a number of ridings in very close races. A court challenge has been initiated by this group to overturn the results of the election in seven ridings, and initiate by-elections for the respective seven House of Commons seats.\n\nAfter reviewing the investigation of the \"Pierre Poutine\" scandal in 2013, Federal Court Judge Richard Mosley found that election fraud had taken place in six ridings across the country but found no evidence that the Conservative party or candidates were involved. He also did not find sufficient evidence to support charges in ridings other than Guelph. As well, he indicated that the \"robocalls\" had not affected the outcome of the 2011 election in any riding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/editorials/2014/08/14/greasy_robocall_scandal_will_haunt_conservatives_at_the_polls_editorial.html|title=Greasy \u2018robocall\u2019 scandal will haunt Conservatives at the polls: Editorial|date=August 14, 2014|work=thestar.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter a lengthy investigation of the circumstances of the scandal,<ref name=\"news.nationalpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/pierre-poutine-robocalls-planned-by-more-than-one-person-but-michael-sona-was-directing-mind-crown-says|title=\u2018Pierre Poutine\u2019 robocalls planned by \u2018more than one person,\u2019 but Michael Sona was \u2018directing mind,\u2019 Crown says - National Post|author=Stephen Maher, Postmedia News|date=June 9, 2014|work=National Post}}</ref> Michael Sona, the former director of communications for the Conservative candidate in the Guelph (Ontario) riding<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/michael-sona-wont-appeal-robocalls-conviction-but-will-seek-lighter-sentence-lawyer|title=Michael Sona won\u2019t appeal robocalls conviction but will seek lighter sentence: lawyer - National Post|author=Stephen Maher|date=April 9, 2015|work=National Post}}</ref> was charged on June 2, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/michael-sona-charged-with-guelph-robocalls-starts-trial-today-1.2659780|title=Michael Sona, charged with Guelph robocalls, starts trial today|date=June 2, 2014|publisher=}}</ref> with \"wilfully preventing or endeavouring to prevent an elector from voting\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kitchener.ctvnews.ca/trial-begins-monday-for-guelph-pc-staffer-charged-in-robocalls-scandal-1.1847885|title=Trial begins Monday for Guelph PC staffer charged in robocalls scandal|work=Kitchener}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/guelph-robocall-victims-ask-elections-canada-to-reopen-case-1.3158248|title=Guelph robocall victims ask Elections Canada to reopen case|date=July 17, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Sona was found guilty on November 14, 2014 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2014/11/19/michael-sona-sentenced-to-9-months-in-robocalls-scandal/|title=Michael Sona sentenced to 9 months in robocalls scandal|work=CityNews}}</ref> and was sentenced to nine months in jail plus twelve months of probation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/michael-sona-sentenced-to-9-months-in-jail-for-callous-robocalls-1.2839410|title=Found guilty of subverting democracy, Michael Sona sentenced to 9 months|publisher=}}</ref> Sona was released from jail on bail after serving twelve days, pending his appeal of the sentence. However, Sona did not appeal the conviction.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> During the trial, Justice Hearn agreed with the Crown allegation <ref name=\"news.nationalpost.com\"/> that Sona had likely not acted alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/robocalls-trial-michael-sona-sentenced-to-9-months-in-jail-1.2108744|title=Conservative staffer Michael Sona given 9-month jail sentence in Robocalls case - CTV News|work=CTVNews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/michael-sona-guilty-in-robocalls-trial-but-did-not-likely-act-alone-1.2735676|title=Michael Sona guilty in robocalls trial - but 'did not likely act alone'|date=August 14, 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n====Political calls====\nRobocalls are made by many political parties in the United States, including but not limited to both the Republican and Democratic parties as well as unaffiliated campaigns, [[527 organization]]s, unions, and individual citizens. Political robocalls are exempt from the [[United States National Do Not Call Registry]].<ref>The do-not-call list restricts \"telephone solicitations\" and does not apply to tax-exempt nonprofit organization. 47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(a)(3) defines \"telephone solicitations\"; 47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(c) enables the do-not-call list.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=National Do Not Call Registry |url=https://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0108-national-do-not-call-registry |website=Consumer Information |publisher=Federal Trade Commission |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref> The [[Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991]] (TCPA) and [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) regulations prohibit anyone (including charities, politicians and political parties) from making robocalls to cell phone numbers without the recipients' prior consent.<ref>47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(b)(1)(A); there are other prohibited destinations such as hospital rooms; some calls, such as those for an emergency purpose, are permitted.</ref> The FCC permits non-commercial robocalls to most residential (non-cellular) telephone lines.<ref>47 C.F.R. \u00a7&nbsp;64.1200(a)(2) [2007] permits non-commercial and tax-exempt nonprofit calls.</ref>\n\nThe federal [[Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991]] (TCPA) regulates automated calls.<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/47/227- Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991 (TCPA)], 47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227.</ref> All robocalls, irrespective of whether they are political in nature, must do two things to be considered legal. Federal law requires all telephone calls using pre-recorded messages to identify who is initiating the calls and include a telephone number or address whereby the initiator can be reached.<ref>47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(d)(3); 47 C.F.R. \u00a764.1200(b)</ref>\n\nSome states (23 according to DMNews) have laws that regulate or prohibit political robocalls.<ref name=\"states\">[http://www.dmnews.com/cms/dm-news/legal-privacy/38770.html States enforce limits on robocalls] \u2013 DMNews, \"States enforce limits on robocalls\"</ref> [[Robocall#Indiana|Indiana]] and [[North Dakota]] prohibit automated political calls.<ref name = \"UPI\">[http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/view.php?StoryID=20061105-010536-9525r Phonebank accents irk congressman] \u2013 UPI, November 5, 2006.</ref> In [[New Hampshire]], political robocalls are allowed, except when the recipient is in the [[United States National Do Not Call Registry|National Do Not Call Registry]].<ref name=\"Concord Monitor\">[http://www.concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061105/REPOSITORY/611050397 Repeat calls not from Hodes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070519052740/http://www.concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20061105%2FREPOSITORY%2F611050397 |date=May 19, 2007 }} \u2013 [[Concord Monitor]], November 5, 2006. \"Repeat calls not from Hodes\"</ref> Many states require the disclosure of who paid for the call, often requiring such notice be recorded in the candidate's own voice. The patch-work of state laws regulating political robocalls has created problems for national campaigns.<ref name = \"Regulating Robocalls\">[http://ssrn.com/abstract=1309780 Regulating Robocalls: Are Automated Calls the Sound of, or a Threat to, Democracy?] \u2013 [[Michigan Telecommunications and Technology Law Review]], Forthcoming 2009. \"Regulating Robocalls: Are Automated Calls the Sound of, or a Threat to, Democracy?\"</ref>\n\n====California====\nThe first political robo calls were launched in January 1983 when business owner Tony Inocentes used his telemarketing machine from his collection agency business to announce his candidacy for the 57th Assembly District in California. He launched over 300,000 automated calls before losing the November 1983 General election to the incumbent Dave Elder. Inocentes founded the GOTV election company ePolitical USA in 1984.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 2001 Inocentes invented political robo polling launching the first political robo poll on October 31, 2001 in the Lynwood, CA city council elections.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n[[California]] prohibits any robocall unless there is an existing relationship.<ref name=\"Cal PUC\">{{cite web|url=http://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displayText.xhtml?division=1.&chapter=10.&part=2.&lawCode=PUC&article=1.|title=Codes Display Text|author=|date=|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> The California Public Utilities Code \u00a7\u00a7 2871 ''et seq.'' holds political campaigns to the same rules as other organizations making calls with an automatic dialing\u2013announcing device.<ref name=\"Cal PUC\"/> The guidelines are:\n* A person must come on the line before the recording to identify the nature of the call and the organization behind it.\n* The recipient of the call must consent to the recording being played.\n* The call must be disconnected from the telephone line as soon as the message is over or the recipient hangs up, whichever comes first.\n\n====Indiana====\nIndiana requires introduction of any prerecorded message by a live operator; the message may only be played if the called party grants permission.<ref name=\"states\"/>\n\n====Missouri====\nIn September 2008, then-[[Missouri Attorney General]] [[Jay Nixon]] alerted political campaigns in Missouri that his office would aggressively enforce federal rules (Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991) requiring calls to include identifying and contact information.<ref>Attorney General's News Release. [http://ago.mo.gov/newsreleases/2008/Federal_law_requires_robo_calls_to_include_identifying_and_contact_information/ Nixon alerts political campaigns that federal law requires \u201crobo-calls\u201d to include identifying and contact information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917151456/http://ago.mo.gov/newsreleases/2008/Federal_law_requires_robo_calls_to_include_identifying_and_contact_information/ |date=September 17, 2008 }}. September 4, 2008.</ref>\n\n====North Carolina====\nRobocalls were made during the [[North Carolina Democratic primary, 2008|2008 North Carolina Democratic primary]], targeting [[African-American]] voters in the days leading up to the primary in late April 2008,<ref>[http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/elections_board_hunting_robocaller \"Elections board hunting robocaller] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620103015/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/elections_board_hunting_robocaller |date=June 20, 2008 }},\" ''The [[News & Observer]]'', April 28, 2008. Accessed April 29, 2008.</ref> which essentially told registered voters that they were not registered.<ref>[https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2008/4/29/505589/- Daily Kos Blog].{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2008}} (blog) Accessed April 29, 2008.</ref>\nAccording to [[NPR]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=90114863|title=Group with Clinton Ties Behind Dubious Robocalls|date=May 1, 2008|work=NPR.org}}</ref> and Facing South,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southernstudies.org/facingsouth/2008/05/center-for-investigative-reporting.asp|title=- The Institute for Southern Studies|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208044411/http://southernstudies.org/facingsouth/2008/05/center-for-investigative-reporting.asp|archivedate=February 8, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> these calls were made by the organization \"[[Women's Voices Women Vote]]\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">Murray, Shailagh, \"Women's Voices, Women Vote: Did the Outreach Overreach?\", ''Washington Post'', Sunday, May 4, 2008; Page A10, found at [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/05/03/AR2008050301870.html Washington Post article on Women's Voices Women Vote]. Accessed May 5, 2008.</ref> Voters and watchdog groups complained that it was a [[Voter intimidation|turnout-suppression]] effort, and the state Attorney General [[Roy A. Cooper|Roy Cooper]] ordered them to stop making the calls.<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\"/> The group stopped the calls and no further legal action was taken.\n\n====South Carolina====\n{{Main|Cahaly v. LaRosa}}\n\n[[South Carolina]] had a law prohibiting most types of unsolicited consumer and political robocalls, but in 2010, campaign consultant Robert Cahaly was arrested by the South Carolina State Law Enforcement Division, being charged for making illegal robocalls to six state house districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wistv.com/story/13429729/gop-consultant-to-face-sled-arrest-for-illegal-robocalls|title= GOP consultant arrested for illegal \"robocalls\"|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> The automated opinion polling system asked whether [[Nancy Pelosi|U.S. Speaker Nancy Pelosi]] should be invited to campaign with six Democratic candidates for the South Carolina Legislature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law360.com/articles/699756/call-me-unconstitutional-hang-up-for-sc-s-robocall-law|title= Call Me Unconstitutional: Hang-Up For SC's Robocall Law|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> Cahaly was arrested despite having a written opinion from the state attorney general stating that he had acted within the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitsnews.com/2015/08/18/fourth-circuit-sc-robocall-ban-is-unconstitutional/|title= Fourth Circuit: SC Robocall Ban Is Unconstitutional|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> The charges were subsequently dismissed in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20121006/PC16/121009479/1031/charges-of-illegal-robo-calls-against-gop-consultant-dismissed|title= Charges Against GOP Consultant Cahaly Dropped|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> After the charges were dropped, Cahaly filed a suit against state officials, claiming his constitutional right to free speech had been violated. U.S. district court judge, [[J. Michelle Childs|Michelle Childs]] ruled that South Carolina's anti-robocall statute was a content-based restriction on speech and therefore unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestate.com/news/politics-government/politics-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article13862843.html|title= Fed Court rules law Cahaly charged under unconstitutional|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed additional regulations====\nCalifornia Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]] (D-CA) introduced the Federal Robocall Privacy Act<ref name=hearing>\n{{cite web |title=Protecting Voters at Home and at the Polls: Limiting Abusive Robocalls and Vote Caging Practices |url=https://www.rules.senate.gov/hearings/protecting-voters-at-home-and-at-the-polls-limiting-abusive-robocalls-and-vote-caging-practices |website=Rules of the Senate |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref> in February 2008 at a Senate Committee on Rules and Administration hearing. The Act proposed to: 1) limit robocalls to no more than two a day by any one candidate, 2) mandate that candidates have accurate caller ID numbers displayed, 3) mandate that the disclosure of who is paying for the call occur at the start of the call, rather than at the end of the call, and 4) mandate that the time of the call occur not before 8{{nbsp}}a.m. or after 9{{nbsp}}p.m. The bill was read twice, and since it received no further action during the session, it did not become law.<ref name=\"govtrack.us\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=s110-2624 S. 2624: Robocall Privacy Act of 2008]. Accessed January 4, 2009.</ref> Similar bills have been submitted in subsequent years without success.<ref>[http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2014/02/05/schumer-pushes-bill-expand-robocall-ban/5231415/ Schumer pushes bill to expand robocall ban]. Democrat and Chronicle. Accessed October 11, 2014</ref>\n\nShaun Dakin, CEO of [[Citizens for Civil Discourse]], testified at the hearing and described how robocalls affect the lives of voters across the nation.<ref name=hearing/> He also wrote an op-ed for the ''Washington Post'' calling for a Voter Privacy Bill of Rights in which all voters would have the right to opt out of political robocalls if they did not wish to receive them.<ref>Washington Post. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/12/AR2008091202658.html A Privacy Shield Against the Campaigns]. Shaun Dakin. Saturday, September 13, 2008; Page A17.</ref>\n\nDakin, a former [[John Kerry]] campaign worker,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stoppoliticalcalls.org/ht/display/ArticleDetails/i/23669/pid/700|title=Stop political robocalls and telemarketers with Nomorobo|publisher=}}</ref> set up a website called Stoppoliticalcalls.org and claimed to allow citizens to opt out of receiving robocalls.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/10/23/robo.calls/index.html |date=October 23, 2008 |accessdate=May 22, 2010 |publisher=CNN |title=Robocalls flood phone lines in battleground states}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todaystmj4.com/features/call4action/30567724.html |title=Stop the Calls |publisher=NBC Affiliate TMJ |accessdate=June 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120102026/http://www.todaystmj4.com/features/call4action/30567724.html |archivedate=November 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,430242,00.html |title=Tech Q and A: I Am Serious. And Don't Call Me Shirley |author=Guy R. Briggs |publisher=Fox News |date=September 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-10073249-38.html?tag=newsLeadStoriesArea.0 |publisher=CNET.com |title=Election Day brings invasion of robocalls |date=October 23, 2008 |author=Stephanie Condon}}</ref> However, there is no guarantee that the registry will stop the calls and since there is no law that supports the database it is essentially an [[Internet petition]]. As mentioned above, the Robocall Privacy Act failed to become law and neither bill had provisions for a do-not-call registry for stopping robocalls.<ref name=\"govtrack.us\"/><ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h110-5747 H.R. 5747: Robocall Privacy Act of 2008]. Accessed October 23, 2008.</ref>\n\nDespite heavy media publicity of the database, only seven politicians in the United States voluntarily pledged to respect the list during the 2008 general election cycle. Of those seven, only three made it to the general election and only [[Virginia Foxx]] (R) was successfully reelected in November 2008.\n\nOn September 1, 2009, a new regulation of the [[Federal Trade Commission]] went into effect, banning most robocalls without written opt-in from the receiver.<ref>[http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/08/robocalls.shtm \"New Rule Prohibiting Unwanted \"Robocalls\" to Take Effect on September 1\", FTC News Release August 27, 2009] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003154923/http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/08/robocalls.shtm |date=October 3, 2011 }}</ref> Political campaigns, surveys, charities, debt collectors, and health care providers are exempt, as are calls to businesses. Calls from banks, insurers, and phone companies are out of the jurisdiction of the FTC. In situations under federal jurisdiction, the federal law will supersede a slightly less restrictive law in the state of California.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/pender/detail?&entry_id=46359 |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |title=Kathleen Pender - Net Worth Plus : FTC is putting an end to most robo calls |date=August 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Reverse robocalling==\nIn December 2011, reporting described \"robocall revenge\" where voters can turn the table and send robocalls to politicians and others using online website tools.<ref>{{cite news | first = Ambreen | last = Ali | title = Website Seeks Robocall Revenge | date = December 8, 2011 | url = http://www.rollcall.com/news/website_seeks_robocall_revenge-210937-1.html?pos=opolh | work = [[Roll Call]] | accessdate =December 28, 2011 | quote = Launched last month, Reverse Robocall has already helped individuals and advocacy groups make nearly 2,000 calls to lawmakers, politicians and private companies.}}</ref>\n\n==Suppressing unwanted and illegal robocalls==\nMany robocalls are not wanted, and several methods have been developed to prevent unwanted robocalls. Many countries operate [[do not call list]]s, but the lists have been ineffective<ref>{{cite news|title=No hiding from nuisance calls|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/10108666/No-hiding-from-nuisance-calls.html|accessdate=12 December 2016|publisher=The Telegraph|date=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://consumersunion.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Dialing-Back-Complete-Report-11.16.2015.pdf |title=Dialing Back: How Phone Companies Can End Unwanted Robocalls |last=Mahoney |first=Maureen |year=2015 |website=Consumers Union |publisher=Consumers Union |page=3 |format=PDF |publication-date=November 2015}}</ref> and legally problematic in some cases.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Strauss|first1=Jared|title=The Do-Not-Call List's Big Hang-up|journal=Richmond Journal of Law & Technology|date=2004|volume=X|issue=4|url=http://jolt.richmond.edu/v10i4/article27.pdf|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> Consequently, a market has developed for products that allow consumers to block robocalls. Most products use methods similar to those used to mitigate [[VoIP spam|SPIT]] (spam over Internet telephony) and can be broadly categorised by the primary method used. However, due to the complexity of the problem, no single method is sufficiently reliable.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ziming_Zhao/publication/299794558_SoK_Everyone_Hates_Robocalls_A_Survey_of_Techniques_against_Telephone_Spam/links/5705504308ae13eb88b959e5.pdf |title=SoK: Everyone Hates Robocalls: A Survey of Techniques Against Telephone Spam |last=Huahong |first=Tu |last2=Doup\u00e9 |first2=Adam |year=2016 |publisher=University of Arizona |page=14 |format=pdf |last3=Zhao |first3=Ziming |last4=Ahn |first4=Gail-Joon |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nSolutions are available as both hardware and software products. [[Mobile app]]s are especially prevalent as they use techniques which do not require the modification of infrastructure. Many products are limited to use only on a single medium, such as traditional copper landlines, or [[mobile phone]] contracts from a specific [[mobile phone operator]].\n\n=== Blacklisting and whitelisting ===\nIn its simplest form, this method offers the ability to prevent further calls from phone numbers, once they are known to be a source of robocalls. Many mobile apps can prevent robocalls with a user generated [[Blacklist (computing)|blacklist]].\n\n[[File:Call-blocker-wikipedia.jpg|thumb|Landline call blocker in use]]\n\nFor landlines there are standalone call blockers which connect to the telephone. Various models work on blacklisting and whitelisting principles. Call blockers received attention from publications including [[Which?]] and [[Consumer Reports]] in the United Kingdom and United States respectively.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leedham |first1=Robert |title=Call blocking devices \u2013 everything you need to know |url=http://blogs.which.co.uk/technology/phones-3/call-blocking-devices-eveything-you-need-to-know/ |website=which.co.uk |publisher=Which? |accessdate=22 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701075905/http://blogs.which.co.uk/technology/phones-3/call-blocking-devices-eveything-you-need-to-know/ |archivedate=2016-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rage against robocalls|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/magazine/2015/07/robocall-blocker-review/index.htm|website=consumerreports.org|publisher=Consumer Reports|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK [[BT Group|BT]] operates a service for landlines called Choose to Refuse which allows customers to block up to 10 phone numbers of their choice for a monthly fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=All about Choose to Refuse|url=http://bt.custhelp.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/8500/~/all-about-choose-to-refuse|website=BT.com Help|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nA number of physical products have been developed for use with landlines. These are typically installed in homes and employ a [[Hard coding|hard coded]] or irregularly updated blacklist. Some models also have the function to create a user-generated whitelist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/magazine/2015/07/robocall-blocker-review/index.htm|title=Robocall blocker review|last=|first=|date=14 August 2015|website=Consumer Reports|publisher=|language=en|publication-date=|access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref> Newer devices for landlines can use cloud based data to resolve the hard coded blacklist issues and allow you to create your own whitelist/blacklist.\n\n=== Crowdsourcing ===\nA more sophisticated model uses [[crowdsourcing]] to build a more comprehensive blacklist of robocall numbers. A notable example of this is the app [[Truecaller]], which requires users to provide access to their personal [[whitelist]] of genuine contacts in exchange for access to the larger crowdsourced database. In 2013, hackers gained access to Truecaller's database of known genuine numbers, highlighting the danger of centralising this information.<ref>{{cite web|title=Truecaller Statement|url=https://blog.truecaller.com/2013/07/18/truecaller-statement/|website=Truecaller Blog|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=en|date=5 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ehackingnews.com/2013/07/truecaller-database-hacked-by-syrian.html|title=Truecaller Database hacked by Syrian Electronic Army|last=|first=|date=16 July 2013|work=|access-date=|via=E Hacking News}}</ref>\n\n=== CAPTCHA ===\nBuilding on the crowdsourcing model, [[Primus Canada]] launched a patented product called Telemarketing Guard for [[landlines]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stein|first1=Matthew|title=Stopping Fraudulent Robocall Scams: Can More Be Done?|url=https://www.commerce.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/ef5915d3-e47e-4834-9a42-a4393ea03d9c/AB13B79566335ED657BFD89A085CCCA1.stein2.pdf|website=United States Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation|accessdate=21 November 2016|page=1|language=en|format=pdf|date=10 July 2013}}</ref> It improves on previous models by including a [[CAPTCHA]] style challenge-response test.\n\nBased on a database developed from customer feedback, it filters suspected telemarketing calls to a system which challenges callers to record their name after pressing a button. If a name is recorded, the customer's phone rings with the [[Caller ID]] of Telemarketing Guard. If they answer the phone, they are played the recording, at which point they can accept the call or decline and report it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Call-Blocking Technology|url=https://www.ftc.gov/sites/default/files/documents/public_events/robocalls-all-rage-ftc-summit/robocalls-part7-call-blocking.pdf|website=Federal Trade Commission|accessdate=21 November 2016|page=19|language=en|format=pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Realtime analysis ===\nA major problem for the use of both blacklisting and whitelisting techniques is the practice of [[caller ID spoofing]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Scam Alert - How Scammers Use Caller ID Spoofing to Pose as You|url=http://www.bbb.org/council/news-events/bbb-scam-alerts/2014/06/scam-alert-how-scammers-use-caller-id-spoofing-to-pose-as-you/|website=Council of Better Business Bureaus|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=en|date=20 June 2014}}</ref> which is prevalent as a result of the low [[Barriers to entry|barrier to entry]] in the [[Voice over IP|VoIP]] services market.<ref>{{harvnb|Huahong|Doup\u00e9|Zhao|Ahn|2016|p=2}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 the [[Federal Communications Commission]] proposed a framework for the telecommunications industry in the United States, which included a validation system at network level for robocalls from [[Session Initiation Protocol|SIP]] sources by 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=CGB Announces Agenda for Robocall and Caller ID Spoofing Workshop on September 16, 2015|url=https://apps.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-15-1001A1_Rcd.pdf|website=Federal Communications Commission|accessdate=21 November 2016|pages=9880\u20139881|language=en|format=pdf|date=10 September 2015}}</ref> The final authentication task in the framework is the signing of all VoIP calls, which would allow carriers to reliably identify robocalls.\n\nUntil these goals are achieved, a more advanced method for blocking robocalls uses [[real-time business intelligence]] techniques to address the constantly changing identities of robocalls. With access to a large enough data sample, it is possible to create algorithms which detect call patterns without requiring reporting by users.\n\nIn 2016, both [[Verizon Wireless|Verizon]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Verizon Caller Name ID|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/solutions-and-services/caller-name-id/}}</ref> and [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] each launched their own service based on Enhanced Caller ID, which is developed by Cequint and incorporates whitelisting, blacklisting and crowdsourcing techniques.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=TNS and Cequint Deploy Next Generation Robocall Solution Delivering Best-in-Class Service for Sprint Customers |date=30 November 2016 |publisher=Business Wire |location=Reston, Virginia |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20161130005642/en/}}</ref> For improved accuracy, it is complemented by a technology called Call Guardian developed by [[Transaction Network Services|TNS]], which performs caller behavior analysis on the 25 billion public calls they handle every year in real time.<ref>{{cite web|title=TNS Call Guardian|url=http://www.tnsi.com/products-services/telecom/protecting/tns-call-guardian/|website=TNS|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nStarting in mid-2017, and with intended culmination in 2019, the FCC pushed forward Caller ID certification implemented via a methodology of [[Caller ID spoofing#United States|SHAKEN/STIR]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.fcc.gov/call-authentication |title= Combating Spoofed Robocalls with Caller ID Authentication |publisher= [[FCC]] |date= 2017 |first= Ajit |last= Pai }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2019/02/ajit-pai-orders-phone-companies-to-adopt-new-anti-robocall-tech-in-2019/ |title= Ajit Pai orders phone companies to adopt new anti-robocall tech in 2019 |publisher= Arstechnica |date= Feb 14, 2019 |first= Jon |last= Brodkin }}</ref> In June 2019, the FCC adopted a rule allowing (but not mandating) phone companies to block unwanted robocalls by default, without a consumer opt-in; a rule related to source authentication was still in a public comment period.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2019/06/06/730415950/heres-why-you-may-start-receiving-fewer-robocalls Here's Why You May Start Receiving Fewer Robocalls]</ref>\n\nThe TRACED Act, signed into law in December 2019, requires the FCC to implement Caller ID authentication, requires the FCC to report all criminal robocalls to the Justice Department, gives consumers access to robocall blocking at no charge, and increases penalties for violators.<ref>[https://www.zdnet.com/article/trump-signs-the-traced-act-the-first-federal-anti-robocall-law/ Trump signs the TRACED Act, the first federal anti-robocall law]</ref>\n\n==Enforcement==\n\nIn August 2016, a \"Robocall Strike Force\" of thirty companies said they would help crack down on the problem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-robocalls/att-apple-google-to-work-on-robocall-crackdown-idUSKCN10U18L|title=AT&T, Apple, Google to work on 'robocall' crackdown|date=August 20, 2016|publisher=|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Federal Communications Commission Declaratory Rulings===\n\nAfter receiving more than 215,000 consumer complaints in 2014 alone, the U.S. Federal Communications Commission (FCC) strengthened and clarified its regulations protecting consumers from unwanted robocalls and spam emails and texts. The Commission issued a package of declaratory rulings in June 2015 that clarified the provisions of the Telephone Consumer Protection Act (TCPA) that deal with prerecorded and artificial voice calls received by residential wireline phones as well as wireless numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://incompliancemag.com/commission-strengthens-consumer-protections-against-robocalls/|title=Commission Strengthens Consumer Protections Against Robocalls|work=In Compliance Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ruane |first1=Kathleen Ann |title=(Robo)call Me Maybe: Robocalls to Wireless Phones Under the Telephone Consumer Protection Act |date=May 29, 2018 |publisher=Congressional Research Service |location=Washington, DC |url=https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo130753 |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2009 Federal Trade Commission action against an illegal robocall provider===\nIn May 2009, in response to numerous complaints, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] asked a federal court to shut down a telemarketing campaign that has been bombarding U.S. consumers with hundreds of millions of allegedly deceptive robocalls in an effort to sell them vehicle service contracts under the guise that they are extensions of original vehicle [[Warranty|warranties]].<ref>http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/09/twi.shtm, \"FTC Settlement Bans Robocalls from Auto \"Warranty\" Company\", FTC News Release, 9/1/2009</ref> The FTC took action against both the promoter of the phony extended auto warranties, as well as the telemarketing company that it hired to carry out its illegal, deceptive campaign. The FTC contends that the companies are operating a massive telemarketing scheme that uses random, pre-recorded phone calls to deceive consumers into thinking that their vehicle's warranty is about to expire. Consumers who respond to the robocalls are pressured to purchase extended service contracts for their vehicles, which the telemarketers falsely portray as an extension of the manufacturer's original warranty. According to papers the FTC filed with the court, however, the robocalls have prompted tens of thousands of complaints from consumers who are either on the United States National Do Not Call Registry or asked not to be called. Five telephone numbers associated with the defendants have generated a total of 30,000 Do Not Call complaints. Consumers received the robocalls at home, work, and on their cell phones, sometimes several times in one day. Businesses, government offices and even 911 dispatchers have been subjected to the calls.\n\nThose who answer the pre-recorded calls hear a message telling them that their vehicle warranty is about to expire and that they should \"extend coverage before it is too late\". They are told to \"press one\" to speak to a \"warranty specialist\". The \"specialists\" then mislead consumers into believing that their company is affiliated with the dealer or manufacturer of the consumer's vehicle. They try to sell consumers a service contract for between $2,000 and $3,000, which they falsely portray as an extension of the vehicle's original warranty. The seller of extended auto warranties sued by the FTC allegedly took in more than $10 million on the sale of these deceptively marketed service contracts. In their robocalls, the companies dialed every phone number within a particular area code and prefix sequentially, without knowing whether the consumers called were motorists or owned motor vehicles, or whether those consumers' numbers were on the Do Not Call Registry. Consumers who asked that the calls be stopped often were met with \"abusive behavior\" or were simply hung up on, according to the papers filed with the court. Some of the defendants used offshore shell corporations to try to avoid scrutiny, and a top officer in the telemarketing company bragged to prospective clients that he could operate outside the law without any chance of being caught by the FTC, the papers stated. This defendant also claimed that he makes 1.8 million dials per day and that he had done more than $40 million worth of dialing for extended warranty companies, including one billion dials on behalf of his largest client, according to the court papers filed by the FTC. In addition to the robocalls, the FTC charged that the company selling the warranties mails out deceptive postcards to consumers, warning them about the imminent expiration of their auto warranties. The postcards are designed to mislead consumers into believing that they are being contacted by their dealer or manufacturer, and the postcards offer consumers the chance to \"renew\" their original warranties.<ref name=\"case\">[https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20090515-717706.html FTC: Judge Orders Halt To Robocalls Selling Deceptive Warranties], ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', May 15, 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714024144/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20090515-717706.html |date=July 14, 2009 }}</ref> On May 15, 2009 U.S. District Judge [[John Francis Grady|John F. Grady]] issued the temporary restraining order against the defendants Transcontinental Warranty Inc. and Voice Touch Inc. Grady's orders also applied to Transcontinental CEO and President Christopher Cowart, Voice Touch executives James and Maureen Dunne, Voice Touch business partner Network Foundations LLC and Network Foundations executive Damian Kohlfeld. Besides ordering a halt to the automatic telephone sales calls, Grady's order froze the assets of the two companies. The FTC alleged in its complaints that the calls were part of a deceptive scheme and asked the court to assure the assets will not be lost in case they might be needed to repay consumers who have been victimized. The FTC isn't immediately seeking civil fines against the companies but may do so later, agency officials said. Attorneys general in Arkansas, Indiana and Missouri have taken similar actions over calls offering extended warranties on automobiles.<ref name=\"case1\">[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jFpGIsUi1KVrRr07BBoVqLrkz0ZQD986V9404 Judge blocks 'robo-calls' selling car warranties], [[Associated Press]], May 15, 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607220858/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jFpGIsUi1KVrRr07BBoVqLrkz0ZQD986V9404 |date=June 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Voice broadcasting]]\n* [[Ringless voicemail]]\n* [[Cold calling]]\n* [[Google Duplex]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://complaints.donotcall.gov/complaint/complaintcheck.aspx  National Do Not Call Registry Complaints]\n*[https://consumercomplaints.fcc.gov/hc/en-us Federal Communications Commission Consumer Complaint Center]\n*[https://www.nomorobo.com Nomorobo.com]\n\n{{Spamming}}\n\n[[Category:Telemarketing]]\n[[Category:Neologisms]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Phone call delivering pre-recorded message}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Update|date=June 2019|reason=Information on the US FCC's [https://www.fcc.gov/document/fcc-affirms-robocall-blocking-default-protect-consumers-0 June 6, 2019, vote] needs to be included}}\n{{lead too short|date=May 2012}}\n{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=March 2010}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n\nA '''robocall''' is a phone call that uses a computerized [[autodialer]] to deliver a pre-recorded message, as if from a [[robot]]. Robocalls are often associated with political and [[telemarketing]] phone campaigns, but can also be used for public-service or emergency announcements. Some robocalls use [[Personalized audio messaging|personalized audio messages]] to simulate an actual personal phone call. In 2019 the [[United States Congress]] passed legislation expanding the regulation of robocalls.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Timothy B. |title=Congress passes legislation expanding robocall penalties |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2019/12/congress-slaps-robocallers-with-10000-penalty-per-call/?bxid=5be9fceb2ddf9c72dc8994b7&cndid=30462369 |website=Ars Technica |accessdate=26 December 2019 |language=en-us |date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==North America==\n===Canada===\n{{Main|Robocall scandal}}\n\nRobocalls can be and are legitimately used by mainstream political parties in Canada to reach voters. Controversy surrounded the use of robocalls during the [[2011 Canadian federal election]], leading [[Elections Canada]] and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] to investigate claims that robocalls were used in an attempt to dissuade voters from casting their ballot by falsely telling them their poll stations had changed locations.<ref>{{cite web |last=McGregor |first=Glen |title=Michael Sona to be sentenced Nov. 19 in robocalls affair |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/crown-seeks-increased-sentence-for-sona-over-2011-robocalls-case |website=Ottawa Citizen |publisher=Postmedia Network Inc. |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref> Elections Canada traced the origin of the automated calls to a disposable cellphone registered to a fictional name \"Pierre Poutine\" at a phony address from 450 [[area code]] of [[Joliette]], [[Quebec]], and issued a subpoena to the cellphone provider that produced a list of outgoing calls from the same number. One of the calls was to the toll-free number used by customers of 2call.ca, a subsidiary of [[Edmonton]]-based [[Internet Service Provider]] RackNine, to phone in and record their outgoing messages. The burner cell phone belonging to \"Pierre Poutine\" was used to contact the owner of Racknine at his personal unlisted number and gave the name \"Pierre Jones\". This burner phone initiated a series of automated robocalls mostly in Guelph but with a few dozen in other ridings, that targeted mostly non-Conservative voters with false voting location changes. Some voters attended what they had been led to believe were their voting locations, and sometimes destroyed their voter registration cards in anger.{{Citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\nIn November 2011, the investigator served RackNine with a production order for records and had the account holder associated with the bogus calls quickly identified.<ref>{{cite web|last=Maher and McGregor |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Tracking+telephone+tricks/6194759/story.html |title=Tracking telephone tricks |publisher=Ottawa Citizen |accessdate=28 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226004126/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/Tracking+telephone+tricks/6194759/story.html |archivedate=February 26, 2012 }}</ref> Investigators have also examined the Conservative Party's CIMS voter database and showed that \"Pierre Poutine\" used the Conservative voter database to select whom to call. Investigators have blank entries for one specific login, leading to speculation that evidence has been deleted. PayPal has also surrendered their records to investigators since \"Pierre Poutine\" has used a PayPal account to pay for the bill for the automated calls. The cost for these May 2, 2011, calls was $162.10, Elections Canada said in court filings. This expenditure was never reported to Elections Canada, as required for legitimate political spending.\n\nPrime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] and the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] have denied any knowledge or involvement.<ref>{{cite web|last=Maher and McGregor|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/robocalls-probe-centres-on-disposable-burner-cellphone-linked-to-guelph-black-ops|title=Robocalls probe centres on disposable \u2018burner\u2019 cellphone linked to black ops in Guelph riding|publisher=National Post|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> A Conservative party staffer resigned soon after the scandal was reported but has since come forward stating that he was not involved.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/who-s-who-in-the-election-phone-calls-controversy-1.1128163 | title=Who's who in the election phone calls controversy | work=CBC News | date=February 29, 2012}}</ref> Elections Canada has made a statement<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=med&document=mar1512&dir=pre&lang=e |title=Elections Canada Online - News Releases and Media Advisories}}</ref> and reported to Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=med&document=mar2912&dir=spe&lang=e|title=Elections Canada Online - Statements and Speeches|publisher=}}</ref> that the fraud was extensive, affecting 200 ridings in all ten provinces plus [[Yukon]] Territory.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/politics/article/1153879--robocall-probe-stretches-to-200-ridings-across-canada-chief-electoral-officer-marc-mayrand-tells-commons-committee | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Susan | last=Delacourt | title=Robocall probe stretches to 200 ridings across Canada, chief electoral officer Marc Mayrand tells Commons committee | date=March 30, 2012}}</ref> The Council of Canadians, a left of centre activist group, has asserted that the robocalls may have been enough to swing the result by 4%, enough to win a number of ridings in very close races. A court challenge has been initiated by this group to overturn the results of the election in seven ridings, and initiate by-elections for the respective seven House of Commons seats.\n\nAfter reviewing the investigation of the \"Pierre Poutine\" scandal in 2013, Federal Court Judge Richard Mosley found that election fraud had taken place in six ridings across the country but found no evidence that the Conservative party or candidates were involved. He also did not find sufficient evidence to support charges in ridings other than Guelph. As well, he indicated that the \"robocalls\" had not affected the outcome of the 2011 election in any riding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/editorials/2014/08/14/greasy_robocall_scandal_will_haunt_conservatives_at_the_polls_editorial.html|title=Greasy \u2018robocall\u2019 scandal will haunt Conservatives at the polls: Editorial|date=August 14, 2014|work=thestar.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter a lengthy investigation of the circumstances of the scandal,<ref name=\"news.nationalpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/pierre-poutine-robocalls-planned-by-more-than-one-person-but-michael-sona-was-directing-mind-crown-says|title=\u2018Pierre Poutine\u2019 robocalls planned by \u2018more than one person,\u2019 but Michael Sona was \u2018directing mind,\u2019 Crown says - National Post|author=Stephen Maher, Postmedia News|date=June 9, 2014|work=National Post}}</ref> Michael Sona, the former director of communications for the Conservative candidate in the Guelph (Ontario) riding<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/michael-sona-wont-appeal-robocalls-conviction-but-will-seek-lighter-sentence-lawyer|title=Michael Sona won\u2019t appeal robocalls conviction but will seek lighter sentence: lawyer - National Post|author=Stephen Maher|date=April 9, 2015|work=National Post}}</ref> was charged on June 2, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/michael-sona-charged-with-guelph-robocalls-starts-trial-today-1.2659780|title=Michael Sona, charged with Guelph robocalls, starts trial today|date=June 2, 2014|publisher=}}</ref> with \"wilfully preventing or endeavouring to prevent an elector from voting\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kitchener.ctvnews.ca/trial-begins-monday-for-guelph-pc-staffer-charged-in-robocalls-scandal-1.1847885|title=Trial begins Monday for Guelph PC staffer charged in robocalls scandal|work=Kitchener}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/guelph-robocall-victims-ask-elections-canada-to-reopen-case-1.3158248|title=Guelph robocall victims ask Elections Canada to reopen case|date=July 17, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Sona was found guilty on November 14, 2014 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2014/11/19/michael-sona-sentenced-to-9-months-in-robocalls-scandal/|title=Michael Sona sentenced to 9 months in robocalls scandal|work=CityNews}}</ref> and was sentenced to nine months in jail plus twelve months of probation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/michael-sona-sentenced-to-9-months-in-jail-for-callous-robocalls-1.2839410|title=Found guilty of subverting democracy, Michael Sona sentenced to 9 months|publisher=}}</ref> Sona was released from jail on bail after serving twelve days, pending his appeal of the sentence. However, Sona did not appeal the conviction.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> During the trial, Justice Hearn agreed with the Crown allegation <ref name=\"news.nationalpost.com\"/> that Sona had likely not acted alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/robocalls-trial-michael-sona-sentenced-to-9-months-in-jail-1.2108744|title=Conservative staffer Michael Sona given 9-month jail sentence in Robocalls case - CTV News|work=CTVNews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/michael-sona-guilty-in-robocalls-trial-but-did-not-likely-act-alone-1.2735676|title=Michael Sona guilty in robocalls trial - but 'did not likely act alone'|date=August 14, 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n====Political calls====\nRobocalls are made by many political parties in the United States, including but not limited to both the Republican and Democratic parties as well as unaffiliated campaigns, [[527 organization]]s, unions, and individual citizens. Political robocalls are exempt from the [[United States National Do Not Call Registry]].<ref>The do-not-call list restricts \"telephone solicitations\" and does not apply to tax-exempt nonprofit organization. 47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(a)(3) defines \"telephone solicitations\"; 47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(c) enables the do-not-call list.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=National Do Not Call Registry |url=https://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0108-national-do-not-call-registry |website=Consumer Information |publisher=Federal Trade Commission |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref> The [[Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991]] (TCPA) and [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) regulations prohibit anyone (including charities, politicians and political parties) from making robocalls to cell phone numbers without the recipients' prior consent.<ref>47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(b)(1)(A); there are other prohibited destinations such as hospital rooms; some calls, such as those for an emergency purpose, are permitted.</ref> The FCC permits non-commercial robocalls to most residential (non-cellular) telephone lines.<ref>47 C.F.R. \u00a7&nbsp;64.1200(a)(2) [2007] permits non-commercial and tax-exempt nonprofit calls.</ref>\n\nThe federal [[Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991]] (TCPA) regulates automated calls.<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/47/227- Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991 (TCPA)], 47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227.</ref> All robocalls, irrespective of whether they are political in nature, must do two things to be considered legal. Federal law requires all telephone calls using pre-recorded messages to identify who is initiating the calls and include a telephone number or address whereby the initiator can be reached.<ref>47 U.S.C. \u00a7&nbsp;227(d)(3); 47 C.F.R. \u00a764.1200(b)</ref>\n\nSome states (23 according to DMNews) have laws that regulate or prohibit political robocalls.<ref name=\"states\">[http://www.dmnews.com/cms/dm-news/legal-privacy/38770.html States enforce limits on robocalls] \u2013 DMNews, \"States enforce limits on robocalls\"</ref> [[Robocall#Indiana|Indiana]] and [[North Dakota]] prohibit automated political calls.<ref name = \"UPI\">[http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/view.php?StoryID=20061105-010536-9525r Phonebank accents irk congressman] \u2013 UPI, November 5, 2006.</ref> In [[New Hampshire]], political robocalls are allowed, except when the recipient is in the [[United States National Do Not Call Registry|National Do Not Call Registry]].<ref name=\"Concord Monitor\">[http://www.concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061105/REPOSITORY/611050397 Repeat calls not from Hodes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070519052740/http://www.concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20061105%2FREPOSITORY%2F611050397 |date=May 19, 2007 }} \u2013 [[Concord Monitor]], November 5, 2006. \"Repeat calls not from Hodes\"</ref> Many states require the disclosure of who paid for the call, often requiring such notice be recorded in the candidate's own voice. The patch-work of state laws regulating political robocalls has created problems for national campaigns.<ref name = \"Regulating Robocalls\">[http://ssrn.com/abstract=1309780 Regulating Robocalls: Are Automated Calls the Sound of, or a Threat to, Democracy?] \u2013 [[Michigan Telecommunications and Technology Law Review]], Forthcoming 2009. \"Regulating Robocalls: Are Automated Calls the Sound of, or a Threat to, Democracy?\"</ref>\n\n====California====\nThe first political robo calls were launched in January 1983 when business owner Tony Inocentes used his telemarketing machine from his collection agency business to announce his candidacy for the 57th Assembly District in California. He launched over 300,000 automated calls before losing the November 1983 General election to the incumbent Dave Elder. Inocentes founded the GOTV election company ePolitical USA in 1984.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 2001 Inocentes invented political robo polling launching the first political robo poll on October 31, 2001 in the Lynwood, CA city council elections.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n[[California]] prohibits any robocall unless there is an existing relationship.<ref name=\"Cal PUC\">{{cite web|url=http://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displayText.xhtml?division=1.&chapter=10.&part=2.&lawCode=PUC&article=1.|title=Codes Display Text|author=|date=|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> The California Public Utilities Code \u00a7\u00a7 2871 ''et seq.'' holds political campaigns to the same rules as other organizations making calls with an automatic dialing\u2013announcing device.<ref name=\"Cal PUC\"/> The guidelines are:\n* A person must come on the line before the recording to identify the nature of the call and the organization behind it.\n* The recipient of the call must consent to the recording being played.\n* The call must be disconnected from the telephone line as soon as the message is over or the recipient hangs up, whichever comes first.\n\n====Indiana====\nIndiana requires introduction of any prerecorded message by a live operator; the message may only be played if the called party grants permission.<ref name=\"states\"/>\n\n====Missouri====\nIn September 2008, then-[[Missouri Attorney General]] [[Jay Nixon]] alerted political campaigns in Missouri that his office would aggressively enforce federal rules (Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991) requiring calls to include identifying and contact information.<ref>Attorney General's News Release. [http://ago.mo.gov/newsreleases/2008/Federal_law_requires_robo_calls_to_include_identifying_and_contact_information/ Nixon alerts political campaigns that federal law requires \u201crobo-calls\u201d to include identifying and contact information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917151456/http://ago.mo.gov/newsreleases/2008/Federal_law_requires_robo_calls_to_include_identifying_and_contact_information/ |date=September 17, 2008 }}. September 4, 2008.</ref>\n\n====North Carolina====\nRobocalls were made during the [[North Carolina Democratic primary, 2008|2008 North Carolina Democratic primary]], targeting [[African-American]] voters in the days leading up to the primary in late April 2008,<ref>[http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/elections_board_hunting_robocaller \"Elections board hunting robocaller] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620103015/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/elections_board_hunting_robocaller |date=June 20, 2008 }},\" ''The [[News & Observer]]'', April 28, 2008. Accessed April 29, 2008.</ref> which essentially told registered voters that they were not registered.<ref>[https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2008/4/29/505589/- Daily Kos Blog].{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2008}} (blog) Accessed April 29, 2008.</ref>\nAccording to [[NPR]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=90114863|title=Group with Clinton Ties Behind Dubious Robocalls|date=May 1, 2008|work=NPR.org}}</ref> and Facing South,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southernstudies.org/facingsouth/2008/05/center-for-investigative-reporting.asp|title=- The Institute for Southern Studies|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208044411/http://southernstudies.org/facingsouth/2008/05/center-for-investigative-reporting.asp|archivedate=February 8, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> these calls were made by the organization \"[[Women's Voices Women Vote]]\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">Murray, Shailagh, \"Women's Voices, Women Vote: Did the Outreach Overreach?\", ''Washington Post'', Sunday, May 4, 2008; Page A10, found at [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/05/03/AR2008050301870.html Washington Post article on Women's Voices Women Vote]. Accessed May 5, 2008.</ref> Voters and watchdog groups complained that it was a [[Voter intimidation|turnout-suppression]] effort, and the state Attorney General [[Roy A. Cooper|Roy Cooper]] ordered them to stop making the calls.<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\"/> The group stopped the calls and no further legal action was taken.\n\n====South Carolina====\n{{Main|Cahaly v. LaRosa}}\n\n[[South Carolina]] had a law prohibiting most types of unsolicited consumer and political robocalls, but in 2010, campaign consultant Robert Cahaly was arrested by the South Carolina State Law Enforcement Division, being charged for making illegal robocalls to six state house districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wistv.com/story/13429729/gop-consultant-to-face-sled-arrest-for-illegal-robocalls|title= GOP consultant arrested for illegal \"robocalls\"|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> The automated opinion polling system asked whether [[Nancy Pelosi|U.S. Speaker Nancy Pelosi]] should be invited to campaign with six Democratic candidates for the South Carolina Legislature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law360.com/articles/699756/call-me-unconstitutional-hang-up-for-sc-s-robocall-law|title= Call Me Unconstitutional: Hang-Up For SC's Robocall Law|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> Cahaly was arrested despite having a written opinion from the state attorney general stating that he had acted within the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitsnews.com/2015/08/18/fourth-circuit-sc-robocall-ban-is-unconstitutional/|title= Fourth Circuit: SC Robocall Ban Is Unconstitutional|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> The charges were subsequently dismissed in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20121006/PC16/121009479/1031/charges-of-illegal-robo-calls-against-gop-consultant-dismissed|title= Charges Against GOP Consultant Cahaly Dropped|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref> After the charges were dropped, Cahaly filed a suit against state officials, claiming his constitutional right to free speech had been violated. U.S. district court judge, [[J. Michelle Childs|Michelle Childs]] ruled that South Carolina's anti-robocall statute was a content-based restriction on speech and therefore unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestate.com/news/politics-government/politics-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article13862843.html|title= Fed Court rules law Cahaly charged under unconstitutional|accessdate=Oct 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed additional regulations====\nCalifornia Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]] (D-CA) introduced the Federal Robocall Privacy Act<ref name=hearing>\n{{cite web |title=Protecting Voters at Home and at the Polls: Limiting Abusive Robocalls and Vote Caging Practices |url=https://www.rules.senate.gov/hearings/protecting-voters-at-home-and-at-the-polls-limiting-abusive-robocalls-and-vote-caging-practices |website=Rules of the Senate |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref> in February 2008 at a Senate Committee on Rules and Administration hearing. The Act proposed to: 1) limit robocalls to no more than two a day by any one candidate, 2) mandate that candidates have accurate caller ID numbers displayed, 3) mandate that the disclosure of who is paying for the call occur at the start of the call, rather than at the end of the call, and 4) mandate that the time of the call occur not before 8{{nbsp}}a.m. or after 9{{nbsp}}p.m. The bill was read twice, and since it received no further action during the session, it did not become law.<ref name=\"govtrack.us\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=s110-2624 S. 2624: Robocall Privacy Act of 2008]. Accessed January 4, 2009.</ref> Similar bills have been submitted in subsequent years without success.<ref>[http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2014/02/05/schumer-pushes-bill-expand-robocall-ban/5231415/ Schumer pushes bill to expand robocall ban]. Democrat and Chronicle. Accessed October 11, 2014</ref>\n\nShaun Dakin, CEO of [[Citizens for Civil Discourse]], testified at the hearing and described how robocalls affect the lives of voters across the nation.<ref name=hearing/> He also wrote an op-ed for the ''Washington Post'' calling for a Voter Privacy Bill of Rights in which all voters would have the right to opt out of political robocalls if they did not wish to receive them.<ref>Washington Post. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/12/AR2008091202658.html A Privacy Shield Against the Campaigns]. Shaun Dakin. Saturday, September 13, 2008; Page A17.</ref>\n\nDakin, a former [[John Kerry]] campaign worker,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stoppoliticalcalls.org/ht/display/ArticleDetails/i/23669/pid/700|title=Stop political robocalls and telemarketers with Nomorobo|publisher=}}</ref> set up a website called Stoppoliticalcalls.org and claimed to allow citizens to opt out of receiving robocalls.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/10/23/robo.calls/index.html |date=October 23, 2008 |accessdate=May 22, 2010 |publisher=CNN |title=Robocalls flood phone lines in battleground states}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todaystmj4.com/features/call4action/30567724.html |title=Stop the Calls |publisher=NBC Affiliate TMJ |accessdate=June 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120102026/http://www.todaystmj4.com/features/call4action/30567724.html |archivedate=November 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,430242,00.html |title=Tech Q and A: I Am Serious. And Don't Call Me Shirley |author=Guy R. Briggs |publisher=Fox News |date=September 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-10073249-38.html?tag=newsLeadStoriesArea.0 |publisher=CNET.com |title=Election Day brings invasion of robocalls |date=October 23, 2008 |author=Stephanie Condon}}</ref> However, there is no guarantee that the registry will stop the calls and since there is no law that supports the database it is essentially an [[Internet petition]]. As mentioned above, the Robocall Privacy Act failed to become law and neither bill had provisions for a do-not-call registry for stopping robocalls.<ref name=\"govtrack.us\"/><ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h110-5747 H.R. 5747: Robocall Privacy Act of 2008]. Accessed October 23, 2008.</ref>\n\nDespite heavy media publicity of the database, only seven politicians in the United States voluntarily pledged to respect the list during the 2008 general election cycle. Of those seven, only three made it to the general election and only [[Virginia Foxx]] (R) was successfully reelected in November 2008.\n\nOn September 1, 2009, a new regulation of the [[Federal Trade Commission]] went into effect, banning most robocalls without written opt-in from the receiver.<ref>[http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/08/robocalls.shtm \"New Rule Prohibiting Unwanted \"Robocalls\" to Take Effect on September 1\", FTC News Release August 27, 2009] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003154923/http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/08/robocalls.shtm |date=October 3, 2011 }}</ref> Political campaigns, surveys, charities, debt collectors, and health care providers are exempt, as are calls to businesses. Calls from banks, insurers, and phone companies are out of the jurisdiction of the FTC. In situations under federal jurisdiction, the federal law will supersede a slightly less restrictive law in the state of California.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/pender/detail?&entry_id=46359 |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |title=Kathleen Pender - Net Worth Plus : FTC is putting an end to most robo calls |date=August 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Reverse robocalling==\nIn December 2011 reporting described \"robocall revenge\" where voters can turn the table and send robocalls to politicians and others using online website tools.<ref>{{cite news | first = Ambreen | last = Ali | title = Website Seeks Robocall Revenge | date = December 8, 2011 | url = http://www.rollcall.com/news/website_seeks_robocall_revenge-210937-1.html?pos=opolh | work = [[Roll Call]] | accessdate =December 28, 2011 | quote = Launched last month, Reverse Robocall has already helped individuals and advocacy groups make nearly 2,000 calls to lawmakers, politicians and private companies.}}</ref>\n\n==Suppressing unwanted and illegal robocalls==\nMany robocalls are not wanted, and several methods have been developed to prevent unwanted robocalls. Many countries operate [[do not call list]]s, but the lists have been ineffective<ref>{{cite news|title=No hiding from nuisance calls|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/10108666/No-hiding-from-nuisance-calls.html|accessdate=12 December 2016|publisher=The Telegraph|date=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://consumersunion.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Dialing-Back-Complete-Report-11.16.2015.pdf |title=Dialing Back: How Phone Companies Can End Unwanted Robocalls |last=Mahoney |first=Maureen |year=2015 |website=Consumers Union |publisher=Consumers Union |page=3 |format=PDF |publication-date=November 2015}}</ref> and legally problematic in some cases.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Strauss|first1=Jared|title=The Do-Not-Call List's Big Hang-up|journal=Richmond Journal of Law & Technology|date=2004|volume=X|issue=4|url=http://jolt.richmond.edu/v10i4/article27.pdf|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> Consequently, a market has developed for products that allow consumers to block robocalls. Most products use methods similar to those used to mitigate [[VoIP spam|SPIT]] (spam over Internet telephony) and can be broadly categorised by the primary method used. However, due to the complexity of the problem, no single method is sufficiently reliable.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ziming_Zhao/publication/299794558_SoK_Everyone_Hates_Robocalls_A_Survey_of_Techniques_against_Telephone_Spam/links/5705504308ae13eb88b959e5.pdf |title=SoK: Everyone Hates Robocalls: A Survey of Techniques Against Telephone Spam |last=Huahong |first=Tu |last2=Doup\u00e9 |first2=Adam |year=2016 |publisher=University of Arizona |page=14 |format=pdf |last3=Zhao |first3=Ziming |last4=Ahn |first4=Gail-Joon |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nSolutions are available as both hardware and software products. [[Mobile app]]s are especially prevalent as they use techniques which do not require the modification of infrastructure. Many products are limited to use only on a single medium, such as traditional copper landlines, or [[mobile phone]] contracts from a specific [[mobile phone operator]].\n\n=== Blacklisting and whitelisting ===\nIn its simplest form, this method offers the ability to prevent further calls from phone numbers, once they are known to be a source of robocalls. Many mobile apps can prevent robocalls with a user generated [[Blacklist (computing)|blacklist]].\n\n[[File:Call-blocker-wikipedia.jpg|thumb|Landline call blocker in use]]\n\nFor landlines there are standalone call blockers which connect to the telephone. Various models work on blacklisting and whitelisting principles. Call blockers received attention from publications including [[Which?]] and [[Consumer Reports]] in the United Kingdom and United States respectively.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leedham |first1=Robert |title=Call blocking devices \u2013 everything you need to know |url=http://blogs.which.co.uk/technology/phones-3/call-blocking-devices-eveything-you-need-to-know/ |website=which.co.uk |publisher=Which? |accessdate=22 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701075905/http://blogs.which.co.uk/technology/phones-3/call-blocking-devices-eveything-you-need-to-know/ |archivedate=2016-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rage against robocalls|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/magazine/2015/07/robocall-blocker-review/index.htm|website=consumerreports.org|publisher=Consumer Reports|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK [[BT Group|BT]] operates a service for landlines called Choose to Refuse which allows customers to block up to 10 phone numbers of their choice for a monthly fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=All about Choose to Refuse|url=http://bt.custhelp.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/8500/~/all-about-choose-to-refuse|website=BT.com Help|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nA number of physical products have been developed for use with landlines. These are typically installed in homes and employ a [[Hard coding|hard coded]] or irregularly updated blacklist. Some models also have the function to create a user-generated whitelist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/magazine/2015/07/robocall-blocker-review/index.htm|title=Robocall blocker review|last=|first=|date=14 August 2015|website=Consumer Reports|publisher=|language=en|publication-date=|access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref> Newer devices for landlines can use cloud based data to resolve the hard coded blacklist issues and allow you to create your own whitelist/blacklist.\n\n=== Crowdsourcing ===\nA more sophisticated model uses [[crowdsourcing]] to build a more comprehensive blacklist of robocall numbers. A notable example of this is the app [[Truecaller]], which requires users to provide access to their personal [[whitelist]] of genuine contacts in exchange for access to the larger crowdsourced database. In 2013, hackers gained access to Truecaller's database of known genuine numbers, highlighting the danger of centralising this information.<ref>{{cite web|title=Truecaller Statement|url=https://blog.truecaller.com/2013/07/18/truecaller-statement/|website=Truecaller Blog|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=en|date=5 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ehackingnews.com/2013/07/truecaller-database-hacked-by-syrian.html|title=Truecaller Database hacked by Syrian Electronic Army|last=|first=|date=16 July 2013|work=|access-date=|via=E Hacking News}}</ref>\n\n=== CAPTCHA ===\nBuilding on the crowdsourcing model, [[Primus Canada]] launched a patented product called Telemarketing Guard for [[landlines]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stein|first1=Matthew|title=Stopping Fraudulent Robocall Scams: Can More Be Done?|url=https://www.commerce.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/ef5915d3-e47e-4834-9a42-a4393ea03d9c/AB13B79566335ED657BFD89A085CCCA1.stein2.pdf|website=United States Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation|accessdate=21 November 2016|page=1|language=en|format=pdf|date=10 July 2013}}</ref> It improves on previous models by including a [[CAPTCHA]] style challenge-response test.\n\nBased on a database developed from customer feedback, it filters suspected telemarketing calls to a system which challenges callers to record their name after pressing a button. If a name is recorded, the customer's phone rings with the [[Caller ID]] of Telemarketing Guard. If they answer the phone, they are played the recording, at which point they can accept the call or decline and report it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Call-Blocking Technology|url=https://www.ftc.gov/sites/default/files/documents/public_events/robocalls-all-rage-ftc-summit/robocalls-part7-call-blocking.pdf|website=Federal Trade Commission|accessdate=21 November 2016|page=19|language=en|format=pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Realtime analysis ===\nA major problem for the use of both blacklisting and whitelisting techniques is the practice of [[caller ID spoofing]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Scam Alert - How Scammers Use Caller ID Spoofing to Pose as You|url=http://www.bbb.org/council/news-events/bbb-scam-alerts/2014/06/scam-alert-how-scammers-use-caller-id-spoofing-to-pose-as-you/|website=Council of Better Business Bureaus|accessdate=21 November 2016|language=en|date=20 June 2014}}</ref> which is prevalent as a result of the low [[Barriers to entry|barrier to entry]] in the [[Voice over IP|VoIP]] services market.<ref>{{harvnb|Huahong|Doup\u00e9|Zhao|Ahn|2016|p=2}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 the [[Federal Communications Commission]] proposed a framework for the telecommunications industry in the United States, which included a validation system at network level for robocalls from [[Session Initiation Protocol|SIP]] sources by 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=CGB Announces Agenda for Robocall and Caller ID Spoofing Workshop on September 16, 2015|url=https://apps.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-15-1001A1_Rcd.pdf|website=Federal Communications Commission|accessdate=21 November 2016|pages=9880\u20139881|language=en|format=pdf|date=10 September 2015}}</ref> The final authentication task in the framework is the signing of all VoIP calls, which would allow carriers to reliably identify robocalls.\n\nUntil these goals are achieved, a more advanced method for blocking robocalls uses [[real-time business intelligence]] techniques to address the constantly changing identities of robocalls. With access to a large enough data sample, it is possible to create algorithms which detect call patterns without requiring reporting by users.\n\nIn 2016, both [[Verizon Wireless|Verizon]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Verizon Caller Name ID|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/solutions-and-services/caller-name-id/}}</ref> and [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] each launched their own service based on Enhanced Caller ID, which is developed by Cequint and incorporates whitelisting, blacklisting and crowdsourcing techniques.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=TNS and Cequint Deploy Next Generation Robocall Solution Delivering Best-in-Class Service for Sprint Customers |date=30 November 2016 |publisher=Business Wire |location=Reston, Virginia |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20161130005642/en/}}</ref> For improved accuracy, it is complemented by a technology called Call Guardian developed by [[Transaction Network Services|TNS]], which performs caller behavior analysis on the 25 billion public calls they handle every year in real time.<ref>{{cite web|title=TNS Call Guardian|url=http://www.tnsi.com/products-services/telecom/protecting/tns-call-guardian/|website=TNS|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nStarting in mid-2017, and with intended culmination in 2019, the FCC pushed forward Caller ID certification implemented via a methodology of [[Caller ID spoofing#United States|SHAKEN/STIR]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.fcc.gov/call-authentication |title= Combating Spoofed Robocalls with Caller ID Authentication |publisher= [[FCC]] |date= 2017 |first= Ajit |last= Pai }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2019/02/ajit-pai-orders-phone-companies-to-adopt-new-anti-robocall-tech-in-2019/ |title= Ajit Pai orders phone companies to adopt new anti-robocall tech in 2019 |publisher= Arstechnica |date= Feb 14, 2019 |first= Jon |last= Brodkin }}</ref> In June 2019, the FCC adopted a rule allowing (but not mandating) phone companies to block unwanted robocalls by default, without a consumer opt-in; a rule related to source authentication was still in a public comment period.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2019/06/06/730415950/heres-why-you-may-start-receiving-fewer-robocalls Here's Why You May Start Receiving Fewer Robocalls]</ref>\n\nThe TRACED Act, signed into law in December 2019, requires the FCC to implement Caller ID authentication, requires the FCC to report all criminal robocalls to the Justice Department, gives consumers access to robocall blocking at no charge, and increases penalties for violators.<ref>[https://www.zdnet.com/article/trump-signs-the-traced-act-the-first-federal-anti-robocall-law/ Trump signs the TRACED Act, the first federal anti-robocall law]</ref>\n\n==Enforcement==\n\nIn August 2016, a \"Robocall Strike Force\" of thirty companies said they would help crack down on the problem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-robocalls/att-apple-google-to-work-on-robocall-crackdown-idUSKCN10U18L|title=AT&T, Apple, Google to work on 'robocall' crackdown|date=August 20, 2016|publisher=|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Federal Communications Commission Declaratory Rulings===\n\nAfter receiving more than 215,000 consumer complaints in 2014 alone, the U.S. Federal Communications Commission (FCC) strengthened and clarified its regulations protecting consumers from unwanted robocalls and spam emails and texts. The Commission issued a package of declaratory rulings in June 2015 that clarified the provisions of the Telephone Consumer Protection Act (TCPA) that deal with prerecorded and artificial voice calls received by residential wireline phones as well as wireless numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://incompliancemag.com/commission-strengthens-consumer-protections-against-robocalls/|title=Commission Strengthens Consumer Protections Against Robocalls|work=In Compliance Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ruane |first1=Kathleen Ann |title=(Robo)call Me Maybe: Robocalls to Wireless Phones Under the Telephone Consumer Protection Act |date=May 29, 2018 |publisher=Congressional Research Service |location=Washington, DC |url=https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo130753 |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2009 Federal Trade Commission action against an illegal robocall provider===\nIn May 2009, in response to numerous complaints, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] asked a federal court to shut down a telemarketing campaign that has been bombarding U.S. consumers with hundreds of millions of allegedly deceptive robocalls in an effort to sell them vehicle service contracts under the guise that they are extensions of original vehicle [[Warranty|warranties]].<ref>http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2009/09/twi.shtm, \"FTC Settlement Bans Robocalls from Auto \"Warranty\" Company\", FTC News Release, 9/1/2009</ref> The FTC took action against both the promoter of the phony extended auto warranties, as well as the telemarketing company that it hired to carry out its illegal, deceptive campaign. The FTC contends that the companies are operating a massive telemarketing scheme that uses random, pre-recorded phone calls to deceive consumers into thinking that their vehicle's warranty is about to expire. Consumers who respond to the robocalls are pressured to purchase extended service contracts for their vehicles, which the telemarketers falsely portray as an extension of the manufacturer's original warranty. According to papers the FTC filed with the court, however, the robocalls have prompted tens of thousands of complaints from consumers who are either on the United States National Do Not Call Registry or asked not to be called. Five telephone numbers associated with the defendants have generated a total of 30,000 Do Not Call complaints. Consumers received the robocalls at home, work, and on their cell phones, sometimes several times in one day. Businesses, government offices and even 911 dispatchers have been subjected to the calls.\n\nThose who answer the pre-recorded calls hear a message telling them that their vehicle warranty is about to expire and that they should \"extend coverage before it is too late\". They are told to \"press one\" to speak to a \"warranty specialist\". The \"specialists\" then mislead consumers into believing that their company is affiliated with the dealer or manufacturer of the consumer's vehicle. They try to sell consumers a service contract for between $2,000 and $3,000, which they falsely portray as an extension of the vehicle's original warranty. The seller of extended auto warranties sued by the FTC allegedly took in more than $10 million on the sale of these deceptively marketed service contracts. In their robocalls, the companies dialed every phone number within a particular area code and prefix sequentially, without knowing whether the consumers called were motorists or owned motor vehicles, or whether those consumers' numbers were on the Do Not Call Registry. Consumers who asked that the calls be stopped often were met with \"abusive behavior\" or were simply hung up on, according to the papers filed with the court. Some of the defendants used offshore shell corporations to try to avoid scrutiny, and a top officer in the telemarketing company bragged to prospective clients that he could operate outside the law without any chance of being caught by the FTC, the papers stated. This defendant also claimed that he makes 1.8 million dials per day and that he had done more than $40 million worth of dialing for extended warranty companies, including one billion dials on behalf of his largest client, according to the court papers filed by the FTC. In addition to the robocalls, the FTC charged that the company selling the warranties mails out deceptive postcards to consumers, warning them about the imminent expiration of their auto warranties. The postcards are designed to mislead consumers into believing that they are being contacted by their dealer or manufacturer, and the postcards offer consumers the chance to \"renew\" their original warranties.<ref name=\"case\">[https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20090515-717706.html FTC: Judge Orders Halt To Robocalls Selling Deceptive Warranties], ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', May 15, 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714024144/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20090515-717706.html |date=July 14, 2009 }}</ref> On May 15, 2009 U.S. District Judge [[John Francis Grady|John F. Grady]] issued the temporary restraining order against the defendants Transcontinental Warranty Inc. and Voice Touch Inc. Grady's orders also applied to Transcontinental CEO and President Christopher Cowart, Voice Touch executives James and Maureen Dunne, Voice Touch business partner Network Foundations LLC and Network Foundations executive Damian Kohlfeld. Besides ordering a halt to the automatic telephone sales calls, Grady's order froze the assets of the two companies. The FTC alleged in its complaints that the calls were part of a deceptive scheme and asked the court to assure the assets will not be lost in case they might be needed to repay consumers who have been victimized. The FTC isn't immediately seeking civil fines against the companies but may do so later, agency officials said. Attorneys general in Arkansas, Indiana and Missouri have taken similar actions over calls offering extended warranties on automobiles.<ref name=\"case1\">[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jFpGIsUi1KVrRr07BBoVqLrkz0ZQD986V9404 Judge blocks 'robo-calls' selling car warranties], [[Associated Press]], May 15, 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607220858/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jFpGIsUi1KVrRr07BBoVqLrkz0ZQD986V9404 |date=June 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Voice broadcasting]]\n* [[Ringless voicemail]]\n* [[Cold calling]]\n* [[Google Duplex]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://complaints.donotcall.gov/complaint/complaintcheck.aspx  National Do Not Call Registry Complaints]\n*[https://consumercomplaints.fcc.gov/hc/en-us Federal Communications Commission Consumer Complaint Center]\n*[https://www.nomorobo.com Nomorobo.com]\n\n{{Spamming}}\n\n[[Category:Telemarketing]]\n[[Category:Neologisms]]\n", "name_user": "Corn cheese", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReverse robocalling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robocall"}
{"title_page": "Rockingham War Memorial", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Rockingham Naval Memorial Park}}\n{{Infobox military memorial\n| name             = Rockingham War Memorial\n| country          = Australia\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| body             = \n| image            = File:Rockingham War Memorial, view from the north-west, March 2020.jpg\n| caption          = The Rockingham War Memorial\n| commemorates     = [[World War I]]{{-}}[[World War II]]{{-}}[[Korean War]]{{-}}[[Vietnam War]]\n| use_dates        = <!--(Do not use if parameter \"commemorates\" is used)-->\n| established      = {{start date|2005|08|13}}\n| unveiled         = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|-32.276389|115.7322|display=inline,title}}\n| location         = [[Rockingham, Western Australia|Rockingham]], [[Western Australia]]\n| nearest_town     = \n| designer         = \n| total_burials    = \n| unknowns         = \n| commemorated     = \n| by_country       = \n| by_war           = \n| inscription      = \n| embedded         = \n| source           = [http://monumentaustralia.org.au/display/61111-city-of-rockingham-war-memorial- monumentaustralia.org.au]\n}}\nThe '''Rockingham War Memorial''' is a [[List of Australian military memorials|military memorial]] in the [[City of Rockingham]], [[Western Australia]], dedicated to what is now the [[Australian Defence Force]].<ref name=\"Memorial\" >{{cite web |url=http://monumentaustralia.org.au/display/61111-city-of-rockingham-war-memorial- |title=Rockingham War Memorial |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=monumentaustralia.org.au |publisher= |access-date=1 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Memorial==\n[[File:Rockingham War Memorial, August 2019 03.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bronze soldier at the memorial]]\nThe monument was dedicated on 13 August 2005 by [[Mark McGowan]], then Western Australian Minister for Tourism, Racing and Gaming, Barry Sammels, Mayor of the City of Rockingham, and Mark Stevens, President of the City of Rockingham RSL Sub-Branch.<ref name=\"Memorial\" /> The dedication took place two days before the 60th anniversary of [[Victory over Japan Day]].<ref name=\"Stevens\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.ausemade.com.au/war-memorial/wa/rockingham/wm-wa-rockingham.htm|title=Rockingham War Memorial|author=Mark Stevens (President City of Rockingham RSL)|date= |website=ausemade.com.au |publisher= |access-date=1 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe centre piece of the war memorial was originally located on the opposite side of Flinders Lane but relocated to it's current location in 2007, when the area was redeveloped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://inherit.stateheritage.wa.gov.au/Public/Inventory/Details/70becd99-71c9-4feb-83c4-af78a522a149|title=Flinder\u2019s Hall and Rose Garden (fmr)|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=inherit.stateheritage.wa.gov.au |publisher=Heritage Council of Western Australia |access-date=1 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe memorials main feature are it's thirteen classical styled columns, one for each major conflict Australia participated in. The 5.5 metre tall columns are arranged in a circle of a diameter of 30 metres. A fourteenth column socket has been left empty to commemorate Australian soldiers missing in action. The three branches of the Australian Defence Force, Army, Air Force and Navy, are represented by a [[Ordnance QF 25-pounder|QF 25-pounder field gun]], a propeller and an anchor. The entrance to the memorial is guarded by two bronze soldiers, created by Perth sculptor Andrew Kay. Each weights 160 kilograms and is double the human size.<ref name=\"Stevens\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Category:Rockingham War Memorial|Rockingham War Memorial}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:City of Rockingham]]\n[[Category:Australian military memorials]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Rockingham Naval Memorial Park}}\n{{Infobox military memorial\n| name             = Rockingham War Memorial\n| country          = Australia\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| body             = \n| image            = File:Rockingham War Memorial, view from the north-west, March 2020.jpg\n| caption          = The Rockingham War Memorial\n| commemorates     = [[World War I]]{{-}}[[World War II]]{{-}}[[Korean War]]{{-}}[[Vietnam War]]\n| use_dates        = <!--(Do not use if parameter \"commemorates\" is used)-->\n| established      = {{start date|2005|08|13}}\n| unveiled         = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|-32.276389|115.7322|display=inline,title}}\n| location         = [[Rockingham, Western Australia|Rockingham]], [[Western Australia]]\n| nearest_town     = \n| designer         = \n| total_burials    = \n| unknowns         = \n| commemorated     = \n| by_country       = \n| by_war           = \n| inscription      = \n| embedded         = \n| source           = [http://monumentaustralia.org.au/display/61111-city-of-rockingham-war-memorial- monumentaustralia.org.au]\n}}\nThe '''Rockingham War Memorial''' is a [[List of Australian military memorials|military memorial]] in the [[City of Rockingham]], [[Western Australia]], dedicated to what is now the [[Australian Defence Force]].<ref name=\"Memorial\" >{{cite web |url=http://monumentaustralia.org.au/display/61111-city-of-rockingham-war-memorial- |title=Rockingham War Memoria |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=monumentaustralia.org.au |publisher= |access-date=1 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Memorial==\n[[File:Rockingham War Memorial, August 2019 03.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bronze soldier at the memorial]]\nThe monument was dedicated on 13 August 2005 by [[Mark McGowan]], then Western Australian Minister for Tourism, Racing and Gaming, Barry Sammels, Mayor of the City of Rockingham, and Mark Stevens, President of the City of Rockingham RSL Sub-Branch.<ref name=\"Memorial\" /> The dedication took place two days before the 60th anniversary of [[Victory over Japan Day]].<ref name=\"Stevens\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.ausemade.com.au/war-memorial/wa/rockingham/wm-wa-rockingham.htm|title=Rockingham War Memorial|author=Mark Stevens (President City of Rockingham RSL)|date= |website=ausemade.com.au |publisher= |access-date=1 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe centre piece of the war memorial was originally located on the opposite side of Flinders Lane but relocated to it's current location in 2007, when the area was redeveloped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://inherit.stateheritage.wa.gov.au/Public/Inventory/Details/70becd99-71c9-4feb-83c4-af78a522a149|title=Flinder\u2019s Hall and Rose Garden (fmr)|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=inherit.stateheritage.wa.gov.au |publisher=Heritage Council of Western Australia |access-date=1 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe memorials main feature are it's thirteen classical styled columns, one for each major conflict Australia participated in. The 5.5 metre tall columns are arranged in a circle of a diameter of 30 metres. A fourteenth column socket has been left empty to commemorate Australian soldiers missing in action. The three branches of the Australian Defence Force, Army, Air Force and Navy, are represented by a [[Ordnance QF 25-pounder|QF 25-pounder field gun]], a propeller and an anchor. The entrance to the memorial is guarded by two bronze soldiers, created by Perth sculptor Andrew Kay. Each weights 160 kilograms and is double the human size.<ref name=\"Stevens\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Category:Rockingham War Memorial|Rockingham War Memorial}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:City of Rockingham]]\n[[Category:Australian military memorials]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Calistemon", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rockingham_War_Memorial"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Bhalerao", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = [[Bishop in the Catholic Church|Bishop]]\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name             = Thomas Bhalerao\n| honorific_suffix = [[Society of Jesus|S.J.]]\n| title            = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik|Bishop Emeritus of Nashik]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bombay|Archdiocese of Bombay]]\n| province         = [[Bombay]]\n| metropolis       = [[Bombay]]\n| diocese          =  [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik]]\n| see              = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik]] ([[emeritus]])\n| term_start       = 31 March 2007\n| term_end         = 13 February 2015\n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = Bishop Valerian D\u2019Souza\n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = Bishop of Nashik.<sup>'''''(1987-2007)'''''</sup>\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 27 March 1965\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = 23 August 1987\n| consecrated_by   = [[Simon Pimenta|Archbishop Simon Pimenta]]\n| cardinal         = \n| created_cardinal_by = \n| rank             = [[File:Prelate-Bishop.svg|35px]] [[Hierarchy of the Catholic Church|Bishop-Priest]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Thomas Bhalerao\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1933|02|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Sangamner]], [[Maharashtra]].\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2015|02|13|1933|02|01|df=y}}\n| death_place      = St. Luke\u2019s Hospital, Sreerampur, [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| buried           =  St. Mary\u2019s Church, [[Sangamner]], [[Ahmednagar]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|19.5612|N|74.2187|E|}}\n| nationality      = {{flagicon|India}} Indian\n| religion         = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence        = Sreerampur\n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\n{{Infobox bishop styles\n|bishop name = Thomas Bhalerao\n|dipstyle= [[Bishop]]\n|offstyle= Your Excellency\n|relstyle= The Most Reverend\n}}\n{{Ordination\n| ordained deacon by = \n| date of diaconal ordination = \n| place of diaconal ordination = \n| ordained priest by = \n| date of priestly ordination = 27 March 1965\n| place of priestly ordination =  \n| consecrated by = [[Simon Ignatius Pimenta|Archbishop Simon Ignatius Pimenta]]\n| co-consecrators = Bishop Valerian D\u2019Souza,<br />Bishop Charles Gomes, S.J.\n| date of consecration = 23 August 1987\n| place of consecration = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Bhalerao''' (1 February 1933 &ndash; 13 February 2015<ref>[http://cbci.in/FullNews.aspx?Id=1499 Most Rev. Thomas Bhalerao, SJ, Bishop Emeritus of the Diocese of Nashik passed away] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216155607/http://cbci.in/FullNews.aspx?Id=1499 |date=16 February 2015 }}</ref>\n) was an Indian [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priest and, from 1987, the [[Roman Catholic]] bishop of Nashik.\n\nOrdained to the [[Catholic priesthood|priesthood]] in the [[Society of Jesus]] in 1965, Bhalerao was named bishop of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik]], [[India]], in 1987. He resigned in 2007.\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbhalerao.html Profile of Mons. Bhalerao] ''www.catholic-hierarchy.org'' [[Wikipedia:Verifiability#Reliable sources|{{sup|{{small|[''self-published'']}}}}]]\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhalerao, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Indian Roman Catholic bishops]]\n\n\n{{india-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = [[Bishop in the Catholic Church|Bishop]]\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name             = Thomas Bhalerao\n| honorific_suffix = [[Society of Jesus|S.J.]]\n| title            = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik|Bishop Emeritus of Nashik]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bombay|Archdiocese of Bombay]]\n| province         = [[Bombay]]\n| metropolis       = [[Bombay]]\n| diocese          =  [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik]]\n| see              = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashik]] ([[emeritus]])\n| term_start       = 31 March 2007\n| term_end         = 13 February 2015\n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = Bishop Valerian D\u2019Souza\n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = Bishop of Nashik.<sup>'''''(1987-2007)'''''</sup>\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 27 March 1965\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = 23 August 1987\n| consecrated_by   = [[Simon Pimenta|Archbishop Simon Pimenta]]\n| cardinal         = \n| created_cardinal_by = \n| rank             = [[File:Prelate-Bishop.svg|35px]] [[Hierarchy of the Catholic Church|Bishop-Priest]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Thomas Bhalerao\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1933|02|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Sangamner]], [[Maharashtra]].\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2015|02|13|1933|02|01|df=y}}\n| death_place      = St. Luke\